{"title_page": "Walter Hungerb\u00fchler", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox football official\n| name                = Walter Hungerb\u00fchler\n| image               = Walter Hungerb\u00fchler (1975).jpg\n| caption             = Hungerb\u00fchler in 1975\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1930|8|9|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[St. Gallen]], Switzerland\n| death_date          = {{Death date and age|2012|3|27|1930|8|9|df=y}}\n| death_place         = St. Gallen, Switzerland\n| otheroccupation     =\n| years1              = 1969\u20131978\n| league1             = [[Swiss Super League]]\n| role1               = Referee\n| internationalyears1 = 1972\u20131978\n| confederation1      = [[FIFA International Referees List|FIFA listed]]\n| internationalrole1  = Referee\n}}\n\n'''Walter Hungerb\u00fchler''' (9 August 1930 \u2013 27 March 2012) was a Swiss [[Association football|football]] referee.\n\n==Refereeing career==\nIn 1969, Hungerb\u00fchler became a referee in the [[Swiss Super League]], the top flight of football in Switzerland. In 1972, he was appointed as a [[FIFA International Referees List|FIFA referee]].\n\nIn 1976, Hungerb\u00fchler was appointed as a referee for [[UEFA Euro 1976]], where he officiated the [[UEFA Euro 1976 final tournament#Third place play-off|third place play-off]] between the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] and [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldfootball.net/report/em-1976-in-jugoslawien-3-platz-jugoslawien-niederlande/ |title=Yugoslavia - Netherlands 2:3 (EURO 1976 Yugoslavia, 3td place) |website=worldfootball.net |publisher=HEIM:SPIEL |access-date=3 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nHungerb\u00fchler retired from refereeing in 1978.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.worldfootball.net/referee_summary/walter-hungerbuehler/ Profile] at worldfootball.net\n\n{{UEFA Euro 1976 referees}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hungerbuhler, Walter}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from St. Gallen (city)]]\n[[Category:Swiss football referees]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1976 referees]]\n\n\n{{Switzerland-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox football official\n| name                = Walter Hungerb\u00fchler\n| image               = Walter Hungerb\u00fchler (1975).jpg\n| caption             = Hungerb\u00fchler in 1975\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1930|8|9|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[St. Gallen]], Switzerland\n| death_date          = {{Death date and age|2012|3|27|1930|8|9|df=y}}\n| death_place         = St. Gallen, Switzerland\n| otheroccupation     =\n| 1976s1              = 1969\u20131978\n| league1             = [[Swiss Super League]]\n| role1               = Referee\n| internationalyears1 = 1972\u20131978\n| confederation1      = [[FIFA International Referees List|FIFA listed]]\n| internationalrole1  = Referee\n}}\n'''Walter Hungerb\u00fchler''' (9 August 1930 \u2013 27 March 2012) was a Swiss [[Association football|football]] referee.\n\n==Refereeing career==\nIn 1969, Hungerb\u00fchler became a referee in the [[Swiss Super League]], the top flight of football in Switzerland. In 1972, he was appointed as a [[FIFA International Referees List|FIFA referee]].\n\nIn 1976, Hungerb\u00fchler was appointed as a referee for [[UEFA Euro 1976]], where he officiated the [[UEFA Euro 1976 final tournament#Third place play-off|third place play-off]] between the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] and [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldfootball.net/report/em-1976-in-jugoslawien-3-platz-jugoslawien-niederlande/ |title=Yugoslavia - Netherlands 2:3 (EURO 1976 Yugoslavia, 3td place) |website=worldfootball.net |publisher=HEIM:SPIEL |access-date=3 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nHungerb\u00fchler retired from refereeing in 1978.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.worldfootball.net/referee_summary/walter-hungerbuehler/ Profile] at worldfootball.net\n\n{{UEFA Euro 1976 referees}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hungerbuhler, Walter}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from St. Gallen (city)]]\n[[Category:Swiss football referees]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1976 referees]]\n\n\n{{Switzerland-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update infobox", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walter_Hungerb%C3%BChler"}
{"title_page": "Battle of Tadcaster", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Battle of Tadcaster\n| partof      = the [[First English Civil War]]\n| image       =\n| caption     =\n| date        = 7 December 1642\n| place       = [[Tadcaster]], Yorkshire\n| result      = Royalist victory\n| coordinates = \n| map_type    = \n| map_size    = \n| map_caption = \n| map_label   = \n| combatant1  = [[Cavalier|Royalists]]\n| combatant2  = [[Roundhead|Parliamentarians]]\n| commander1  = [[William Cavendish, 1st Duke of Newcastle|Earl of Newcastle]]\n| commander2  = [[Ferdinando Fairfax, 2nd Lord Fairfax of Cameron|Ferdinando Fairfax, Lord Fairfax]]\n| strength1   = {{circa|4,000}}\n| strength2   = 900\u20131,500\n| casualties1 = \n| casualties2 = \n| campaignbox = {{Campaignbox First English Civil War|state=collapsed}}\n}}\nThe '''Battle of Tadcaster''' took place during the [[First English Civil War]] on 7 December 1642, when a [[Cavalier|Royalist]] force attacked the [[Roundhead|Parliamentarian]] garrison of [[Tadcaster]], Yorkshire, which was held by between 900 and 1,500 soldiers under the command of [[Ferdinando Fairfax, 2nd Lord Fairfax of Cameron|Ferdinando Fairfax, Lord Fairfax]]. Newcastle marched out of York on 6 December, and split his force of 6,000 into two; he took 4,000 infantry down the main York\u2013Tadcaster road to attack the town from the east, while sending a deputy, the [[Mountjoy Blount, 1st Earl of Newport|Earl of Newport]], with a further 1,500 to circle around and trap the Parliamentarians by attacking from the north-west.\n\nNewcastle's infantry engaged the town on the morning of 7 December, but after some initial minor incursions, the battle settled into an exchange of [[musket]] fire. Newport's detachment never joined the battle. Fairfax was nevertheless forced to retreat overnight, as he was running short of gunpowder, and Newcastle occupied the town the following day. He subsequently garrisoned a number of nearby towns, and cut Fairfax off from the [[West Riding of Yorkshire]].\n\n==Background==\nIn December 1642, the [[First English Civil War]] had been running for four months, since [[Charles I of England|King Charles I]] had raised his banner in Nottingham and declared the Earl of Essex, and by extension [[Parliament of England|Parliament]], traitors.{{sfn|Bennett|2005|p=xii}} That action had been the culmination of religious, fiscal and legislative tensions going back over fifty years.{{sfn|Bleiberg|Soergel|2005|p=344\u2013348}}\n\n===State of the war in Yorkshire===\nEven before the formal start of the war, [[Yorkshire]] became a key area in the conflict. After King Charles I attempted to [[Five Members|arrest five members of parliament]] in January 1642, members of the [[gentry]] started openly taking sides and preparing for battle. [[Sir John Hotham, 1st Baronet|Sir John Hotham]] seized [[Kingston-upon-Hull|Hull]] for parliament the same month, and after fleeing London, the King established himself at [[York]] in March. The King twice attempted to take Hull in 1642 without success. Although Charles subsequently returned south, his wife, [[Henrietta Maria of France|Henrietta Maria]] (formally known as Queen Mary) had travelled to the [[Low Countries]] to acquire weapons and the [[William Cavendish, 1st Duke of Newcastle|Earl of Newcastle]] was charged with ensuring her safe travel through the northeast when she returned.{{sfn|Cooke|2006|pp=128\u2013133}} On the other side, [[Ferdinando Fairfax, 2nd Lord Fairfax of Cameron|Ferdinando Fairfax, Lord Fairfax]], was appointed as the commander of parliament's forces in Yorkshire.<ref>{{cite odnb |id=9081 |title=Fairfax, Ferdinando, second Lord Fairfax of Cameron |last=Hopper |first=Andrew J. |year=2008 |origyear=2004}}</ref>\n\n==Prelude==\nIn response to requests from Yorkshire Royalists, Newcastle advanced into Yorkshire with around 8,000 men, defeating the Parliamentarians at the [[Battle of Piercebridge]], and established himself in [[York]] on 3 December.{{sfn|Hulse|2011}} Lord Fairfax had himself been leading a Parliamentarian army towards York, but when he received news of the Royalist victory at Piercebridge he stopped at [[Tadcaster]], around {{convert|10|miles}} south-west of York. Newcastle's advance had split the Parliamentarian forces, and shifted the balance of power in the county. He soon took the opportunity to march on Tadcaster and attempt to [[Defeat in detail|defeat the Parliamentarians in detail]].{{sfn|Cooke|2006|p=133}}\n\n==Battle==\n[[File:William Cavendish, First Duke of Newcastle.jpg|thumb|right|The [[William Cavendish, 1st Duke of Newcastle|Earl of Newcastle]] led the Royalist force which captured Tadcaster.]]\nOn 6 December,{{sfn|Manganiello|2004|p=524}} Newcastle approached Tadcaster with two forces totalling around 6,000; he commanded the larger one himself, heading directly down the road from York to attack Tadcaster from the east. At the same time, he sent the [[Mountjoy Blount, 1st Earl of Newport|Earl of Newport]] with 1,500 men to circle around through [[Wetherby]] and attack Fairfax from the north-west. In the mean time, Fairfax had been preparing Tadcaster's defences: he built a [[redoubt]] atop a hill by the [[River Wharfe]] overlooking the York road, and drew in additional troops, gathering between 900 and 1,500 soldiers in the town.{{sfn|Cooke|2006|pp=136\u2013137}}{{sfn|Manganiello|2004|p=524}} In the face of the large Royalist army, Fairfax and his commanders held a [[council of war]], and decided to withdraw from the town the next morning, 7 December.{{sfn|Cooke|2006|p=137}} However, by the time they had gathered their men to leave, fighting had broken out on the edge of town. The Royalist infantry was attacking the east side of town, still defended by the Parliamentarian rearguard. The attack meant that retreat was no longer possible, and Fairfax sent his men back to join the town's defence.{{sfn|Cooke|2006|p=137}}\n\nThe initial Royalist attack was thwarted, but more of Newcastle's infantry managed to break into the town and capture a house near the redoubt, isolating it from the bulk of the defensive garrison. A Parliamentarian counter-attack reclaimed the house, drove the Royalists back out of town, and set fire to some of the houses on the edge of the town to prevent the attackers occupying them. Both sides settled into their positions, and exchanged [[musket]] fire for the rest of the day. The planned second prong of Newcastle's attack, under Newport's command, never arrived. The historian David Cooke suggests that it was most likely due to his artillery slowing him down on the poor winter roads. The 18th-century historian [[Francis Drake (antiquary)|Francis Drake]] claimed that one of the Parliamentarian officers, [[John Hotham, the younger|Captain John Hotham]], forged a letter to Newport, purporting to be from Newcastle, ordering him to halt.{{sfn|Cooke|2006|p=137}}\n\nThe Parliamentarians, despite holding a defensible position, were running short of gunpowder, and decided to withdraw from the town overnight. They split their force; Fairfax took his men to [[Selby]], and Hotham to [[Cawood]].{{sfn|Cooke|2006|p=137}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nAfter the town had been vacated by the Parliamentarians, Newcastle advanced his forces into it on the morning of 8 December, subsequently garrisoning [[Pontefract Castle]] and a number of other towns in the area, cutting Fairfax off from the [[West Riding of Yorkshire]].{{sfn|Cooke|2006|p=137}} He sent [[Sir William Savile, 3rd Baronet|Sir William Savile]] with a detachment of 2,000 men to secure the [[West Riding of Yorkshire|West Riding]] towns of Leeds, [[Wakefield]] and [[Bradford]].{{sfn|Firth|Cavendish|1886|p=32}} Savile took Leeds and Wakefield without a fight, but had to split off a portion of his force to attempt to capture Bradford on 18 December, where he was repelled.{{sfn|Lamplough|2019|p=118}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hNSEAgAAQBAJ |title=The Civil Wars Experienced: Britain and Ireland, 1638\u20131661 |last=Bennett |first=Martyn |year=2005 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |location=London |isbn=0-203-98180-4 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/artshumanitiesth00edwa |chapter=The English Civil Wars |title=Arts and Humanities Through the Eras |volume=5: The Age of the Baroque and Enlightenment 1600\u20131800 |editor1-last=Bleiberg |editor1-first=Edward |editor2-last=Soergel |editor2-first=Philip |collaboration=true |publisher=[[Gale (publisher)|Gale]] |year=2005 |location=Detroit |isbn=978-0-787-65697-3 |ref=harv |chapter-url-access=registration }}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last=Cooke |first=David |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ehvOAwAAQBAJ |title=Battlefield Yorkshire: From the Romans to the English Civil Wars |location=Barnsley |publisher=Pen & Sword Military |year=2006 |isbn=1-84415-424-6}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hl4JAAAAQAAJ |title=The Life of William Cavendish, Duke of Newcastle |last1=Firth |first1=C. H. |last2=Cavendish |first2=Margaret |author2-link=Margaret Cavendish, Duchess of Newcastle-upon-Tyne |year=1886 |location=London |publisher=John C. Nimmo |oclc=502532864 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite odnb |id=4946 |title=Cavendish, William, first duke of Newcastle upon Tyne |last=Hulse |first=Lynn |origyear=2004 |year=2011 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last=Lamplough |first=Edward |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=167EDwAAQBAJ |title=Yorkshire Battles |publisher=Good Press |year=2019 |origyear=1891}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=an-eXXA3DBMC |title=The Concise Encyclopedia of the Revolutions and Wars of England, Scotland, and Ireland, 1639\u20131660 |last=Manganiello |first=Stephen C. |year=2004 |publisher=The Scarecrow Press |location=[[Lanham, Maryland]] |isbn=0-8108-5100-8 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{coord missing|England}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tadcaster, Battle Of}}\n[[Category:1642 in England]]\n[[Category:17th century in Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Battles of the English Civil Wars]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1642]]\n[[Category:First English Civil War]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Battle of Tadcaster\n| partof      = the [[First English Civil War]]\n| image       =\n| caption     =\n| date        = 7 December 1642\n| place       = [[Tadcaster]], Yorkshire\n| result      = Royalist victory\n| coordinates = \n| map_type    = \n| map_size    = \n| map_caption = \n| map_label   = \n| combatant1  = [[Cavalier|Royalists]]\n| combatant2  = [[Roundhead|Parliamentarians]]\n| commander1  = [[William Cavendish, 1st Duke of Newcastle|Earl of Newcastle]]\n| commander2  = [[Ferdinando Fairfax, 2nd Lord Fairfax of Cameron|Ferdinando Fairfax, Lord Fairfax]]\n| strength1   = {{circa|4,000}}\n| strength2   = 900\u20131,500\n| casualties1 = \n| casualties2 = \n| campaignbox = {{Campaignbox First English Civil War|state=collapsed}}\n}}\nThe '''Battle of Tadcaster''' took place during the [[First English Civil War]] on 7 December 1642, when a [[Cavalier|Royalist]] force attacked the [[Roundhead|Parliamentarian]] garrison of [[Tadcaster]], Yorkshire, which was held by between 900 and 1,500 soldiers under the command of [[Ferdinando Fairfax, 2nd Lord Fairfax of Cameron|Ferdinando Fairfax, Lord Fairfax]]. Newcastle marched out of York on 6 December, and split his force of 6,000 into two; he took 4,000 infantry down the main York\u2013Tadcaster road to attack the town from the east, while sending a deputy, the [[Mountjoy Blount, 1st Earl of Newport|Earl of Newport]], with a further 1,500 to circle around and trap the Parliamentarians by attacking from the north-west.\n\nNewcastle's infantry engaged the town on the morning of 7 December, but after some initial minor incursions, the battle settled into an exchange of [[musket]] fire. Newport's detachment never joined the battle. Fairfax was nevertheless forced to retreat overnight, as he was running short of gunpowder, and Newcastle occupied the town the following day. He subsequently garrisoned a number of nearby towns, and cut Fairfax off from the [[West Riding of Yorkshire]].\n\n==Background==\nIn December 1642, the [[First English Civil War]] had been running for four months, since [[Charles I of England|King Charles I]] had raised his banner in Nottingham and declared the Earl of Essex, and by extension [[Parliament of England|Parliament]], traitors.{{sfn|Bennett|2005|p=xii}} That action had been the culmination of religious, fiscal and legislative tensions going back over fifty years.{{sfn|Bleiberg|Soergel|2005|p=344\u2013348}}\n\n===State of the war in Yorkshire===\nEven before the formal start of the war, [[Yorkshire]] became a key area in the conflict. After King Charles I attempted to [[Five Members|arrest five members of parliament]] in January 1642, members of the [[gentry]] started openly taking sides and preparing for battle. [[Sir John Hotham, 1st Baronet|Sir John Hotham]] seized [[Kingston-upon-Hull|Hull]] for parliament the same month, and after fleeing London, the King established himself at [[York]] in March. The King twice attempted to take Hull in 1642 without success. Although Charles subsequently returned south, his wife, [[Henrietta Maria of France|Henrietta Maria]] (formally known as Queen Mary) had travelled to the [[Low Countries]] to acquire weapons and the [[William Cavendish, 1st Duke of Newcastle|Earl of Newcastle]] was charged with ensuring her safe travel through the northeast when she returned.{{sfn|Cooke|2006|pp=128\u2013133}} On the other side, [[Ferdinando Fairfax, 2nd Lord Fairfax of Cameron|Ferdinando Fairfax, Lord Fairfax]], was appointed as the commander of parliament's forces in Yorkshire.<ref>{{cite odnb |id=9081 |title=Fairfax, Ferdinando, second Lord Fairfax of Cameron |last=Hopper |first=Andrew J. |year=2008 |origyear=2004}}</ref>\n\n==Prelude==\nIn response to requests from Yorkshire Royalists, Newcastle advanced into Yorkshire with around 8,000 men, defeating the Parliamentarians at the [[Battle of Piercebridge]], and established himself in [[York]] on 3 December.{{sfn|Hulse|2011}} Lord Fairfax had himself been leading a Parliamentarian army towards York, but when he received news of the Royalist victory at Piercebridge he stopped at [[Tadcaster]], around {{convert|10|miles}} south-west of York. Newcastle's advance had split the Parliamentarian forces, and shifted the balance of power in the county. He soon took the opportunity to march on Tadcaster and attempt to [[Defeat in detail|defeat the Parliamentarians in detail]].{{sfn|Cooke|2006|p=133}}\n\n==Battle==\n[[File:William Cavendish, First Duke of Newcastle.jpg|thumb|right|The [[William Cavendish, 1st Duke of Newcastle|Earl of Newcastle]] led the Royalist force which captured Tadcaster.]]\nOn 7 December,{{sfn|Manganiello|2004|p=524}} Newcastle approached Tadcaster with two forces totalling around 6,000; he commanded the larger one himself, heading directly down the road from York to attack Tadcaster from the east. At the same time, he sent the [[Mountjoy Blount, 1st Earl of Newport|Earl of Newport]] with 1,500 men to circle around through [[Wetherby]] and attack Fairfax from the north-west. In the mean time, Fairfax had been preparing Tadcaster's defences: he built a [[redoubt]] atop a hill by the [[River Wharfe]] overlooking the York road, and drew in additional troops, gathering between 900 and 1,500 soldiers in the town.{{sfn|Cooke|2006|pp=136\u2013137}}{{sfn|Manganiello|2004|p=524}} In the face of the large Royalist army, Fairfax and his commanders held a [[council of war]], and decided to withdraw from the town. However, by the time they had gathered their men to leave, fighting had broken out on the edge of town. The Royalist infantry was attacking the east side of town, still defended by the Parliamentarian rearguard. The attack meant that retreat was no longer possible, and Fairfax sent his men back to join the town's defence.{{sfn|Cooke|2006|p=137}}\n\nThe initial Royalist attack was thwarted, but more of Newcastle's infantry managed to break into the town and capture a house near the redoubt, isolating it from the bulk of the defensive garrison. A Parliamentarian counter-attack reclaimed the house, drove the Royalists back out of town, and set fire to some of the houses on the edge of the town to prevent the attackers occupying them. Both sides settled into their positions, and exchanged [[musket]] fire for the rest of the day. The planned second prong of Newcastle's attack, under Newport's command, never arrived. The historian David Cooke suggests that it was most likely due to his artillery slowing him down on the poor winter roads. The 18th-century historian [[Francis Drake (antiquary)|Francis Drake]] claimed that one of the Parliamentarian officers, [[John Hotham, the younger|Captain John Hotham]], forged a letter to Newport, purporting to be from Newcastle, ordering him to halt.{{sfn|Cooke|2006|p=137}}\n\nThe Parliamentarians, despite holding a defensible position, were running short of gunpowder, and decided to withdraw from the town overnight. They split their force; Fairfax took his men to [[Selby]], and Hotham to [[Cawood]].{{sfn|Cooke|2006|p=137}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nAfter the town had been vacated by the Parliamentarians, Newcastle advanced his forces into it on the morning of 8 December, subsequently garrisoning [[Pontefract Castle]] and a number of other towns in the area, cutting Fairfax off from the [[West Riding of Yorkshire]].{{sfn|Cooke|2006|p=137}} He sent [[Sir William Savile, 3rd Baronet|Sir William Savile]] with a detachment of 2,000 men to secure the [[West Riding of Yorkshire|West Riding]] towns of Leeds, [[Wakefield]] and [[Bradford]].{{sfn|Firth|Cavendish|1886|p=32}} Savile took Leeds and Wakefield without a fight, but had to split off a portion of his force to attempt to capture Bradford on 18 December, where he was repelled.{{sfn|Lamplough|2019|p=118}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hNSEAgAAQBAJ |title=The Civil Wars Experienced: Britain and Ireland, 1638\u20131661 |last=Bennett |first=Martyn |year=2005 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |location=London |isbn=0-203-98180-4 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/artshumanitiesth00edwa |chapter=The English Civil Wars |title=Arts and Humanities Through the Eras |volume=5: The Age of the Baroque and Enlightenment 1600\u20131800 |editor1-last=Bleiberg |editor1-first=Edward |editor2-last=Soergel |editor2-first=Philip |collaboration=true |publisher=[[Gale (publisher)|Gale]] |year=2005 |location=Detroit |isbn=978-0-787-65697-3 |ref=harv |chapter-url-access=registration }}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last=Cooke |first=David |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ehvOAwAAQBAJ |title=Battlefield Yorkshire: From the Romans to the English Civil Wars |location=Barnsley |publisher=Pen & Sword Military |year=2006 |isbn=1-84415-424-6}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hl4JAAAAQAAJ |title=The Life of William Cavendish, Duke of Newcastle |last1=Firth |first1=C. H. |last2=Cavendish |first2=Margaret |author2-link=Margaret Cavendish, Duchess of Newcastle-upon-Tyne |year=1886 |location=London |publisher=John C. Nimmo |oclc=502532864 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite odnb |id=4946 |title=Cavendish, William, first duke of Newcastle upon Tyne |last=Hulse |first=Lynn |origyear=2004 |year=2011 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last=Lamplough |first=Edward |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=167EDwAAQBAJ |title=Yorkshire Battles |publisher=Good Press |year=2019 |origyear=1891}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=an-eXXA3DBMC |title=The Concise Encyclopedia of the Revolutions and Wars of England, Scotland, and Ireland, 1639\u20131660 |last=Manganiello |first=Stephen C. |year=2004 |publisher=The Scarecrow Press |location=[[Lanham, Maryland]] |isbn=0-8108-5100-8 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{coord missing|England}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tadcaster, Battle Of}}\n[[Category:1642 in England]]\n[[Category:17th century in Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Battles of the English Civil Wars]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1642]]\n[[Category:First English Civil War]]\n", "name_user": "Harrias", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBattle:clarify", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Tadcaster"}
{"title_page": "List of tallest buildings in Rotterdam", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}}\n[[File:Erasmusbrug seen from Euromast.jpg|thumb|right|300px|[[Kop van Zuid]], viewed from the [[Euromast]]]]\n\n[[File:Skyline Rotterdam from Schiebroek.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The skyline of Rotterdam, viewed from [[Schiebroek]]]]\n\n[[Rotterdam]], the second most populous city in the [[Netherlands]], is home to 352 completed high-rises,<ref name=\"emporis1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.emporis.com/city/100760/rotterdam-netherlands/type/3/18 |title=Rotterdam |publisher=Emporis |date= |accessdate=2017-02-24}}</ref> 36 of which are higher than {{convert|100|m|ft}}. The tallest building in Rotterdam is the [[Maastoren]], which rises {{convert|165|m|ft}}.<ref name=maastoren>{{Ctbuh|5559|Maastoren}}</ref> The 44 storey skyscraper also stands as the highest building in the [[Netherlands]] and the [[Benelux]].<ref name=maastoren/>\n\nRotterdam is well known as the high-rise city of the [[Netherlands]]. The city is therefore often called \"[[Manhattan]] at the [[Meuse]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.holland.com/global/tourism/architecture-rotterdam.htm# |title=Architecture Rotterdam - Tourism in the Netherlands |website=Holland.com |date=2017-02-09 |accessdate=2017-02-24}}</ref> because a large amount of skyscrapers is standing close to the river [[Meuse]], especially at [[Kop van Zuid]]. Rotterdam has a rich history in high-rises, dating back to 1897 with the completion of \"Het [[Witte Huis]]\". This office building was at that time the tallest skyscraper in Europe.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jan van Helleman |url=http://www.top010.nl/html/het_witte_huis.htm |title=Het Witte Huis Rotterdam - Nieuwbouw Architectuur Rotterdam |website=Top010.nl |date=2016-12-23 |accessdate=2017-02-24}}</ref> Rotterdam is famous because of its characteristic skyline, and its world-wide reputation for innovative architecture.\nThe city is standing in the European SkylineTop together with [[Frankfurt]], [[Milan]], [[London]], [[Madrid]], [[Paris]], [[Warsaw]] and [[Moscow]]. Over 30 new high-rise projects are being developed at the moment.<ref name=\"emporis1\"/>\n\n==Buildings==\nThe listed heights are the constructive heights of the building. Architectonic and functional masts are only shown here for comparison.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!  \n! Name\n! Height<br />{{nowrap|[[Metre|m]] ([[Foot (unit)|ft]])}}\n! Finished\n! Storeys\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Image\n|- \n|1\n|[[Maastoren]]\n|{{convert|182.25|m|ft|abbr=values}}&nbsp;{{small|(Antenna)}}\n{{convert|164.75|m|ft|abbr=values}}&nbsp;{{small|(Roof)}}\n|2009\n|44\n|[[File:Rotterdam toren maastoren.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n|2\n|[[New Orleans (Rotterdam)|New Orleans]]\n|{{convert|163.00|m|ft|abbr=values}}&nbsp;{{small|(Antenna)}}\n{{convert|158.36|m|ft|abbr=values}}&nbsp;{{small|(Roof)}}\n|2010\n|45\n| [[File:Rotterdam toren new orleans.jpg|100px]]\n|- \n|3\n|[[Gebouw Delftse Poort]]\n|{{convert|164.00|m|ft|abbr=values}}&nbsp;{{small|(Antenna)}}\n{{convert|151.35|m|ft|abbr=values}}&nbsp;{{small|(Roof)}}\n|1992\n|41\n| [[File:Rotterdam NationaleNederlanden.jpg|100px]] \n|-\n|4\n|[[De Rotterdam]]\n|{{convert|149.10|m|ft|abbr=values}}\n|2013\n|44\n|[[File:DeRotterdam.JPG|100px]]\n|- \n|5\n|[[Montevideo (Rotterdam)|Montevideo]]\n|{{convert|152.32|m|ft|abbr=values}}&nbsp;{{small|(Antenna)}}\n{{convert|139.50|m|ft|abbr=values}}&nbsp;{{small|(Roof)}}\n|2005\n|43\n| [[File:Rotterdam montevideotoren.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n|6\n|[[Millennium Tower (Rotterdam)|Millennium Tower]]\n|{{convert|149.00|m|ft|abbr=values}}&nbsp;{{small|(Antenna)}}\n{{convert|131.85|m|ft|abbr=values}}&nbsp;{{small|(Roof)}}\n|2000\n|34\n| [[File:Rotterdam, Millenniumtoren.jpg|100px]]\n|- \n|7\n|[[First Rotterdam|FIRST Rotterdam]]\n|{{convert|130.00|m|ft|abbr=values}}\n|2015\n|44\n|\n|-\n|8\n|[[The Red Apple]]\n|{{convert|127.10|m|ft|abbr=values}}\n|2009\n|40\n|[[File:Rotterdam toren red apple.jpg|100px]]\n|-\