n Helleman |url=http://www.nieuws.top010.nl/woontoren-kruiskade-rotterdam |title=De Metropool woontoren Kruiskade Rotterdam |website=Nieuws.top010.nl |date= |accessdate=2017-02-24}}</ref>\n|{{convert|70|m|ft|abbr=values}}\n|2020\n|Approved\n|-\n|12\n|Rotta Nova <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.overhd.nl/rottanova |title=Rottanova |website=Overhd.nl |date= |accessdate=2017-02-24}}</ref>\n|{{convert|70|m|ft|abbr=values}}\n|2020\n|On hold\n|-\n|13\n|Bright <ref>http://www.cobouw.nl/bouwbericht/1646121-bright-nieuwe-blikvanger-voor-hart-oude-rotterdam</ref>\n|{{convert|70|m|ft|abbr=values}}\n|2019\n|Approved\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of tallest buildings in the Netherlands]]\n* [[List of tallest structures in the Netherlands]]\n* [[List of tallest buildings in Amsterdam]]\n* [[List of tallest buildings in Haaglanden]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of buildings and structures in the Netherlands|Tallest in Rotterdam]]\n[[Category:Lists of tallest buildings in the Netherlands|Rotterdam]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Rotterdam|*]]\n[[Category:Skyscrapers in the Netherlands|*]]\n", "name_user": "Slashslasher", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added a picture of Up;Town", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_tallest_buildings_in_Rotterdam"}
{"title_page": "Splint armour", "text_new": "[[Image:Guenther von schwarzburg.jpg|thumb|left|German King [[G\u00fcnther von Schwarzburg]] with splinted bracers and greaves]]\n\n'''Splint armour''', (also '''splinted armour''') is armour consisting of strips of metal (\"splints\") attached to a cloth or leather backing. It is most commonly found as limb armour such as [[greave]]s or [[vambraces]].\n\n==Description==\nLimb armor consisting of strips of metal (\"splints\") are attached to a fabric (cloth or leather) backing (\"foundation\"). The splints are narrow metal strips arranged longitudinally, pierced for riveting or sewing to the foundation. Splint armour is most commonly found as [[greave]]s or [[vambraces]]. \n\nIt first appears in a [[Scythia]]n grave from the 4th century BC<ref name=\"Oakeshott_p67\">Oakeshott: ''The Archaeology of Weapons'', 67</ref>\nthen in the Swedish [[Migration Era]];<ref name=\"Oakeshott_p124\">Oakeshott: ''The Archaeology of Weapons'', 124</ref> and again in the 14th century as part of [[transitional armour]], where it was also used to form [[cuisses]] and [[rerebrace]]s.\n\n==Splint mail/splinted mail==\n[[File:Return of the Samurai 38.JPG|thumb|An antique Japanese ([[samurai]]) suit of armor, showing splinted vambraces ]]\n\nWhile a few complete suits of armour have been found made from splints of wood, leather, or bone, the Victorian neologism \"splinted mail\" usually refers to the limb protections of [[Crusades|crusader]] [[knights]]. Depictions typically show it on the limbs of a person wearing [[mail (armour)|mail]], [[scale armour]], a [[coat of plates]] or other [[plate armour|plate]] harness. \n\nKnights in [[effigy]] are depicted with leg protection of a matrix of disks with a diameter equal to the splints. This style appears to depict [[sabaton]]s and splints on greaves, or may represent padded armour underneath splints, or the rivets on [[brigandine]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Coat of plates]]\n*[[Mirror Armor]]\n*[[Scale armour]]\n*[[Plated mail]]\n*[[Gambeson]]\n*[[Brigandine]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite book | last=Oakeshott|first=R. Ewart|authorlink = Ewart Oakeshott|title=The Archaeology of Weapons|year=1996|origyear=1960|edition=Dover reprint|publisher=Dover Publications|isbn=0-486-29288-6}}\n\n{{Types of armour}}\n\n[[Category:Body armor]]\n[[Category:Medieval armour]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Guenther von schwarzburg.jpg|thumb|left|German King [[G\u00fcnther von Schwarzburg]] with splinted bracers and greaves]]\n\n'''Splint armour''', (also '''splinted armour''') is armour consisting of strips of metal (\"splints\") attached to a cloth or leather backing. It is most commonly found as limb armour such as [[greave]]s or [[vambraces]].\n\n==Description==\nLimb armor consisting of strips of metal (\"splints\") are attached to a fabric (cloth or leather) backing (\"foundation\"). The splints are narrow metal strips arranged longitudinally, pierced for riveting or sewing to the foundation. Splint armour is most commonly found as [[greave]]s or [[vambraces]]. \n\nIt first appears in a [[Scythia]]n grave from the 4th century BC<ref name=\"Oakeshott_p67\">Oakeshott: ''The Archaeology of Weapons'', 67</ref>\nthen in the Swedish [[Migration Era]];<ref name=\"Oakeshott_p124\">Oakeshott: ''The Archaeology of Weapons'', 124</ref> and again in the 14th century as part of [[transitional armour]], where it was also used to form [[cuisses]] and [[rerebrace]]s.\n\n===Splint mail/splinted mail===\n[[File:Return of the Samurai 38.JPG|thumb|An antique Japanese ([[samurai]]) suit of armor, showing splinted vambraces ]]\n\nWhile a few complete suits of armour have been found made from splints of wood, leather, or bone, the Victorian neologism \"splinted mail\" usually refers to the limb protections of [[Crusades|crusader]] [[knights]]. Depictions typically show it on the limbs of a person wearing [[mail (armour)|mail]], [[scale armour]], a [[coat of plates]] or other [[plate armour|plate]] harness. \n\nKnights in [[effigy]] are depicted with leg protection of a matrix of disks with a diameter equal to the splints. This style appears to depict [[sabaton]]s and splints on greaves, or may represent padded armour underneath splints, or the rivets on [[brigandine]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Coat of plates]]\n*[[Mirror Armor]]\n*[[Scale armour]]\n*[[Plated mail]]\n*[[Gambeson]]\n*[[Brigandine]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite book | last=Oakeshott|first=R. Ewart|authorlink = Ewart Oakeshott|title=The Archaeology of Weapons|year=1996|origyear=1960|edition=Dover reprint|publisher=Dover Publications|isbn=0-486-29288-6}}\n\n{{Types of armour}}\n\n[[Category:Body armor]]\n[[Category:Medieval armour]]\n", "name_user": "Jmackaerospace", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Splint_armour"}
{"title_page": "Danh V\u014d", "text_new": "[[File:Danh Vo.jpg|thumb|300px|Danh V\u014d (2018)]]\n'''Danh V\u014d''' (born 1975)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artfacts.net/en/artist/danh-vo-51015/profile.html |title=Danh Vo - Biography |publisher=Artfacts.net |date=2013-08-18 |accessdate=2013-08-23}}</ref> is a [[Danes|Danish]] performance art inspired conceptual artist.<ref name=\"artic1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.artic.edu/exhibition/danh-vo-we-people-detail-2010-2013 |title=Danh Vo: We The People (detail), 2010\u20132013 |publisher=The Art Institute of Chicago |date= |accessdate=2013-08-23}}</ref> He lives and works in [[Berlin]], Germany and [[Mexico City]].<ref name=\"NewYorkerProfile\"/><ref name=\"articles.latimes.com\">David Ng (November 1, 2012), [http://articles.latimes.com/2012/nov/01/entertainment/la-et-cm-artist-danh-vo-hugo-boss-prize-guggenheim-20121101 Danh Vo wins 2012 Hugo Boss Prize from Guggenheim Foundation] ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''.</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nDanh V\u014d (pronounced ''yon voh'')<ref name=\"Awash in a Cultural Deluge\">[[Roberta Smith|Smith, Roberta]] (March 14, 2013). \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/15/arts/design/the-hugo-boss-prize-2012-danh-vo-works-at-the-guggenheim.html Awash in a Cultural Deluge]\". ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref> was born in [[B\u00e0 R\u1ecba]], Vietnam in August 1975.<ref name=\"NewYorkerProfile\">[[Calvin Tomkins|Tomkins, Calvin]]\n (January&nbsp;29, 2018). \"[https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2018/01/29/the-artist-questioning-authorship The Artist Questioning Authorship]\". ''[[The New Yorker]]''. newyorker.com. Retrieved 2018-02-10.</ref><ref>[http://www.guggenheim.org/new-york/exhibitions/past/exhibit/5488 The Hugo Boss Prize 2012: Danh Vo] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141206094400/http://www.guggenheim.org/new-york/exhibitions/past/exhibit/5488 |date=2014-12-06 }} [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]], New York.</ref> After the [[Communist Party of Vietnam|Communists]]' victory and the [[fall of Saigon]], the Vo family and 20,000 other South Vietnamese were brought in 1975 to the island of [[Ph\u00fa Qu\u1ed1c]].<ref name=\"Danh Vo: In Memory of Forgetting\">Daniel V\u00f6lzke (December 11, 2009), [http://www.db-artmag.com/en/57/feature/danh-vo-in-memory-of-forgetting/ Danh Vo: In Memory of Forgetting] ''DB ArtMag''.</ref> in 1979, when he was 4 years old, his family fled South Vietnam in a homemade boat and was rescued at sea by a freighter belonging to the Danish [[Maersk]] shipping company.<ref name=\"NewYorkerProfile\"/><ref>[http://www.renaissancesociety.org/site/Exhibitions/Intro.Danh-Vo.629.html Danh Vo: Uterus, September 23 \u2013 December 16, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004221059/http://www.renaissancesociety.org/site/Exhibitions/Intro.Danh-Vo.629.html |date=October 4, 2013 }} [[Renaissance Society]], Chicago.</ref> The family members settled in Denmark.<ref name=\"NewYorkerProfile\"/> Their assimilation into European culture and the events that led up to their flight from Vietnam are reflected in V\u014d's art, which juxtaposes the historical and the personal.<ref>Carol Vogel (November 1, 2012), [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/02/arts/design/danh-vo-wins-hugo-boss-prize.html Native of Vietnam Wins Hugo Boss Prize] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref> When Danh Vo and his family were registered by the Danish authorities, the family name Vo was placed last. His middle name, Trung, was recorded as his first name.\n\nV\u014d moved to Berlin in 2005, after finishing school at [[St\u00e4delschule]] in [[Frankfurt]], where he went after quitting painting at the [[Royal Danish Academy of Fine Arts]] in [[Copenhagen]].<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">Hilarie M. Sheets (September 20, 2012), [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/23/arts/design/danh-vos-we-the-people-project-in-chicago.html Lady Liberty, Inspiring Even in Pieces] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref> He had residencies at the Villa Aurora in [[Los Angeles]] (2006)<ref name=\"articles.latimes.com\"/> and at [[Kadist Art Foundation]] in [[Paris]] (2009).<ref>[http://kadist.org/en/programs/all/1354 Residencies: Danh Vo] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131118054606/http://www.kadist.org/en/programs/all/1354 |date=2013-11-18 }} Kadist Art Foundation, Paris.</ref> He lives in both Berlin and Mexico City.<ref name=\"NewYorkerProfile\"/>\n\n==Work==\n[[File:Installation view of We The People.JPG|300px|right|thumb|Installation view of \"We The People\", 2010-2013, at National Gallery of Denmark in 2013.]]\nVo's [[Installation art|installation]]<nowiki/>s, which are composed of documents, photos and appropriations of works of other artists, often address the issues of identity and belonging.<ref name=\"Danh Vo: In Memory of Forgetting\"/>\n \nThe conceptual work ''Vo Rosasco Rasmussen'' (2002\u2013) involves the artist's marriage to and immediate divorce from a growing list of important people in his life;<ref name=\"Danh Vo\">\"[https://www.guggenheim.org/artwork/artist/danh-vo Danh Vo]\". [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]], New York. guggenheim.org. Retrieved 2018-02-09.</ref> after each marriage, V\u014d retains the last name of his former spouse. His official name is now Trung Ky Danh Vo Rosaco Rasmussen.<ref>[http://www.smk.dk/en/visit-the-museum/exhibitions/past-exhibitions/2011/danh-vo/about-danh-vo/ Danh Vo: Hip Hip Hurra, 20 November 2010 - 20 March 2011] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203013610/http://www.smk.dk/en/visit-the-museum/exhibitions/past-exhibitions/2011/danh-vo/about-danh-vo/ |date=3 December 2013 }} Statens Museum for Kunst, Copenhagen.</ref> ''Oma Totem'' (2009), a stacked sculpture of his grandmother's welcome gifts from a relief program on her arrival in Germany in the 1980s, displays her television set, washing machine, and refrigerator (adorned with her own [[crucifix]]), among other items.<ref name=\"Danh Vo\"/>\n\nFor ''2.02.1861'' (2009\u2013), the artist asked his father Phung Vo to transcribe the last communication from the French Catholic [[Th\u00e9ophane V\u00e9nard|Saint Th\u00e9ophane V\u00e9nard]] to his own father before he was decapitated in 1861 in Vo's native Vietnam; although multiple copies of the transcribed letter exist (1200 as of 2017),<ref name=\"NewYorkerProfile\"/> the total number will remain undefined until Phung Vo's death.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/><ref>[http://www.guggenheim.org/new-york/collections/collection-online/artwork/28837 Danh Vo, ''2.2.1861'', (2009\u2013)] [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]], New York.</ref>\n\nIn ''Autoerotic Asphyxiation'' (2010), V\u014d presents documentary pictures of young Asian men taken by Joseph Carrier, an American anthropologist and counterinsurgency specialist who worked in Vietnam for the [[RAND Corporation]] from 1962 to 1973. While in Vietnam, Carrier privately documented the casual interactions he observed, intimate without necessarily being homoerotic, between local men; he produced a substantial photographic archive, which he subsequently bequeathed to Danh V\u014d.<ref>Holland Cotter (November 5, 2010), [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/05/arts/design/05galleries-copy2.html Danh Vo: Autoerotic Asphyxiation] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref>\n\nFor his project ''We the People'', created between 2010 and 2012, Vo enlisted a [[Shanghai]] fabricator to recast a life-size [[Statue of Liberty]] from 30 tons of [[copper]] sheets the width of just two pennies.<ref>Martha Schwendener (August 7, 2014), [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/08/arts/design/danh-vos-we-the-people-divided.html Two Parks, One Statue, Lots of Pieces Lying Around] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref> Rather than assemble the approximately 300 sections,<ref name=\"Awash in a Cultural Deluge\"/> the artist shipped the giant elements to some 15 sites around the world after they rolled off the production line in China.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/> From mid May to early December 2014 ''We the People'' was shown in [[New York City]] under the auspices of the [[Public Art Fund]],<ref>\"[https://www.publicartfund.org/view/exhibitions/6042_danh_vo_we_the_people Danh Vo: We The People&nbsp;&ndash; About the Exhibition]\". Public Art Fund. publicartfund.org. Retrieved 2018-02-09.</ref> with its assembly of parts shared between [[City Hall Park]] in [[Lower Manhattan]] and [[Brooklyn Bridge Park]] in the borough of [[Brooklyn]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/exhibition-in-new-york-gives-new-perspective-on-statue-of-liberty-1400208982|title=Exhibition in New York Gives New Perspective on Statue of Liberty|first=Kirthana|last=Ramisetti|date=May 16, 2014|type=preview only; subscription required |publisher=Wall Street Journal. wsj.com}}</ref><ref>Rosenberg, Karen (August&nbsp;7, 2014). \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/08/arts/design/danh-vos-we-the-people-divided.html Two Parks, One Statue, Lots of Pieces Lying Around: Danh Vo\u2019s \u2018We the People,\u2019 Divided]\". ''New York Times''. nytimes.com. Retrieved 2018-02-09.</ref> While the work was being installed in City Hall Park, a few of its pieces&nbsp;&ndash; replicas of the chain links found at the feet of the original Statue of Liberty&nbsp;&ndash; were stolen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.phaidon.com/agenda/art/articles/2014/may/20/danh-vo-artwork-stolen-in-new-york/|title=Danh Vo artwork stolen in New York |publisher=Phaidon |date=May 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\nFor a 2013 show at the [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]], Vo conceived a homage to the artist [[Martin Wong]]. The installation consists of nearly 4,000 frequently small artworks, artifacts and [[tchotchke]]<nowiki/>s that once belonged to Wong, crowded into a specially designed gallery lined with [[laminated]] [[plywood]] shelves. The show's title\u2014''I am you and you are too''\u2014appeared on Wong's business cards and stamps.<ref name=\"Awash in a Cultural Deluge\"/>\n\nAnother 2013 show at New York's [[Marian Goodman Gallery]] focused on the personal effects of the late U.S. Secretary of Defense [[Robert McNamara]], the architect of the [[Vietnam War]]. Looking to open up a dialogue about shared and private histories, V\u014d displayed or modified 14 items acquired at a [[Sotheby's]] auction\u2014including the pen used to the sign the [[Gulf of Tonkin incident|Gulf of Tonkin memo]] and a 1944 photograph by [[Ansel Adams]].<ref>Michael Slenske (March 2013), [http://www.wmagazine.com/fashion/2013/03/conceptual-artist-danh-vo-at-the-guggenheim-and-marian-goodman/ Don't Miss: Danh Vo at the Guggenheim and Marian Goodman] ''[[W (magazine)|W]]''.</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\nV\u014d won the 2012 [[Hugo Boss Prize]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.guggenheim.org/new-york/press-room/releases/5121-winnerhugobossprize2012 |title=Artist Danh Vo Wins Hugo Boss Prize 2012 |publisher=Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum |date=2012-11-01 |accessdate=2013-08-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130820005310/http://www.guggenheim.org/new-york/press-room/releases/5121-winnerhugobossprize2012 |archivedate=2013-08-20 }}</ref> the BlauOrange Kunstpreis of Berlin's [[Bundesverband der Deutschen Volksbanken und Raiffeisenbanken|Deutschen Volksbanken und Raiffeisenbanken]] in 2007, and was a nominee for the Preis der [[Nationalgalerie]] f\u00fcr junge Kunst in 2009.<ref name=\"mariangoodman.com\">[http://www.mariangoodman.com/artists/danh-v/ Danh Vo] [[Marian Goodman Gallery]], New York/Paris.</ref>\n\n==Exhibitions==\nV\u014d had his first solo exhibition in 2005, at the Galerie Klosterfelde in Berlin.<ref>[http://cgi.klosterfelde.de/user-cgi-bin/exhibitions/?s1=03-previous&s2=2005 Danh Vo, November 19 - December 23, 2005] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004215516/http://cgi.klosterfelde.de/user-cgi-bin/exhibitions/?s1=03-previous&s2=2005 |date=October 4, 2013 }} Galerie Klosterfelde, Berlin.</ref>\n\nHe participated in the [[Venice Biennale]] in 2013.<ref name=\"mariangoodman.com\"/> His work has been exhibited at the [[Walker Art Center]] in [[Minneapolis]];<ref>{{cite web|last=Ryan |first=Bartholomew |url=http://www.walkerart.org/magazine/2012/tombstone-for-phung-vo |title=Tombstone for Ph\u00f9ng Vo \u2014 Magazine \u2014 Walker Art Center |publisher=Walkerart.org |date=2012-01-04 |accessdate=2013-08-23}}</ref> the [[Art Institute of Chicago]];<ref name=\"artic1\" /> the [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]] in New York; and the [[Mus\u00e9e d'art moderne de la Ville de Paris]], [[Kunsthaus Bregenz]], [[Austria]], the [[Kunsthalle Mainz]], [[Germany]],<ref>[http://www.kunsthalle-mainz.de/en/exhibitions/past/thomas-schuette-brdanh-vo/ Reich ohne Mitte, Thomas Schuette und Danh Vo, August 5 - October 6, 2013] [[Kunsthalle Mainz]].</ref> among other institutions.\n\nIn 2014 he shared an exhibition with [[Carol Rama]] at the [[Nottingham Contemporary]]. On November 14, 2014, his exhibition \"\u0627\u0644\u062d\u062c\u0627\u0631\u0629 \u0648\u0627\u062f\u064a\" (W\u0101d al-\u1e25a\u0177ara) opened at [[Museo Jumex]] in [[Mexico City]]. From February 9 through May 9, 2018, the [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]] is presenting ''Danh Vo: Take My Breath Away'',<ref>\"[https://www.guggenheim.org/exhibition/danh-vo Danh Vo: Take My Breath Away]\". Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum. guggenheim.org. Retrieved 2018-02-10.</ref> the first comprehensive survey of the artist's work in the United States.\n\n[https://www.westkowloon.hk/en/mplus/about-m M+] [[M+|[1]]] in partnership with the Isamu Noguchi Foundation and Garden Museum organised an exhibition of [[Isamu Noguchi]] and Danh V\u014d. [https://stories.mplus.org.hk/en/blog/a-chat-with-danh-vo-about-noguchi-for-danh-vo-counterpoint/ (M+ Story)]  [https://www.westkowloon.hk/en/whats-on/current-forthcoming/noguchi-for-danh-vo-counterpoint/event-type/highlights Noguchi for Danh Vo: Counterpoint](16 Nov 2018 - 22 Apr 2019) The exhibition take place in the [https://www.westkowloon.hk/en/mplus/m-pavilion M+ Pavilion], [[Hong Kong|Hongkong]].\n\n==Art market==\nToday, V\u014d is represented by the [[Marian Goodman Gallery]] in [[New York City]]; Galerie Chantal Crousel, [[Paris]]; [[Xavier Hufkens]], Brussels; and [[Galerie Buchholz]], [[Cologne]]. Until 2015, he also worked with Isabella Bortolozzi Galerie, Berlin.<ref>{{cite web |first=Anny |last=Shaw |date=August 14, 2015 |url=http://theartnewspaper.com/market/art-market-news/158216/ |title=Danh Vo and Isabella Bortolozzi part ways as appeal in Bert Kreuk case is lodged |publisher=[[The Art Newspaper]]. theartnewspaper.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150818071243/http://theartnewspaper.com/market/art-market-news/158216/ |archivedate=2015-08-18 |accessdate=2018-02-10}}</ref>\n\n===2015 law suit===\nIn 2014, Dutch collector and entrepreneur Bert Kreuk filed a suit against V\u014d, claiming that the artist agreed in January 2013 to produce one or more new works for Kreuk\u2019s exhibition, Transforming the Known, at the [[Gemeentemuseum Den Haag]], and that the work would be acquired by the collector after the show. Before the exhibition opened in June 2013, V\u014d sent an existing work, ''Fiat Veritas'' (2013), a cardboard box marked with gold leaf. However, Kreuk said the agreement had been for V\u014d to create a new work for his collection, expressing a preference for the artist\u2019s large-scale Budweiser and American Flag series. In June 2015, a Rotterdam court upheld Kreuk\u2019s claim and ordered the artist to create a new artwork for the collector within a year.<ref>{{cite web |first=Anny |last=Shaw |date=June 25, 2015 |url=http://theartnewspaper.com/market/art-market-news/157210/ |title=Danh Vo to appeal court order to make \u2018large and impressive\u2019 new work for collector |publisher=The Art Newspaper. theartnewspaper.com |accessdate=2018-02-10}}</ref> In July 2015, V\u014d proposed to answer the court ruling by producing a site-specific wall work, as large as Kreuk wished, with the text \"Shove it up your ass, you faggot\";<ref name=\"NewYorkerProfile\" /><ref>\"[https://news.artnet.com/art-world/danh-vo-tells-bert-kreuk-to-shove-it-317385 Danh V\u014d Tells Collector Bert Kreuk to \u201cShove It\u201d in Stunning Private Letter After Contentious Court Ruling]\". ''[[Artnet|Artnet News]]''. artnet.com. Retrieved 2018-02-10.</ref><ref>Zwetsloot, Joris (July 17, 2015). \"[http://www.volkskrant.nl/beeldende-kunst/-indrukwekkend-kunstwerk-wekt-ergernis-opdrachtgever~a4102455/ 'Indrukwekkend' kunstwerk wekt ergernis opdrachtgever]\"{{in lang|nl}}. ''De Volkskrant''. volkskrant.nl.</ref> subsequently, his legal team reached a settlement and the collector dropped the suit.<ref name=\"NewYorkerProfile\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://galeriebuchholz.com/index.php?menu_id=artists&artists_id=87/ Danh Vo at [[Galerie Buchholz]]]\n* [http://en.artpress.com/article/22/04/2013/danh-vo--the-refined-complexity-of-things/9301 Danh Vo: The Refined Complexity of Things], ''[[Art Press]]'', May 2013\n* [http://www.artinamericamagazine.com/features/living-history/ Living History], by Michele Robecchi, ''[[Art in America]]'', October 2012\n* [http://www.artinamericamagazine.com/news-opinion/finer-things/2013-03-15/danh-vo-channels-martin-wong-at-the-guggenheim-/ Danh Vo Channels Martin Wong at the Guggenheim], by Brian Boucher, ''Art in America'', March 2013{{dead link|date=January 2018}}\n* [https://www.kunsthaus-bregenz.at/fileadmin/danh_vo/Heft_Danh_Vo.pdf ''V\u00f4 Danh'' at Kunsthaus Bregenz 2012, Ausstellungskatalog 2012] (in German, transl. [[:de:Sonja Finck|Sonja Finck]])\n*[https://ocula.com/artists/danh-vo/ Danh Vo] at Ocula\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vo, Danh}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Danish contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:Danish performance artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Vietnamese artists]]\n[[Category:Vietnamese emigrants to Denmark]]\n[[Category:Vietnamese expatriates in Germany]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Danh Vo.jpg|thumb|300px|Danh V\u014d (2018)]]\n'''Danh V\u014d''' (born 1975)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artfacts.net/en/artist/danh-vo-51015/profile.html |title=Danh Vo - Biography |publisher=Artfacts.net |date=2013-08-18 |accessdate=2013-08-23}}</ref> is a [[Danes|Danish]] performance art inspired conceptual artist.<ref name=\"artic1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.artic.edu/exhibition/danh-vo-we-people-detail-2010-2013 |title=Danh Vo: We The People (detail), 2010\u20132013 |publisher=The Art Institute of Chicago |date= |accessdate=2013-08-23}}</ref> He lives and works in [[Berlin]], Germany and [[Mexico City]].<ref name=\"NewYorkerProfile\"/><ref name=\"articles.latimes.com\">David Ng (November 1, 2012), [http://articles.latimes.com/2012/nov/01/entertainment/la-et-cm-artist-danh-vo-hugo-boss-prize-guggenheim-20121101 Danh Vo wins 2012 Hugo Boss Prize from Guggenheim Foundation] ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''.</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nDanh V\u014d (pronounced ''yon voh'')<ref name=\"Awash in a Cultural Deluge\">[[Roberta Smith|Smith, Roberta]] (March 14, 2013). \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/15/arts/design/the-hugo-boss-prize-2012-danh-vo-works-at-the-guggenheim.html Awash in a Cultural Deluge]\". ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref> was born in [[B\u00e0 R\u1ecba]], Vietnam in August 1975.<ref name=\"NewYorkerProfile\">[[Calvin Tomkins|Tomkins, Calvin]]\n (January&nbsp;29, 2018). \"[https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2018/01/29/the-artist-questioning-authorship The Artist Questioning Authorship]\". ''[[The New Yorker]]''. newyorker.com. Retrieved 2018-02-10.</ref><ref>[http://www.guggenheim.org/new-york/exhibitions/past/exhibit/5488 The Hugo Boss Prize 2012: Danh Vo] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141206094400/http://www.guggenheim.org/new-york/exhibitions/past/exhibit/5488 |date=2014-12-06 }} [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]], New York.</ref> After the [[Communist Party of Vietnam|Communists]]' victory and the [[fall of Saigon]], the Vo family and 20,000 other South Vietnamese were brought in 1975 to the island of [[Ph\u00fa Qu\u1ed1c]].<ref name=\"Danh Vo: In Memory of Forgetting\">Daniel V\u00f6lzke (December 11, 2009), [http://www.db-artmag.com/en/57/feature/danh-vo-in-memory-of-forgetting/ Danh Vo: In Memory of Forgetting] ''DB ArtMag''.</ref> in 1979, when he was 4 years old, his family fled South Vietnam in a homemade boat and was rescued at sea by a freighter belonging to the Danish [[Maersk]] shipping company.<ref name=\"NewYorkerProfile\"/><ref>[http://www.renaissancesociety.org/site/Exhibitions/Intro.Danh-Vo.629.html Danh Vo: Uterus, September 23 \u2013 December 16, 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004221059/http://www.renaissancesociety.org/site/Exhibitions/Intro.Danh-Vo.629.html |date=October 4, 2013 }} [[Renaissance Society]], Chicago.</ref> The family members settled in Denmark.<ref name=\"NewYorkerProfile\"/> Their assimilation into European culture and the events that led up to their flight from Vietnam are reflected in V\u014d's art, which juxtaposes the historical and the personal.<ref>Carol Vogel (November 1, 2012), [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/02/arts/design/danh-vo-wins-hugo-boss-prize.html Native of Vietnam Wins Hugo Boss Prize] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref> When Danh Vo and his family were registered by the Danish authorities, the family name Vo was placed last. His middle name, Trung, was recorded as his first name.\n\nV\u014d moved to Berlin in 2005, after finishing school at [[St\u00e4delschule]] in [[Frankfurt]], where he went after quitting painting at the [[Royal Danish Academy of Fine Arts]] in [[Copenhagen]].<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">Hilarie M. Sheets (September 20, 2012), [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/23/arts/design/danh-vos-we-the-people-project-in-chicago.html Lady Liberty, Inspiring Even in Pieces] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref> He had residencies at the Villa Aurora in [[Los Angeles]] (2006)<ref name=\"articles.latimes.com\"/> and at [[Kadist Art Foundation]] in [[Paris]] (2009).<ref>[http://kadist.org/en/programs/all/1354 Residencies: Danh Vo] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131118054606/http://www.kadist.org/en/programs/all/1354 |date=2013-11-18 }} Kadist Art Foundation, Paris.</ref> He lives in both Berlin and Mexico City.<ref name=\"NewYorkerProfile\"/>\n\n==Work==\n[[File:Installation view of We The People.JPG|300px|right|thumb|Installation view of \"We The People\", 2010-2013, at National Gallery of Denmark in 2013.]]\nVo's [[Installation art|installation]]<nowiki/>s, which are composed of documents, photos and appropriations of works of other artists, often address the issues of identity and belonging.<ref name=\"Danh Vo: In Memory of Forgetting\"/>\n \nThe conceptual work ''Vo Rosasco Rasmussen'' (2002\u2013) involves the artist's marriage to and immediate divorce from a growing list of important people in his life;<ref name=\"Danh Vo\">\"[https://www.guggenheim.org/artwork/artist/danh-vo Danh Vo]\". [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]], New York. guggenheim.org. Retrieved 2018-02-09.</ref> after each marriage, V\u014d retains the last name of his former spouse. His official name is now Trung Ky Danh Vo Rosaco Rasmussen.<ref>[http://www.smk.dk/en/visit-the-museum/exhibitions/past-exhibitions/2011/danh-vo/about-danh-vo/ Danh Vo: Hip Hip Hurra, 20 November 2010 - 20 March 2011] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203013610/http://www.smk.dk/en/visit-the-museum/exhibitions/past-exhibitions/2011/danh-vo/about-danh-vo/ |date=3 December 2013 }} Statens Museum for Kunst, Copenhagen.</ref> ''Oma Totem'' (2009), a stacked sculpture of his grandmother's welcome gifts from a relief program on her arrival in Germany in the 1980s, displays her television set, washing machine, and refrigerator (adorned with her own [[crucifix]]), among other items.<ref name=\"Danh Vo\"/>\n\nFor ''2.02.1861'' (2009\u2013), the artist asked his father Phung Vo to transcribe the last communication from the French Catholic [[Th\u00e9ophane V\u00e9nard|Saint Th\u00e9ophane V\u00e9nard]] to his own father before he was decapitated in 1861 in Vo's native Vietnam; although multiple copies of the transcribed letter exist (1200 as of 2017),<ref name=\"NewYorkerProfile\"/> the total number will remain undefined until Phung Vo's death.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/><ref>[http://www.guggenheim.org/new-york/collections/collection-online/artwork/28837 Danh Vo, ''2.2.1861'', (2009\u2013)] [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]], New York.</ref>\n\nIn ''Autoerotic Asphyxiation'' (2010), V\u014d presents documentary pictures of young Asian men taken by Joseph Carrier, an American anthropologist and counterinsurgency specialist who worked in Vietnam for the [[RAND Corporation]] from 1962 to 1973. While in Vietnam, Carrier privately documented the casual interactions he observed, intimate without necessarily being homoerotic, between local men; he produced a substantial photographic archive, which he subsequently bequeathed to Danh V\u014d.<ref>Holland Cotter (November 5, 2010), [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/05/arts/design/05galleries-copy2.html Danh Vo: Autoerotic Asphyxiation] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref>\n\nFor his project ''We the People'', created between 2010 and 2012, Vo enlisted a [[Shanghai]] fabricator to recast a life-size [[Statue of Liberty]] from 30 tons of [[copper]] sheets the width of just two pennies.<ref>Martha Schwendener (August 7, 2014), [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/08/arts/design/danh-vos-we-the-people-divided.html Two Parks, One Statue, Lots of Pieces Lying Around] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref> Rather than assemble the approximately 300 sections,<ref name=\"Awash in a Cultural Deluge\"/> the artist shipped the giant elements to some 15 sites around the world after they rolled off the production line in China.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/> From mid May to early December 2014 ''We the People'' was shown in [[New York City]] under the auspices of the [[Public Art Fund]],<ref>\"[https://www.publicartfund.org/view/exhibitions/6042_danh_vo_we_the_people Danh Vo: We The People&nbsp;&ndash; About the Exhibition]\". Public Art Fund. publicartfund.org. Retrieved 2018-02-09.</ref> with its assembly of parts shared between [[City Hall Park]] in [[Lower Manhattan]] and [[Brooklyn Bridge Park]] in the borough of [[Brooklyn]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/exhibition-in-new-york-gives-new-perspective-on-statue-of-liberty-1400208982|title=Exhibition in New York Gives New Perspective on Statue of Liberty|first=Kirthana|last=Ramisetti|date=May 16, 2014|type=preview only; subscription required |publisher=Wall Street Journal. wsj.com}}</ref><ref>Rosenberg, Karen (August&nbsp;7, 2014). \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/08/arts/design/danh-vos-we-the-people-divided.html Two Parks, One Statue, Lots of Pieces Lying Around: Danh Vo\u2019s \u2018We the People,\u2019 Divided]\". ''New York Times''. nytimes.com. Retrieved 2018-02-09.</ref> While the work was being installed in City Hall Park, a few of its pieces&nbsp;&ndash; replicas of the chain links found at the feet of the original Statue of Liberty&nbsp;&ndash; were stolen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.phaidon.com/agenda/art/articles/2014/may/20/danh-vo-artwork-stolen-in-new-york/|title=Danh Vo artwork stolen in New York |publisher=Phaidon |date=May 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\nFor a 2013 show at the [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]], Vo conceived a homage to the artist [[Martin Wong]]. The installation consists of nearly 4,000 frequently small artworks, artifacts and [[tchotchke]]<nowiki/>s that once belonged to Wong, crowded into a specially designed gallery lined with [[laminated]] [[plywood]] shelves. The show's title\u2014''I am you and you are too''\u2014appeared on Wong's business cards and stamps.<ref name=\"Awash in a Cultural Deluge\"/>\n\nAnother 2013 show at New York's [[Marian Goodman Gallery]] focused on the personal effects of the late U.S. Secretary of Defense [[Robert McNamara]], the architect of the [[Vietnam War]]. Looking to open up a dialogue about shared and private histories, V\u014d displayed or modified 14 items acquired at a [[Sotheby's]] auction\u2014including the pen used to the sign the [[Gulf of Tonkin incident|Gulf of Tonkin memo]] and a 1944 photograph by [[Ansel Adams]].<ref>Michael Slenske (March 2013), [http://www.wmagazine.com/fashion/2013/03/conceptual-artist-danh-vo-at-the-guggenheim-and-marian-goodman/ Don't Miss: Danh Vo at the Guggenheim and Marian Goodman] ''[[W (magazine)|W]]''.</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\nV\u014d won the 2012 [[Hugo Boss Prize]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.guggenheim.org/new-york/press-room/releases/5121-winnerhugobossprize2012 |title=Artist Danh Vo Wins Hugo Boss Prize 2012 |publisher=Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum |date=2012-11-01 |accessdate=2013-08-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130820005310/http://www.guggenheim.org/new-york/press-room/releases/5121-winnerhugobossprize2012 |archivedate=2013-08-20 }}</ref> the BlauOrange Kunstpreis of Berlin's [[Bundesverband der Deutschen Volksbanken und Raiffeisenbanken|Deutschen Volksbanken und Raiffeisenbanken]] in 2007, and was a nominee for the Preis der [[Nationalgalerie]] f\u00fcr junge Kunst in 2009.<ref name=\"mariangoodman.com\">[http://www.mariangoodman.com/artists/danh-v/ Danh Vo] [[Marian Goodman Gallery]], New York/Paris.</ref>\n\n==Exhibitions==\nV\u014d had his first solo exhibition in 2005, at the Galerie Klosterfelde in Berlin.<ref>[http://cgi.klosterfelde.de/user-cgi-bin/exhibitions/?s1=03-previous&s2=2005 Danh Vo, November 19 - December 23, 2005] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004215516/http://cgi.klosterfelde.de/user-cgi-bin/exhibitions/?s1=03-previous&s2=2005 |date=October 4, 2013 }} Galerie Klosterfelde, Berlin.</ref>\n\nHe participated in the [[Venice Biennale]] in 2013.<ref name=\"mariangoodman.com\"/> His work has been exhibited at the [[Walker Art Center]] in [[Minneapolis]];<ref>{{cite web|last=Ryan |first=Bartholomew |url=http://www.walkerart.org/magazine/2012/tombstone-for-phung-vo |title=Tombstone for Ph\u00f9ng Vo \u2014 Magazine \u2014 Walker Art Center |publisher=Walkerart.org |date=2012-01-04 |accessdate=2013-08-23}}</ref> the [[Art Institute of Chicago]];<ref name=\"artic1\" /> the [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]] in New York; and the [[Mus\u00e9e d'art moderne de la Ville de Paris]], [[Kunsthaus Bregenz]], [[Austria]], the [[Kunsthalle Mainz]], [[Germany]],<ref>[http://www.kunsthalle-mainz.de/en/exhibitions/past/thomas-schuette-brdanh-vo/ Reich ohne Mitte, Thomas Schuette und Danh Vo, August 5 - October 6, 2013] [[Kunsthalle Mainz]].</ref> among other institutions.\n\nIn 2014 he shared an exhibition with [[Carol Rama]] at the [[Nottingham Contemporary]]. On November 14, 2014, his exhibition \"\u0627\u0644\u062d\u062c\u0627\u0631\u0629 \u0648\u0627\u062f\u064a\" (W\u0101d al-\u1e25a\u0177ara) opened at [[Museo Jumex]] in [[Mexico City]]. From February 9 through May 9, 2018, the [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]] is presenting ''Danh Vo: Take My Breath Away'',<ref>\"[https://www.guggenheim.org/exhibition/danh-vo Danh Vo: Take My Breath Away]\". Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum. guggenheim.org. Retrieved 2018-02-10.</ref> the first comprehensive survey of the artist's work in the United States.\n\n[https://www.westkowloon.hk/en/mplus/about-m M+] [[M+|[1]]] in partnership with the Isamu Noguchi Foundation and Garden Museum organised an exhibition of [[Isamu Noguchi]] and Danh V\u014d. [https://stories.mplus.org.hk/en/blog/a-chat-with-danh-vo-about-noguchi-for-danh-vo-counterpoint/ (M+ Story)]  [https://www.westkowloon.hk/en/whats-on/current-forthcoming/noguchi-for-danh-vo-counterpoint/event-type/highlights Noguchi for Danh Vo: Counterpoint](16 Nov 2018 - 22 Apr 2019) The exhibition take place in the [https://www.westkowloon.hk/en/mplus/m-pavilion M+ Pavilion], [[Hong Kong|Hongkong]].\n\n==Art market==\nToday, V\u014d is represented by the [[Marian Goodman Gallery]] in [[New York City]]; Galerie Chantal Crousel, [[Paris]]; and [[Galerie Buchholz]], [[Cologne]]. Until 2015, he also worked with Isabella Bortolozzi Galerie, Berlin.<ref>{{cite web |first=Anny |last=Shaw |date=August 14, 2015 |url=http://theartnewspaper.com/market/art-market-news/158216/ |title=Danh Vo and Isabella Bortolozzi part ways as appeal in Bert Kreuk case is lodged |publisher=[[The Art Newspaper]]. theartnewspaper.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150818071243/http://theartnewspaper.com/market/art-market-news/158216/ |archivedate=2015-08-18 |accessdate=2018-02-10}}</ref>\n\n===2015 law suit===\nIn 2014, Dutch collector and entrepreneur Bert Kreuk filed a suit against V\u014d, claiming that the artist agreed in January 2013 to produce one or more new works for Kreuk\u2019s exhibition, Transforming the Known, at the [[Gemeentemuseum Den Haag]], and that the work would be acquired by the collector after the show. Before the exhibition opened in June 2013, V\u014d sent an existing work, ''Fiat Veritas'' (2013), a cardboard box marked with gold leaf. However, Kreuk said the agreement had been for V\u014d to create a new work for his collection, expressing a preference for the artist\u2019s large-scale Budweiser and American Flag series. In June 2015, a Rotterdam court upheld Kreuk\u2019s claim and ordered the artist to create a new artwork for the collector within a year.<ref>{{cite web |first=Anny |last=Shaw |date=June 25, 2015 |url=http://theartnewspaper.com/market/art-market-news/157210/ |title=Danh Vo to appeal court order to make \u2018large and impressive\u2019 new work for collector |publisher=The Art Newspaper. theartnewspaper.com |accessdate=2018-02-10}}</ref> In July 2015, V\u014d proposed to answer the court ruling by producing a site-specific wall work, as large as Kreuk wished, with the text \"Shove it up your ass, you faggot\";<ref name=\"NewYorkerProfile\" /><ref>\"[https://news.artnet.com/art-world/danh-vo-tells-bert-kreuk-to-shove-it-317385 Danh V\u014d Tells Collector Bert Kreuk to \u201cShove It\u201d in Stunning Private Letter After Contentious Court Ruling]\". ''[[Artnet|Artnet News]]''. artnet.com. Retrieved 2018-02-10.</ref><ref>Zwetsloot, Joris (July 17, 2015). \"[http://www.volkskrant.nl/beeldende-kunst/-indrukwekkend-kunstwerk-wekt-ergernis-opdrachtgever~a4102455/ 'Indrukwekkend' kunstwerk wekt ergernis opdrachtgever]\"{{in lang|nl}}. ''De Volkskrant''. volkskrant.nl.</ref> subsequently, his legal team reached a settlement and the collector dropped the suit.<ref name=\"NewYorkerProfile\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://galeriebuchholz.com/index.php?menu_id=artists&artists_id=87/ Danh Vo at [[Galerie Buchholz]]]\n* [http://en.artpress.com/article/22/04/2013/danh-vo--the-refined-complexity-of-things/9301 Danh Vo: The Refined Complexity of Things], ''[[Art Press]]'', May 2013\n* [http://www.artinamericamagazine.com/features/living-history/ Living History], by Michele Robecchi, ''[[Art in America]]'', October 2012\n* [http://www.artinamericamagazine.com/news-opinion/finer-things/2013-03-15/danh-vo-channels-martin-wong-at-the-guggenheim-/ Danh Vo Channels Martin Wong at the Guggenheim], by Brian Boucher, ''Art in America'', March 2013{{dead link|date=January 2018}}\n* [https://www.kunsthaus-bregenz.at/fileadmin/danh_vo/Heft_Danh_Vo.pdf ''V\u00f4 Danh'' at Kunsthaus Bregenz 2012, Ausstellungskatalog 2012] (in German, transl. [[:de:Sonja Finck|Sonja Finck]])\n*[https://ocula.com/artists/danh-vo/ Danh Vo] at Ocula\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vo, Danh}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Danish contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:Danish performance artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Vietnamese artists]]\n[[Category:Vietnamese emigrants to Denmark]]\n[[Category:Vietnamese expatriates in Germany]]\n", "name_user": "Madehp", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eArt market", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Danh_V%C5%8D"}
{"title_page": "List of natural disasters in the British Isles", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2013}}\n{{More citations needed|date=July 2007}}\nThis is a '''list of [[natural disaster]]s in [[Great Britain]] and [[Ireland]]'''.\n\n== List of natural disasters to have affected the British Isles, ordered chronologically ==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"; margin: 0 0 0.5em 1em; padding: 0.5em; border: 1px solid #ddb; width: 250px; font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! Colour scheme used in this table:\n|-\n| style=\"background: rgb(245,222,179)\" | Geological event\n|-\n| style=\"background: rgb(255,255,255)\" | Cold weather event\n|-\n| style=\"background: rgb(255,225,225)\" | Hot weather event\n|-\n| style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | High winds event\n|-\n| style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | Wet weather event\n|-\n| style=\"background: rgb(255,250,205)\" | Famine\n|-\n| style=\"background: rgb(210,255,210)\" | Sickness epidemic\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Disaster event\n! Notes; disaster type, people killed, region affected, etc.\n|-\n|[[Paleolithic|70,000-75,000 ybp]] || style=\"background: rgb(245,222,179)\" | Prolonged [[volcanic winter]] || Long lasting volcanic winters following the [[Toba catastrophe theory|Toba catastrophe]] have been hypothesised to have killed every human not living in Africa at the time.\n|-\n| [[7th millennium BC|6100 BC]] || style=\"background: rgb(245,222,179)\" | Tsunami || Caused by the [[Storegga Slide]], struck east [[Scotland]] with {{convert|70|ft|adj=on}} wave after undersea landslip off [[Norway]].\n|-\n| 535-536 || style=\"background: rgb(255,255,255)\" | [[Extreme weather events of 535\u2013536]] || The most severe cooling in the [[Northern Hemisphere]] in the last 2,000 years, likely caused crop failures and freezing for the [[Anglo-Saxons]].\n|-\n| 10th century || style=\"background: rgb(255,225,225)\" | Regular heatwaves || Extended droughts with regularity: also through the period summers lasted half a year and were often warm or very warm - some notably extreme summers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://booty.org.uk/booty.weather/climate/751_999.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170127142441/http://booty.org.uk/booty.weather/climate/751_999.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=2017-01-27|title=751_999|work=booty.org.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1091 || style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | [[London tornado of 1091]] || 2 deaths, the early [[London Bridge]], 600 houses, many churches (inc. [[St Mary-le-Bow]])\n|-\n| 1235 || style=\"background: rgb(255,250,205)\" | Famine || England; 20,000 die in London alone<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/personal-view/3609390/Poor-studies-will-always-be-with-us.html | work=The Daily Telegraph | location=London | title=Poor studies will always be with us | first=James | last=Bartholomew | date=8 August 2004 | accessdate=8 May 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1252-1253 || style=\"background: rgb(255,225,225)\" | Both dry years and excessive heat || Considered by some (e.g. Brooks), as the driest pair of consecutive years known in the record. The summer (and possibly the spring in London/south) of 1252 was outstandingly dry/hot, with the ensuing drought ruining crops and many people died from the excessive heat. Spring/summer 1253 was also noted as dry/hot London/south.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://booty.org.uk/booty.weather/climate/1200_1299.htm|title=1200_1299|work=booty.org.uk|access-date=9 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140325235004/http://booty.org.uk/booty.weather/climate/1200_1299.htm|archive-date=25 March 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1287 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[St. Lucia's flood]] || Not known by that name the flood killed hundreds in England. This flood along with the [[South England flood of February 1287]] contributed to the decline of [[Dunwich]] as a major port\n|-\n| 1315-1317 || style=\"background: rgb(255,250,205)\" | [[Great Famine of 1315\u20131317]] || Throughout Europe\n|-\n| 1324 || style=\"background: rgb(255,225,225)\" | 10 years of hot summers || Drought in summer (London/south). Possibly the start of ten or so years of warm, often dry summers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://booty.org.uk/booty.weather/climate/1300_1399.htm|title=1300_1399|work=booty.org.uk|access-date=9 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140326042326/http://booty.org.uk/booty.weather/climate/1300_1399.htm|archive-date=26 March 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1348-1350s || style=\"background: rgb(210,255,210)\" | [[Black Death in England]] || Killed somewhere around 50% of the population\n|-\n| 1360s || style=\"background: rgb(210,255,210)\" | [[Black Death in England]] || Killed a further 20% of the population\n|-\n| 1485\u20131551 || style=\"background: rgb(210,255,210)\" | [[Sweating sickness]] || Sporadic outbreaks kill many thousands\n|-\n| 1540-41 || style=\"background: rgb(255,225,225)\" | Great heat and drought || Dry, in 1538\u201339. In 1540\u201341, the [[River Thames]] was so low that [[seawater]] extended above [[London Bridge]]. Reports at the time suggest that there were many deaths due to the 'Ague', and 1540 is described in contemporary chronicles as the 'Big Sun Year'.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://booty.org.uk/booty.weather/climate/1500_1599.htm|title=1500_1599|work=booty.org.uk|access-date=9 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140326054338/http://booty.org.uk/booty.weather/climate/1500_1599.htm|archive-date=26 March 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1580 || style=\"background: rgb(245,222,179)\" | [[1580 Dover Straits earthquake]] || Estimated to have been 5.3\u20135.9 [[Richter magnitude scale|M<sub>L</sub>]]. Two deaths in England.\n|-\n| 1607 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[Bristol Channel floods, 1607]] || 30 January 1607 (possible [[tsunami]]). Flooding in the [[Bristol Channel]] hit [[Carmarthenshire]], [[Glamorgan]], [[Monmouthshire (historic)|Monmouthshire]], [[Devon]], and [[Somerset]]\n|-\n| 1623-24 || style=\"background: rgb(255,250,205)\" | Famine || Said to be the last peace-time famine in England\n|-\n| 1638 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[The Great Thunderstorm]] || [[Widecombe-in-the-Moor]], Devon, four killed and sixty injured\n|-\n| 1651-1653 || style=\"background: rgb(255,250,205)\" | Famine || Famine throughout much of [[Ireland]] during the [[Cromwellian conquest of Ireland, brought on by the \"scorched earth policy\" whereby Cromwell ordered his troops to burn all food crops so as to starve the population. This was part of his genocidal campaign in Ireland and not a natural disaster.#Guerrilla warfare, famine and plague|Cromwellian conquest of Ireland]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/northernireland/ashorthistory/archive/intro99.shtml|title=BBC iPlayer - Northern Ireland - A Short History|work=bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1665 || style=\"background: rgb(210,255,210)\" | [[Great Plague of London]] || [[Bubonic plague]] killed an estimated 100,000 people, 20% of London's population\n|-\n| 1665 || style=\"background: rgb(210,255,210)\" | [[Derby plague of 1665]] || The [[bubonic plague]] spread north, but was stalled by the famous quarantine of [[Eyam]]\n|-\n| 1665-66|| style=\"background: rgb(255,225,225)\" | Long drought followed by a hot summer || Every month from November 1665 to September 1666 was dry. The climatological summer (June, July and August) of 1666 was amongst the top 10 or so of warm summers in the Central English Temperatures (CET) series (began 1659). CET also suggests that July 1666 had a mean value of {{convert|18|C}}, and August was {{convert|17|C}}. The heat and long drought added to a heightened risk of fire in populated areas. Lack of rain and hot temperatures helped spark the [[Great Fire of London]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://booty.org.uk/booty.weather/climate/1650_1699.htm|title=1650_1699|work=booty.org.uk|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140325222440/http://booty.org.uk/booty.weather/climate/1650_1699.htm|archivedate=25 March 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> As a result, this year saw an end to the [[Great Plague of London]] due to extreme heat and fire.\n|-\n| 1690s || style=\"background: rgb(255,250,205)\" | Famine ||| Known as the [[seven ill years]] it occurred throughout Scotland, killing 15% of the population\n|-\n| 1703 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[Great Storm of 1703]] || Up to 15,000 deaths, ships lost, mass damage to buildings and trees\n|-\n| 16th-18th centuries || style=\"background: rgb(255,255,255)\" | [[Little Ice Age]] || Long-lasting period of lower-than-normal average temperatures\n|-\n| 1709 || style=\"background: rgb(255,255,255)\" | [[Great Frost of 1709]] || Extremely cold winter, temperatures as low as {{convert|-12|C}} on 5 January\n|-\n| 1729 || style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | Tornado || [[Bexhill-on-Sea]] struck by a waterspout that came ashore\n|-\n| 1740 || style=\"background: rgb(255,250,205)\" | [[Irish Famine (1740\u201341)]] || Somewhere between 310,000 and 480,000 people starve in Ireland due to cold weather affecting harvests\n|-\n| 1755 || style=\"background: rgb(245,222,179)\" | Tsunami || Following the [[1755 Lisbon earthquake|Lisbon earthquake]], [[Cornwall]] was struck by a {{convert|10|ft|abbr=on}} wave\n|-\n| 1770 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | Flooding and storms || In August throughout southern England. A flood was thought to have occurred in [[Lynmouth]], Devon in 1769 and the date may have transposed to 1796.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1002/j.1477-8696.2001.tb06504.x | volume=56 | issue=10 | title=Great storms and floods over southern England, August 1770 | year=2001 | journal=Weather | pages=327\u2013337 | last1 = Clark | first1 = C.| bibcode=2001Wthr...56..327C }}</ref>\n|-\n| 1783 || style=\"background: rgb(245,222,179)\" | \"[[Laki]] haze\" || [[Sulfur dioxide|Sulphurous gas]] from an eruption in [[Iceland]] suffocates more than 10,000 in Britain,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/3745749.stm Volcano 'drove up UK death toll']</ref> followed by about 8,000 deaths in winter\n|-\n| 1816 || style=\"background: rgb(245,222,179)\" | [[Year Without a Summer]] || Caused by the [[1815 eruption of Mount Tambora]], crops devastated, unknown thousands die\n|-\n| 1816-1819 || style=\"background: rgb(210,255,210)\" | [[Typhus]] epidemic || Ireland\n|-\n| 1831-50 || style=\"background: rgb(210,255,210)\" | [[Cholera]] pandemic || Part of the [[1829\u20131851 cholera pandemic]], beginning in London, 55,000 die in outbreaks across England and Wales\n|-\n| 1836 || style=\"background: rgb(245,222,179)\" | [[Lewes avalanche]] || [[Lewes]], the only major avalanche recorded in [[England]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.theargus.co.uk/2006/12/27/223771.html |title=Avalanche anniversary in Lewes pub |accessdate=18 May 2009 |publisher=The Argus |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929083407/http://archive.theargus.co.uk/2006/12/27/223771.html |archivedate=29 September 2007 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/southerncounties/nature/wtt/03.shtml|title=Radicals and Rebels - Stage 3|publisher=[[BBC]]|\naccessdate=18 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/insideout/south/series1/weird-weather.shtml|title=Inside Out - South: Monday 7th October, 2002|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=18 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.999lewes.com/ | title=About Lewes|date=May 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928225805/http://www.999lewes.com/| archive-date =28 September 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n|1839 || style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | [[Night of the Big Wind]]|| A [[European windstorm]] swept across Ireland causing hundreds of deaths and severe damage to property. Gusts were over {{convert|100|kn|lk=in}}\n|-\n| 1840s || style=\"background: rgb(255,250,205)\" | [[Great Famine (Ireland)|Great Irish Famine]] || [[Phytophthora infestans|Potato blight]] devastates food sources. Killed around 1 million people out of a total population of 8 million\n\n|-\n| 1840s || style=\"background: rgb(255,250,205)\" | [[Highland Potato Famine]] || Another starvation event, similar to the one directly above but in Scotland and with very few deaths. However, 200,000 were said to have emigrated.\n|-\n| 1848 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[Moray Firth fishing disaster]] || 100 fishermen and 124 boats lost at sea during a storm in [[Scotland]]\n|-\n| 1852 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[Holmfirth floods|Holmfirth Flood]] || [[River Holme|Bilberry Reservoir]] embankment collapses, causing 81 deaths and a large amount of damage to property.\n|-\n| 1859 || style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\"  | [[Royal Charter Storm]]||Named for the ''[[Royal Charter (ship)|Royal Charter]]'' the storm, which lasted for two days, sank 133 ships killing 800.\n|-\n| 1864 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[Great Sheffield Flood]] || [[Dale Dike Reservoir]] bursts, destroying 800 houses and killing 270 people. (not strictly a natural disaster because it was structural failure caused by human error)\n|-\n| 1871 || style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | [[Great Gale of 1871]] || Occurring in the North Sea on Friday 10 February 1871 it killed at least 50 people.\n|-\n|1879 ||style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | [[Tay Bridge disaster]] || A European windstorm on 28 December 1879 caused the [[Tay Rail Bridge]] to collapse killing between 60 and 75 people.\n|-\n| 1881 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[Eyemouth disaster]] || 189 fishermen died during a storm in [[Scotland]]\n|-\n| 1881 || style=\"background: rgb(255,255,255)\" | [[Blizzard of January 1881]] || Around 100 die in one of the most severe [[blizzard]]s ever to hit the southern parts of the United Kingdom\n|-\n| 1884 || style=\"background: rgb(245,222,179)\" | [[1884 Colchester earthquake]] || Several people killed, and 1200 buildings destroyed in [[Essex]]\n|-\n|1894-95 || style=\"background: rgb(255,255,255)\" | [[Winter of 1894\u201395 in the United Kingdom]]|| Conditions were such that many people died of [[hypothermia]] or respiratory conditions\n|-\n|1911 || style=\"background: rgb(255,225,225)\" | [[1911 United Kingdom heat wave]] || Heat wave lasted from early July to mid-September. Newspapers ran deaths by heat columns\n|-\n| 1918-19 || style=\"background: rgb(210,255,210)\" | [[1918 flu pandemic]] || Worldwide [[influenza pandemic]] nicknamed the Spanish flu\n|-\n| 1928 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[1928 Thames flood]] || A disastrous flood of the River Thames in London. 14 drowned and thousands made homeless.\n|-\n| 1931 || style=\"background: rgb(245,222,179)\" | [[1931 Dogger Bank earthquake]] || At 6.1 on the Richter Scale, was the largest earthquake in British history, but caused only minor damage as was offshore.\n|-\n| 1946-47 || style=\"background: rgb(255,255,255)\" | [[Winter of 1946\u201347 in the United Kingdom|Winter of 1946&ndash;1947]] || Right after WWII, blizzards block roads and cause blackouts, resulting in industrial stagnation. Followed by heavy flooding in March, causing \u00a3250\u2013375 million of damage.\n|-\n| 1952 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[Lynmouth Flood|Lynmouth flood of 1952]] || 34 people were killed, with a further 420 made homeless. Over 100 buildings were destroyed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/august/16/newsid_2960000/2960180.stm|title=On This Day: 1952: Flood devastates Devon village|accessdate=18 May 2009|publisher=[[BBC]] | date=16 August 1952}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1516880.stm|title=Rain-making link to killer floods|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=18 May 2009 | date=30 August 2001}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exmoor-nationalpark.gov.uk/the_lynmouth_floods_of_1952_exmoor|title=The 1952 Flood Disaster in Context|publisher=Exmoor National Park|accessdate=18 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/devon/news_features/2002/lynmouth_flood.shtml|title=Lynmouth flood disaster|last=Joint|first=Laura|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=18 May 2009}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1953 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[North Sea flood of 1953]] || 307 were killed in the United Kingdom, in the counties of [[Lincolnshire]], [[Norfolk]], [[Suffolk]] and [[Essex]].\n|-\n| 1955 || style=\"background: rgb(255,225,225)\" |[[1955 United Kingdom heat wave]] || Heat wave and drought throughout the country.\n|-\n| 1962-63 || style=\"background: rgb(255,255,255)\" | [[Winter of 1962\u201363 in the United Kingdom|Winter of 1962\u20131963]] || Coldest winter for hundreds of years, temperatures as low as {{convert|-16|C}}.\n|-\n| 1968 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\"  | [[July 1968 England and Wales dust fall storms]] || Dust from the Sahara desert causes extremely heavy rain and hail, causing widespread damage across Wales and western and northern England.\n|-\n| 1968 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[Great Flood of 1968]] || Flooding causes extensive damage to [[Southern England]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Hundreds homeless after flood havoc|work=[[The Times]]|page=1|date=16 September 1968}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1968 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[1968 Scotland storm|1968 Hurricane]] || Hurricane-force winds cause 20 deaths in the [[Central Belt]] of Scotland. In Glasgow alone, over 300 houses were destroyed and 70,000 homes were damaged. Electrical power also failed in Glasgow, leaving the whole city in darkness. In total the storm felled 8,000 hectares of forest across Scotland (1.6 million cubic metres of timber). The storm, which affected Northern England, Scotland and N. Ireland received little attention from the BBC or the national press.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1968/feb/07/scotland-storm-damage?lang=_e|title=Hansard: SCOTLAND (STORM DAMAGE)}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1976 || style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | [[Gale of January 1976]] || The gale of 2\u20135 January resulted in severe wind damage across western and central Europe and coastal flooding around the southern [[North Sea]] coasts. At the time, this was the most severe storm over the [[British Isles]].\n|-\n| 1974-1976|| style=\"background: rgb(255,225,225)\" | Two-year drought and [[1976 United Kingdom heat wave|UK heat wave]] || 1974-1975 had the mildest winter in England and Wales since 1869. However, during the first few days of June 1975, in and around London snow and [[Rain and snow mixed|sleet]] occurred. During the next week maximum temperatures of {{convert|27|C}} were recorded each day across the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://booty.org.uk/booty.weather/climate/1975_1999.htm|title=1975 - 1999|work=booty.org.uk|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003053817/http://booty.org.uk/booty.weather/climate/1975_1999.htm|archivedate=3 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The summer of 1976 experienced 5 days of temperatures exceeding {{convert|35|C}} somewhere in the UK. Between 23 June to 7 July, temperatures in London and other parts of Southern England reached above {{convert|32|C}} for 15 consecutive days. The weather was settled and temperatures were above average, with many short and long periods of above {{convert|30|C|F|0}} heat, between mid June to mid September. In 1976, the country suffered forest fires, grass fires and water shortages. Summer 1976 was followed by an extremely unsettled Autumn.\n|-\n| 1978 || style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | [[1978 North Sea storm surge]] || A storm surge which occurred over 11\u201312 January caused extensive coastal flooding and considerable damage on the east coast of England between the [[Humber]] and [[Kent]]. Locally severe flooding occurred in Lincolnshire, [[The Wash]], north Norfolk and Kent. Improvements in flood protection following the devastating flood of 1953 meant that the catastrophic losses seen during that storm were not repeated. The storm caused severe damage to many piers along the east coast of England.\n|-\n| 1987 || style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | [[Great Storm of 1987]] || After [[Michael Fish]] famously forecast \"very windy\" weather mainly over France, an unusually strong storm occurred in October 1987, with wind speeds widely over {{convert|100|mph|abbr=on}} along England's southern coastline, and which killed 18 people in England. The great storm caused substantial damage over much of Southern England, downing an estimated 15 million trees (including six of the seven eponymous oaks in [[Sevenoaks]]).\n|-\n| 1990 || style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | [[Burns' Day Storm]] || Winds of up to {{convert|100|mph|abbr=on}} kill 97 people and cause \u00a33.37 billion worth of damage, the most costly weather event for insurers in British history.\n|-\n|1990-91|| style=\"background: rgb(255,255,255)\" | [[Winter of 1990\u201391 in Western Europe|Winter of 1990\u201391]]|| Lasting from December 1990 to February 1991 throughout the United Kingdom, Ireland and Western Europe. About 42 people died, almost all in the UK and Ireland\n|-\n| 1998 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[Easter 1998 United Kingdom floods|1998 Easter floods]] || At the start of Easter 1998 (9\u201310 April) a stationary band of heavy rain affected [[the Midlands]]. This resulted in floods in which five people died and thousands had to be evacuated from their homes. The wettest area, with over {{Convert|75|mm|abbr=on}}, stretched from [[Worcestershire]] towards [[The Wash]] and the flooded towns included [[Evesham]], [[Royal Leamington Spa|Leamington Spa]], [[Stratford-upon-Avon]], [[Bedford]], [[Northampton]] and [[Huntingdon]]. On [[Maundy Thursday]] (9 April), thundery rain in the south of England moved northwards and became slow-moving from [[East Anglia]] through the Midlands to [[north Wales]]. This band gave some very heavy downpours with hail and thunder. On [[Good Friday]] (10th) the band rotated slowly anticlockwise spreading to Lincolnshire and the [[West Country]] and continued to rotate, with sleet and heavy bursts of rain in places. There was sleet and snow across the [[Pennines]] and north Wales during the evening.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/interesting/easter1998|title = Easter 1998 floods|date = 25 October 2012|publisher = M.W. Horner and P.D. Walsh}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2000 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[Autumn 2000 Western Europe floods|Flooding]] || Severe flooding in many parts of the UK. Among the worst hit were [[York]], [[Kent]], [[Sussex]], [[Shrewsbury]], [[Lewes]], [[Uckfield]] and [[Maidstone]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/weather/features/flood_facts.shtml|title=BBC Weather: Flood Facts|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=18 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Dead link|url=http://www.defra.gov.uk/environ/fcd/floodincidents/2000flood.htm|date=May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/commondata/acrobat/126637|title=Lessons Learned: Autumn 2000 floods|accessdate=18 May 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927182913/http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/commondata/acrobat/126637|archivedate=27 September 2007|format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/southerncounties/nature/wtt/03.shtml|title=Southern Counties > Nature > Walks > Lewes - Radicals and Rebels > Stage 3|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=18 May 2009}}{{Failed verification|date=May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cfspress.com/Kelman-UK-Floods.pdf|title=The Autumn 2000 Floods in England|last=Kelman|first=Ilan|publisher=The Martin Centre, University of Cambridge|year=2002|accessdate=18 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rms.com/Publications/UKFLOODS_OCT13-14.pdf|title=U.K. Floods, October 13\u201314, 2000: Examination of U.K. Flood Damage During Increased Rainfall in October 2000|publisher=Risk Management Solutions|accessdate=18 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastsussex.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/00016FE4-50D0-4AD8-99BB-BB06D7BEEF22/0/lewesflood.pdf|title=THE LEWES FLOOD OF OCTOBER 2000|accessdate=18 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lewes.gov.uk/Files/env_floodreport.pdf|title=Flood Report: March 2001|publisher=Environment Agency|accessdate=18 May 2009 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060519120319/http://www.lewes.gov.uk/Files/env_floodreport.pdf |archivedate = 19 May 2006}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/interesting/autumn2000.html|title=The wet autumn of 2000|website=Met Office|access-date=2017-02-14}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2002 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[2002 Glasgow floods]] || 200 people immediately evacuated, but the water supply of 140 thousand people was affected.\n|-\n| 2003 || style=\"background: rgb(255,225,225)\" | [[2003 European heat wave]] || More than 2,000 people may have died in the UK alone as a result of the hottest summer recorded in Europe since 1540. Temperatures remained above {{convert|30|C}} for 10 days, between 3 and 13 August. The highest temperature known and accepted was recorded at [[Faversham|Faversham, Kent]] on 10 August when it reached {{convert|38.5|C}}. The death toll across Europe as a result of the heatwave was eventually estimated at 70000.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Robine|first=Jean-Marie|last2=Cheung|first2=Siu Lan K.|last3=Le Roy|first3=Sophie|last4=Van Oyen|first4=Herman|last5=Griffiths|first5=Clare|last6=Michel|first6=Jean-Pierre|last7=Herrmann|first7=Fran\u00e7ois Richard|date=February 2008|title=Death toll exceeded 70,000 in Europe during the summer of 2003|journal=Comptes Rendus Biologies|volume=331|issue=2|pages=171\u2013178|doi=10.1016/j.crvi.2007.12.001|pmid=18241810}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2004 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[Boscastle flood of 2004]] || [[Boscastle]] and [[Crackington Haven]], two villages in [[Cornwall]], were heavily damaged due to flash floods.\n|-\n| 2005 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | Flooding || [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]], 8 January 2005<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cumbria/history/features/cumbrian_floods/index.shtml|title=Archive: Cumbrian Floods|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=18 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/regions/northwest/942672/?lang=_e|title=Cumbria floods|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080104031143/http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/regions/northwest/942672/?lang=_e|archivedate=4 January 2008|accessdate=18 May 2009}}</ref> See [[Cyclone Gudrun]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Windstorm Erwin / Gudrun \u2013 January 2005 |url=http://www.dmi.dk/dmi/8januarstormguycarprapport.pdf |publisher=Guy Carpenter |accessdate=23 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415064808/http://www.dmi.dk/dmi/8januarstormguycarprapport.pdf |archivedate=15 April 2012 }}</ref>\n|-\n| 2005 || style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | [[Birmingham tornado of 2005|Birmingham Tornado]] || 30 injuries caused by the tornado, which uprooted trees, destroyed roofs and picked up cars, causing \u00a340 million in damages.\n|-\n| 2006 || style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | [[2006 London tornado|London Tornado]] || Only one injury, but \u00a310 million of damage caused.\n|-\n| 2007 || style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | [[Cyclone Kyrill|Storm Kyrill]] || Hurricane-force winds across British Isles, at least 11 people dead\n|-\n| 2007 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[2007 United Kingdom floods]] || Killed 13 people. [[Gloucestershire]] suffers many road and rail closures, power cuts and evacuations, with 420,000 inhabitants left without drinking water requiring emergency assistance from the army. Other areas heavily affected include [[Yorkshire]], [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]] and [[Worcestershire]]. The disaster is estimated to have caused \u00a36 billion of damage.\n|-\n|2008|| style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\"  | [[2008 Irish flash floods]]||Flash floods throughout August lead to one death and the destruction of 50 houses.\n|-\n| 2008 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[2008 Morpeth floods]] || [[River Wansbeck]] bursts its banks causing damage to 995 properties costing \u00a340 million. Flooding across the Midlands and [[North East England]] associated with a slow moving front of the low pressure system Mattea.<ref>{{cite web|title=England struck by flash flooding|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/7602110.stm|publisher=BBC|accessdate=23 May 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|2009|| style=\"background: rgb(245,222,179)\" |[[2009 Buachaille Etive M\u00f2r avalanche]]|| An avalanche on [[Buachaille Etive M\u00f2r]] in [[Glen Coe]] in the [[Scottish Highlands]], [[United Kingdom|UK]], on 24 January 2009 killed three climbers and injured another.\n|-\n| 2009 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[2009 Great Britain and Ireland floods]] || Strong winds and heavy rain across the United Kingdom with the worst flooding concentrated in [[Cumbria]]. Four people were killed as a direct result of the flooding.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/topics/weather/6616406/Cumbria-floods-residents-braced-for-more-rain-over-weekend.html|title=Cumbria floods|publisher=Daily Telegraph|accessdate=20 November 2009 | location=London | first1=Aislinn | last1=Laing | first2=Paul | last2=Stokes | first3=Nigel | last3=Bunyan | date=20 November 2009}}</ref>\n|-\n|2009 || style=\"background: rgb(255,255,255)\" | [[February 2009 Great Britain and Ireland snowfall]]||There was {{convert|55|cm|abbr=on}} of snow causing several deaths and an estimated \u00a31.3 billion in damages\n|-\n|2009-10|| style=\"background: rgb(255,255,255)\" | [[Winter of 2009\u201310 in Great Britain and Ireland|Winter of 2009\u201310]]||Reported to be the coldest weather since 1987. About 22 people died.\n|-\n| 2010-11 || style=\"background: rgb(255,255,255)\" | [[Winter of 2010\u201311 in Great Britain and Ireland|Winter of 2010-11]] ||The winter of 2010\u20132011 was a weather event that brought heavy snowfalls, record low temperatures, travel chaos and school disruption to the islands of Britain and Ireland. It included the UK's coldest December since Met Office records began in 1910, with a mean temperature of {{convert|-1|C}}, breaking the previous record of {{convert|0.1|C}} in December 1981.\n|-\n| 2012 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[2012 Great Britain and Ireland floods]] || A series of low pressure systems steered by the [[jet stream]] bring the wettest April in 100 years, and flooding across Britain and Ireland. Continuing through May and leading to the wettest beginning to June in 150 years, with flooding and extreme events occurring periodically throughout Britain and parts of [[Western Europe]]. On 9 June, severe flooding began around [[Aberystwyth]], [[West Wales]] with people evacuated from two holiday parks. 150 people saved by lifeboats with {{convert|4|-|5|ft|abbr=on}} of water. On 28 June, a large [[low-pressure area]] moved across [[Northern Ireland]]. Its [[Weather front|fronts]] brought heavy rain and large hail to many areas in England. One man died from the storm.\n|-\n| 2013 || style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | [[St. Jude storm]] || Torrential rain and winds of up to {{convert|100|mph|abbr=on}} hit the south of England and Wales. 600,000 homes were left without power, and 5 people were killed. In Europe another 6 people were killed by the same storm.\n|-\n|2013 || style=\"background: rgb(255,225,225)\" | [[2013 Great Britain and Ireland heat wave]]||An extra 760 deaths were reported in the UK. In Ireland the heat wave indirectly caused 30 deaths by drowning.\n|-\n| 2013 || style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | [[Cyclone Xaver|2013 East Coast Tidal Surge]] || On 5 December 2013 a large depression that passed eastwards over Scotland brought strong northerly winds along the eastern coast of Britain. This coincided with the spring tide and caused a large [[Storm surge|tidal surge]] to affect large swathes of the east coast. Many settlements along the coast were severely flooded, with sea defences breached in many locations.\n|-\n| 2013-2014 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[2013\u201314 United Kingdom winter floods|Winter Storms of 2013-14]] || During the winter of 2013\u201314 the British Isles were in the path of several winter storms, which culminated in serious coastal damage and widespread persistent flooding. The storms brought the greatest January rainfall in Southern England since at least the year records began in 1910. The season saw persistent [[Winter flooding of 2013\u201314 on the Somerset Levels|flooding on the Somerset Levels]] with recurrent [[fluvial]] flooding in Southern England of the non-tidal [[River Thames|Thames]], [[River Severn|Severn]] and in [[Kent]], [[Sussex]] and [[Hampshire]] and the [[River Stour, Dorset|Stour]] in [[Dorset]]. Briefer coastal flooding and wave battering damage took place in exposed parts of Dorset, Devon and Cornwall.\n|-\n| 2015 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[2015\u201316 Great Britain and Ireland floods]] || Flooding in Cumbria, Yorkshire, southern Scotland and parts of Ireland.\n|-\n| 2017 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[Hurricane Ophelia (2017)|Hurricane Ophelia]] || During the autumn of 2017, Ireland and the United Kingdom were hit by Hurricane Ophelia, which had completed its transition into an extratropical cyclone shortly before its landfall in Ireland and subjected the island to hurricane-force winds. Three people were killed by fallen trees in Ireland and 22,000 people were left without electricity. This also cut off internet for some households across the UK.\n|-\n|2018\n|[[2018 Great Britain and Ireland cold wave|2018 Great Britain and Ireland Cold Wave]]\n|Britain and Ireland were struck by a cold wave which began on the 22nd February and would affect most of Europe. Officially named Anticyclone Hartmut, the cold wave brought unusually low temperatures and heavy snowfall to the UK and would later combine with [[Storm Emma (2018)|Storm Emma]] which would make landfall over South West England and Southern Ireland on the 2nd March. The lowest temperature recorded was -14.7 degrees Celsius in [[Cairn Gorm]]. The cold spell was nicknamed \u2018''the Beast from the East''\u2019. 17 people in total died from this cold wave, with 95 casualties across Europe. This spell of cold weather cost \u00a31.2 billion in damages.\n|-\n| 2018 || style=\"background: rgb(255,225,225)\" | [[2018 British Isles heat wave|Drought and Heatwave]] || Summer 2018 was the fifth hottest in the CET records back to 1659, with the period May\u2013July being the hottest such period on record.<ref>https://www.metoffice.gov.uk/hadobs/hadcet/mly_cet_mean_sort.txt</ref> During this period there was very little rainfall, with particularly low totals in North West England and South East England. Some places had more than 54 consecutive days without rainfall.<ref>https://www.msn.com/en-gb/news/newslondon/uk-heatwave-parts-of-the-country-have-no-rain-for-54-days-in-scorching-start-to-summer/ar-BBL0B7U</ref> This led to the [[2018 United Kingdom wildfires]]. The dry weather continued into the autumn, with most places seeing less than 90% of average rainfall between September and November.<ref>https://www.metoffice.gov.uk/public/weather/climate-anomalies/#?tab=climateAnomalies</ref> By November 2018, Northern England, the Northern Midlands, Eastern England and some parts of East Anglia were still ranked as 'severely dry'.<ref>https://eip.ceh.ac.uk/apps/droughts/</ref>\n|-\n| 2018 || style=\"background: rgb(255,225,225)\" | [[2018 United Kingdom wildfires]] || From June 2018, many destructive wildfires struck the United Kingdom, with the most prolonged and severe of these being in [[England]], with some fires burning for over a month.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/topics/cq5p6wx822pt/england-moor-fires</ref> \n|-\n| 2019\u201320 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[2019\u201320 United Kingdom floods]] || Flooding in much of England in November. 2019 was the wettest year on record across parts of the Midlands, Central and Northern England.<ref>https://www.metoffice.gov.uk/research/climate/maps-and-data/uk-actual-and-anomaly-maps</ref> [[Storm Ciara]] and [[Storm Dennis]] caused more flooding in February.\n|-\n| 2020 || style=\"background: rgb(210,255,210)\" | [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] || Outbreak of [[SARS-CoV-2]], originating in [[China]]. 16 cases reported as of 27 February.<ref name=EveningStandard>{{Cite news|last=Team|first=Evening Standard|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/world/coronavirus-news-live-covid19-europe-uk-latest-a4372836.html|title=Coronavirus news LIVE: Number of UK patients hits 16 as Northern Ireland confirms first case|date=27 February 2020|work=The Telegraph|access-date=27 February 2020|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n|- POO MAKE IT STOP\n\n\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of disasters in Great Britain and Ireland by death toll]]\n*[[Climate of the United Kingdom]]\n*[[Geology of Great Britain]]\n*[[Geology of Ireland]]\n*[[Tsunamis affecting the British Isles]]\n*[[Drought in the United Kingdom]]\n*[[List of floods#United Kingdom|Floods in the United Kingdom]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of Natural Disasters In The British Isles}}\n[[Category:Natural disasters in the United Kingdom| List]]\n[[Category:Lists of disasters in the United Kingdom|Natural disasters]]\n[[Category:British Isles-related lists|Natural disasters]]\n[[Category:Lists of disasters in Ireland|Natural]]\n[[Category:Ireland history-related lists|Disasters]]\n[[Category:Natural disasters in Ireland|Nat]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2013}}\n{{More citations needed|date=July 2007}}\nThis is a '''list of [[natural disaster]]s in [[Great Britain]] and [[Ireland]]'''.\n\n== List of natural disasters to have affected the British Isles, ordered chronologically ==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"; margin: 0 0 0.5em 1em; padding: 0.5em; border: 1px solid #ddb; width: 250px; font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! Colour scheme used in this table:\n|-\n| style=\"background: rgb(245,222,179)\" | Geological event\n|-\n| style=\"background: rgb(255,255,255)\" | Cold weather event\n|-\n| style=\"background: rgb(255,225,225)\" | Hot weather event\n|-\n| style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | High winds event\n|-\n| style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | Wet weather event\n|-\n| style=\"background: rgb(255,250,205)\" | Famine\n|-\n| style=\"background: rgb(210,255,210)\" | Sickness epidemic\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Disaster event\n! Notes; disaster type, people killed, region affected, etc.\n|-\n|[[Paleolithic|70,000-75,000 ybp]] || style=\"background: rgb(245,222,179)\" | Prolonged [[volcanic winter]] || Long lasting volcanic winters following the [[Toba catastrophe theory|Toba catastrophe]] have been hypothesised to have killed every human not living in Africa at the time.\n|-\n| [[7th millennium BC|6100 BC]] || style=\"background: rgb(245,222,179)\" | Tsunami || Caused by the [[Storegga Slide]], struck east [[Scotland]] with {{convert|70|ft|adj=on}} wave after undersea landslip off [[Norway]].\n|-\n| 535-536 || style=\"background: rgb(255,255,255)\" | [[Extreme weather events of 535\u2013536]] || The most severe cooling in the [[Northern Hemisphere]] in the last 2,000 years, likely caused crop failures and freezing for the [[Anglo-Saxons]].\n|-\n| 10th century || style=\"background: rgb(255,225,225)\" | Regular heatwaves || Extended droughts with regularity: also through the period summers lasted half a year and were often warm or very warm - some notably extreme summers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://booty.org.uk/booty.weather/climate/751_999.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170127142441/http://booty.org.uk/booty.weather/climate/751_999.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=2017-01-27|title=751_999|work=booty.org.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1091 || style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | [[London tornado of 1091]] || 2 deaths, the early [[London Bridge]], 600 houses, many churches (inc. [[St Mary-le-Bow]])\n|-\n| 1235 || style=\"background: rgb(255,250,205)\" | Famine || England; 20,000 die in London alone<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/personal-view/3609390/Poor-studies-will-always-be-with-us.html | work=The Daily Telegraph | location=London | title=Poor studies will always be with us | first=James | last=Bartholomew | date=8 August 2004 | accessdate=8 May 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1252-1253 || style=\"background: rgb(255,225,225)\" | Both dry years and excessive heat || Considered by some (e.g. Brooks), as the driest pair of consecutive years known in the record. The summer (and possibly the spring in London/south) of 1252 was outstandingly dry/hot, with the ensuing drought ruining crops and many people died from the excessive heat. Spring/summer 1253 was also noted as dry/hot London/south.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://booty.org.uk/booty.weather/climate/1200_1299.htm|title=1200_1299|work=booty.org.uk|access-date=9 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140325235004/http://booty.org.uk/booty.weather/climate/1200_1299.htm|archive-date=25 March 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1287 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[St. Lucia's flood]] || Not known by that name the flood killed hundreds in England. This flood along with the [[South England flood of February 1287]] contributed to the decline of [[Dunwich]] as a major port\n|-\n| 1315-1317 || style=\"background: rgb(255,250,205)\" | [[Great Famine of 1315\u20131317]] || Throughout Europe\n|-\n| 1324 || style=\"background: rgb(255,225,225)\" | 10 years of hot summers || Drought in summer (London/south). Possibly the start of ten or so years of warm, often dry summers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://booty.org.uk/booty.weather/climate/1300_1399.htm|title=1300_1399|work=booty.org.uk|access-date=9 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140326042326/http://booty.org.uk/booty.weather/climate/1300_1399.htm|archive-date=26 March 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1348-1350s || style=\"background: rgb(210,255,210)\" | [[Black Death in England]] || Killed somewhere around 50% of the population\n|-\n| 1360s || style=\"background: rgb(210,255,210)\" | [[Black Death in England]] || Killed a further 20% of the population\n|-\n| 1485\u20131551 || style=\"background: rgb(210,255,210)\" | [[Sweating sickness]] || Sporadic outbreaks kill many thousands\n|-\n| 1540-41 || style=\"background: rgb(255,225,225)\" | Great heat and drought || Dry, in 1538\u201339. In 1540\u201341, the [[River Thames]] was so low that [[seawater]] extended above [[London Bridge]]. Reports at the time suggest that there were many deaths due to the 'Ague', and 1540 is described in contemporary chronicles as the 'Big Sun Year'.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://booty.org.uk/booty.weather/climate/1500_1599.htm|title=1500_1599|work=booty.org.uk|access-date=9 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140326054338/http://booty.org.uk/booty.weather/climate/1500_1599.htm|archive-date=26 March 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1580 || style=\"background: rgb(245,222,179)\" | [[1580 Dover Straits earthquake]] || Estimated to have been 5.3\u20135.9 [[Richter magnitude scale|M<sub>L</sub>]]. Two deaths in England.\n|-\n| 1607 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[Bristol Channel floods, 1607]] || 30 January 1607 (possible [[tsunami]]). Flooding in the [[Bristol Channel]] hit [[Carmarthenshire]], [[Glamorgan]], [[Monmouthshire (historic)|Monmouthshire]], [[Devon]], and [[Somerset]]\n|-\n| 1623-24 || style=\"background: rgb(255,250,205)\" | Famine || Said to be the last peace-time famine in England\n|-\n| 1638 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[The Great Thunderstorm]] || [[Widecombe-in-the-Moor]], Devon, four killed and sixty injured\n|-\n| 1651-1653 || style=\"background: rgb(255,250,205)\" | Famine || Famine throughout much of [[Ireland]] during the [[Cromwellian conquest of Ireland, brought on by the \"scorched earth policy\" whereby Cromwell ordered his troops to burn all food crops so as to starve the population. This was part of his genocidal campaign in Ireland and not a natural disaster.#Guerrilla warfare, famine and plague|Cromwellian conquest of Ireland]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/northernireland/ashorthistory/archive/intro99.shtml|title=BBC iPlayer - Northern Ireland - A Short History|work=bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1665 || style=\"background: rgb(210,255,210)\" | [[Great Plague of London]] || [[Bubonic plague]] killed an estimated 100,000 people, 20% of London's population\n|-\n| 1665 || style=\"background: rgb(210,255,210)\" | [[Derby plague of 1665]] || The [[bubonic plague]] spread north, but was stalled by the famous quarantine of [[Eyam]]\n|-\n| 1665-66|| style=\"background: rgb(255,225,225)\" | Long drought followed by a hot summer || Every month from November 1665 to September 1666 was dry. The climatological summer (June, July and August) of 1666 was amongst the top 10 or so of warm summers in the Central English Temperatures (CET) series (began 1659). CET also suggests that July 1666 had a mean value of {{convert|18|C}}, and August was {{convert|17|C}}. The heat and long drought added to a heightened risk of fire in populated areas. Lack of rain and hot temperatures helped spark the [[Great Fire of London]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://booty.org.uk/booty.weather/climate/1650_1699.htm|title=1650_1699|work=booty.org.uk|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140325222440/http://booty.org.uk/booty.weather/climate/1650_1699.htm|archivedate=25 March 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> As a result, this year saw an end to the [[Great Plague of London]] due to extreme heat and fire.\n|-\n| 1690s || style=\"background: rgb(255,250,205)\" | Famine ||| Known as the [[seven ill years]] it occurred throughout Scotland, killing 15% of the population\n|-\n| 1703 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[Great Storm of 1703]] || Up to 15,000 deaths, ships lost, mass damage to buildings and trees\n|-\n| 16th-18th centuries || style=\"background: rgb(255,255,255)\" | [[Little Ice Age]] || Long-lasting period of lower-than-normal average temperatures\n|-\n| 1709 || style=\"background: rgb(255,255,255)\" | [[Great Frost of 1709]] || Extremely cold winter, temperatures as low as {{convert|-12|C}} on 5 January\n|-\n| 1729 || style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | Tornado || [[Bexhill-on-Sea]] struck by a waterspout that came ashore\n|-\n| 1740 || style=\"background: rgb(255,250,205)\" | [[Irish Famine (1740\u201341)]] || Somewhere between 310,000 and 480,000 people starve in Ireland due to cold weather affecting harvests\n|-\n| 1755 || style=\"background: rgb(245,222,179)\" | Tsunami || Following the [[1755 Lisbon earthquake|Lisbon earthquake]], [[Cornwall]] was struck by a {{convert|10|ft|abbr=on}} wave\n|-\n| 1770 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | Flooding and storms || In August throughout southern England. A flood was thought to have occurred in [[Lynmouth]], Devon in 1769 and the date may have transposed to 1796.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1002/j.1477-8696.2001.tb06504.x | volume=56 | issue=10 | title=Great storms and floods over southern England, August 1770 | year=2001 | journal=Weather | pages=327\u2013337 | last1 = Clark | first1 = C.| bibcode=2001Wthr...56..327C }}</ref>\n|-\n| 1783 || style=\"background: rgb(245,222,179)\" | \"[[Laki]] haze\" || [[Sulfur dioxide|Sulphurous gas]] from an eruption in [[Iceland]] suffocates more than 10,000 in Britain,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/3745749.stm Volcano 'drove up UK death toll']</ref> followed by about 8,000 deaths in winter\n|-\n| 1816 || style=\"background: rgb(245,222,179)\" | [[Year Without a Summer]] || Caused by the [[1815 eruption of Mount Tambora]], crops devastated, unknown thousands die\n|-\n| 1816-1819 || style=\"background: rgb(210,255,210)\" | [[Typhus]] epidemic || Ireland\n|-\n| 1831-50 || style=\"background: rgb(210,255,210)\" | [[Cholera]] pandemic || Part of the [[1829\u20131851 cholera pandemic]], beginning in London, 55,000 die in outbreaks across England and Wales\n|-\n| 1836 || style=\"background: rgb(245,222,179)\" | [[Lewes avalanche]] || [[Lewes]], the only major avalanche recorded in [[England]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.theargus.co.uk/2006/12/27/223771.html |title=Avalanche anniversary in Lewes pub |accessdate=18 May 2009 |publisher=The Argus |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929083407/http://archive.theargus.co.uk/2006/12/27/223771.html |archivedate=29 September 2007 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/southerncounties/nature/wtt/03.shtml|title=Radicals and Rebels - Stage 3|publisher=[[BBC]]|\naccessdate=18 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/insideout/south/series1/weird-weather.shtml|title=Inside Out - South: Monday 7th October, 2002|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=18 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.999lewes.com/ | title=About Lewes|date=May 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928225805/http://www.999lewes.com/| archive-date =28 September 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n|1839 || style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | [[Night of the Big Wind]]|| A [[European windstorm]] swept across Ireland causing hundreds of deaths and severe damage to property. Gusts were over {{convert|100|kn|lk=in}}\n|-\n| 1840s || style=\"background: rgb(255,250,205)\" | [[Great Famine (Ireland)|Great Irish Famine]] || [[Phytophthora infestans|Potato blight]] devastates food sources. Killed around 1 million people out of a total population of 8 million\n\n|-\n| 1840s || style=\"background: rgb(255,250,205)\" | [[Highland Potato Famine]] || Another starvation event, similar to the one directly above but in Scotland and with very few deaths. However, 200,000 were said to have emigrated.\n|-\n| 1848 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[Moray Firth fishing disaster]] || 100 fishermen and 124 boats lost at sea during a storm in [[Scotland]]\n|-\n| 1852 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[Holmfirth floods|Holmfirth Flood]] || [[River Holme|Bilberry Reservoir]] embankment collapses, causing 81 deaths and a large amount of damage to property.\n|-\n| 1859 || style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\"  | [[Royal Charter Storm]]||Named for the ''[[Royal Charter (ship)|Royal Charter]]'' the storm, which lasted for two days, sank 133 ships killing 800.\n|-\n| 1864 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[Great Sheffield Flood]] || [[Dale Dike Reservoir]] bursts, destroying 800 houses and killing 270 people. (not strictly a natural disaster because it was structural failure caused by human error)\n|-\n| 1871 || style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | [[Great Gale of 1871]] || Occurring in the North Sea on Friday 10 February 1871 it killed at least 50 people.\n|-\n|1879 ||style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | [[Tay Bridge disaster]] || A European windstorm on 28 December 1879 caused the [[Tay Rail Bridge]] to collapse killing between 60 and 75 people.\n|-\n| 1881 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[Eyemouth disaster]] || 189 fishermen died during a storm in [[Scotland]]\n|-\n| 1881 || style=\"background: rgb(255,255,255)\" | [[Blizzard of January 1881]] || Around 100 die in one of the most severe [[blizzard]]s ever to hit the southern parts of the United Kingdom\n|-\n| 1884 || style=\"background: rgb(245,222,179)\" | [[1884 Colchester earthquake]] || Several people killed, and 1200 buildings destroyed in [[Essex]]\n|-\n|1894-95 || style=\"background: rgb(255,255,255)\" | [[Winter of 1894\u201395 in the United Kingdom]]|| Conditions were such that many people died of [[hypothermia]] or respiratory conditions\n|-\n|1911 || style=\"background: rgb(255,225,225)\" | [[1911 United Kingdom heat wave]] || Heat wave lasted from early July to mid-September. Newspapers ran deaths by heat columns\n|-\n| 1918-19 || style=\"background: rgb(210,255,210)\" | [[1918 flu pandemic]] || Worldwide [[influenza pandemic]] nicknamed the Spanish flu\n|-\n| 1928 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[1928 Thames flood]] || A disastrous flood of the River Thames in London. 14 drowned and thousands made homeless.\n|-\n| 1931 || style=\"background: rgb(245,222,179)\" | [[1931 Dogger Bank earthquake]] || At 6.1 on the Richter Scale, was the largest earthquake in British history, but caused only minor damage as was offshore.\n|-\n| 1946-47 || style=\"background: rgb(255,255,255)\" | [[Winter of 1946\u201347 in the United Kingdom|Winter of 1946&ndash;1947]] || Right after WWII, blizzards block roads and cause blackouts, resulting in industrial stagnation. Followed by heavy flooding in March, causing \u00a3250\u2013375 million of damage.\n|-\n| 1952 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[Lynmouth Flood|Lynmouth flood of 1952]] || 34 people were killed, with a further 420 made homeless. Over 100 buildings were destroyed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/august/16/newsid_2960000/2960180.stm|title=On This Day: 1952: Flood devastates Devon village|accessdate=18 May 2009|publisher=[[BBC]] | date=16 August 1952}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1516880.stm|title=Rain-making link to killer floods|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=18 May 2009 | date=30 August 2001}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exmoor-nationalpark.gov.uk/the_lynmouth_floods_of_1952_exmoor|title=The 1952 Flood Disaster in Context|publisher=Exmoor National Park|accessdate=18 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/devon/news_features/2002/lynmouth_flood.shtml|title=Lynmouth flood disaster|last=Joint|first=Laura|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=18 May 2009}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1953 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[North Sea flood of 1953]] || 307 were killed in the United Kingdom, in the counties of [[Lincolnshire]], [[Norfolk]], [[Suffolk]] and [[Essex]].\n|-\n| 1955 || style=\"background: rgb(255,225,225)\" |[[1955 United Kingdom heat wave]] || Heat wave and drought throughout the country.\n|-\n| 1962-63 || style=\"background: rgb(255,255,255)\" | [[Winter of 1962\u201363 in the United Kingdom|Winter of 1962\u20131963]] || Coldest winter for hundreds of years, temperatures as low as {{convert|-16|C}}.\n|-\n| 1968 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\"  | [[July 1968 England and Wales dust fall storms]] || Dust from the Sahara desert causes extremely heavy rain and hail, causing widespread damage across Wales and western and northern England.\n|-\n| 1968 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[Great Flood of 1968]] || Flooding causes extensive damage to [[Southern England]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Hundreds homeless after flood havoc|work=[[The Times]]|page=1|date=16 September 1968}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1968 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[1968 Scotland storm|1968 Hurricane]] || Hurricane-force winds cause 20 deaths in the [[Central Belt]] of Scotland. In Glasgow alone, over 300 houses were destroyed and 70,000 homes were damaged. Electrical power also failed in Glasgow, leaving the whole city in darkness. In total the storm felled 8,000 hectares of forest across Scotland (1.6 million cubic metres of timber). The storm, which affected Northern England, Scotland and N. Ireland received little attention from the BBC or the national press.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1968/feb/07/scotland-storm-damage?lang=_e|title=Hansard: SCOTLAND (STORM DAMAGE)}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1976 || style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | [[Gale of January 1976]] || The gale of 2\u20135 January resulted in severe wind damage across western and central Europe and coastal flooding around the southern [[North Sea]] coasts. At the time, this was the most severe storm over the [[British Isles]].\n|-\n| 1974-1976|| style=\"background: rgb(255,225,225)\" | Two-year drought and [[1976 United Kingdom heat wave|UK heat wave]] || 1974-1975 had the mildest winter in England and Wales since 1869. However, during the first few days of June 1975, in and around London snow and [[Rain and snow mixed|sleet]] occurred. During the next week maximum temperatures of {{convert|27|C}} were recorded each day across the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://booty.org.uk/booty.weather/climate/1975_1999.htm|title=1975 - 1999|work=booty.org.uk|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003053817/http://booty.org.uk/booty.weather/climate/1975_1999.htm|archivedate=3 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The summer of 1976 experienced 5 days of temperatures exceeding {{convert|35|C}} somewhere in the UK. Between 23 June to 7 July, temperatures in London and other parts of Southern England reached above {{convert|32|C}} for 15 consecutive days. The weather was settled and temperatures were above average, with many short and long periods of above {{convert|30|C|F|0}} heat, between mid June to mid September. In 1976, the country suffered forest fires, grass fires and water shortages. Summer 1976 was followed by an extremely unsettled Autumn.\n|-\n| 1978 || style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | [[1978 North Sea storm surge]] || A storm surge which occurred over 11\u201312 January caused extensive coastal flooding and considerable damage on the east coast of England between the [[Humber]] and [[Kent]]. Locally severe flooding occurred in Lincolnshire, [[The Wash]], north Norfolk and Kent. Improvements in flood protection following the devastating flood of 1953 meant that the catastrophic losses seen during that storm were not repeated. The storm caused severe damage to many piers along the east coast of England.\n|-\n| 1987 || style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | [[Great Storm of 1987]] || After [[Michael Fish]] famously forecast \"very windy\" weather mainly over France, an unusually strong storm occurred in October 1987, with wind speeds widely over {{convert|100|mph|abbr=on}} along England's southern coastline, and which killed 18 people in England. The great storm caused substantial damage over much of Southern England, downing an estimated 15 million trees (including six of the seven eponymous oaks in [[Sevenoaks]]).\n|-\n| 1990 || style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | [[Burns' Day Storm]] || Winds of up to {{convert|100|mph|abbr=on}} kill 97 people and cause \u00a33.37 billion worth of damage, the most costly weather event for insurers in British history.\n|-\n|1990-91|| style=\"background: rgb(255,255,255)\" | [[Winter of 1990\u201391 in Western Europe|Winter of 1990\u201391]]|| Lasting from December 1990 to February 1991 throughout the United Kingdom, Ireland and Western Europe. About 42 people died, almost all in the UK and Ireland\n|-\n| 1998 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[Easter 1998 United Kingdom floods|1998 Easter floods]] || At the start of Easter 1998 (9\u201310 April) a stationary band of heavy rain affected [[the Midlands]]. This resulted in floods in which five people died and thousands had to be evacuated from their homes. The wettest area, with over {{Convert|75|mm|abbr=on}}, stretched from [[Worcestershire]] towards [[The Wash]] and the flooded towns included [[Evesham]], [[Royal Leamington Spa|Leamington Spa]], [[Stratford-upon-Avon]], [[Bedford]], [[Northampton]] and [[Huntingdon]]. On [[Maundy Thursday]] (9 April), thundery rain in the south of England moved northwards and became slow-moving from [[East Anglia]] through the Midlands to [[north Wales]]. This band gave some very heavy downpours with hail and thunder. On [[Good Friday]] (10th) the band rotated slowly anticlockwise spreading to Lincolnshire and the [[West Country]] and continued to rotate, with sleet and heavy bursts of rain in places. There was sleet and snow across the [[Pennines]] and north Wales during the evening.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/interesting/easter1998|title = Easter 1998 floods|date = 25 October 2012|publisher = M.W. Horner and P.D. Walsh}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2000 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[Autumn 2000 Western Europe floods|Flooding]] || Severe flooding in many parts of the UK. Among the worst hit were [[York]], [[Kent]], [[Sussex]], [[Shrewsbury]], [[Lewes]], [[Uckfield]] and [[Maidstone]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/weather/features/flood_facts.shtml|title=BBC Weather: Flood Facts|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=18 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Dead link|url=http://www.defra.gov.uk/environ/fcd/floodincidents/2000flood.htm|date=May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/commondata/acrobat/126637|title=Lessons Learned: Autumn 2000 floods|accessdate=18 May 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927182913/http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/commondata/acrobat/126637|archivedate=27 September 2007|format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/southerncounties/nature/wtt/03.shtml|title=Southern Counties > Nature > Walks > Lewes - Radicals and Rebels > Stage 3|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=18 May 2009}}{{Failed verification|date=May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cfspress.com/Kelman-UK-Floods.pdf|title=The Autumn 2000 Floods in England|last=Kelman|first=Ilan|publisher=The Martin Centre, University of Cambridge|year=2002|accessdate=18 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rms.com/Publications/UKFLOODS_OCT13-14.pdf|title=U.K. Floods, October 13\u201314, 2000: Examination of U.K. Flood Damage During Increased Rainfall in October 2000|publisher=Risk Management Solutions|accessdate=18 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastsussex.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/00016FE4-50D0-4AD8-99BB-BB06D7BEEF22/0/lewesflood.pdf|title=THE LEWES FLOOD OF OCTOBER 2000|accessdate=18 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lewes.gov.uk/Files/env_floodreport.pdf|title=Flood Report: March 2001|publisher=Environment Agency|accessdate=18 May 2009 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060519120319/http://www.lewes.gov.uk/Files/env_floodreport.pdf |archivedate = 19 May 2006}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/interesting/autumn2000.html|title=The wet autumn of 2000|website=Met Office|access-date=2017-02-14}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2002 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[2002 Glasgow floods]] || 200 people immediately evacuated, but the water supply of 140 thousand people was affected.\n|-\n| 2003 || style=\"background: rgb(255,225,225)\" | [[2003 European heat wave]] || More than 2,000 people may have died in the UK alone as a result of the hottest summer recorded in Europe since 1540. Temperatures remained above {{convert|30|C}} for 10 days, between 3 and 13 August. The highest temperature known and accepted was recorded at [[Faversham|Faversham, Kent]] on 10 August when it reached {{convert|38.5|C}}. The death toll across Europe as a result of the heatwave was eventually estimated at 70000.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Robine|first=Jean-Marie|last2=Cheung|first2=Siu Lan K.|last3=Le Roy|first3=Sophie|last4=Van Oyen|first4=Herman|last5=Griffiths|first5=Clare|last6=Michel|first6=Jean-Pierre|last7=Herrmann|first7=Fran\u00e7ois Richard|date=February 2008|title=Death toll exceeded 70,000 in Europe during the summer of 2003|journal=Comptes Rendus Biologies|volume=331|issue=2|pages=171\u2013178|doi=10.1016/j.crvi.2007.12.001|pmid=18241810}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2004 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[Boscastle flood of 2004]] || [[Boscastle]] and [[Crackington Haven]], two villages in [[Cornwall]], were heavily damaged due to flash floods.\n|-\n| 2005 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | Flooding || [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]], 8 January 2005<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cumbria/history/features/cumbrian_floods/index.shtml|title=Archive: Cumbrian Floods|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=18 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/regions/northwest/942672/?lang=_e|title=Cumbria floods|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080104031143/http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/regions/northwest/942672/?lang=_e|archivedate=4 January 2008|accessdate=18 May 2009}}</ref> See [[Cyclone Gudrun]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Windstorm Erwin / Gudrun \u2013 January 2005 |url=http://www.dmi.dk/dmi/8januarstormguycarprapport.pdf |publisher=Guy Carpenter |accessdate=23 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415064808/http://www.dmi.dk/dmi/8januarstormguycarprapport.pdf |archivedate=15 April 2012 }}</ref>\n|-\n| 2005 || style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | [[Birmingham tornado of 2005|Birmingham Tornado]] || 30 injuries caused by the tornado, which uprooted trees, destroyed roofs and picked up cars, causing \u00a340 million in damages.\n|-\n| 2006 || style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | [[2006 London tornado|London Tornado]] || Only one injury, but \u00a310 million of damage caused.\n|-\n| 2007 || style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | [[Cyclone Kyrill|Storm Kyrill]] || Hurricane-force winds across British Isles, at least 11 people dead\n|-\n| 2007 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[2007 United Kingdom floods]] || Killed 13 people. [[Gloucestershire]] suffers many road and rail closures, power cuts and evacuations, with 420,000 inhabitants left without drinking water requiring emergency assistance from the army. Other areas heavily affected include [[Yorkshire]], [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]] and [[Worcestershire]]. The disaster is estimated to have caused \u00a36 billion of damage.\n|-\n|2008|| style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\"  | [[2008 Irish flash floods]]||Flash floods throughout August lead to one death and the destruction of 50 houses.\n|-\n| 2008 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[2008 Morpeth floods]] || [[River Wansbeck]] bursts its banks causing damage to 995 properties costing \u00a340 million. Flooding across the Midlands and [[North East England]] associated with a slow moving front of the low pressure system Mattea.<ref>{{cite web|title=England struck by flash flooding|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/7602110.stm|publisher=BBC|accessdate=23 May 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|2009|| style=\"background: rgb(245,222,179)\" |[[2009 Buachaille Etive M\u00f2r avalanche]]|| An avalanche on [[Buachaille Etive M\u00f2r]] in [[Glen Coe]] in the [[Scottish Highlands]], [[United Kingdom|UK]], on 24 January 2009 killed three climbers and injured another.\n|-\n| 2009 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[2009 Great Britain and Ireland floods]] || Strong winds and heavy rain across the United Kingdom with the worst flooding concentrated in [[Cumbria]]. Four people were killed as a direct result of the flooding.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/topics/weather/6616406/Cumbria-floods-residents-braced-for-more-rain-over-weekend.html|title=Cumbria floods|publisher=Daily Telegraph|accessdate=20 November 2009 | location=London | first1=Aislinn | last1=Laing | first2=Paul | last2=Stokes | first3=Nigel | last3=Bunyan | date=20 November 2009}}</ref>\n|-\n|2009 || style=\"background: rgb(255,255,255)\" | [[February 2009 Great Britain and Ireland snowfall]]||There was {{convert|55|cm|abbr=on}} of snow causing several deaths and an estimated \u00a31.3 billion in damages\n|-\n|2009-10|| style=\"background: rgb(255,255,255)\" | [[Winter of 2009\u201310 in Great Britain and Ireland|Winter of 2009\u201310]]||Reported to be the coldest weather since 1987. About 22 people died.\n|-\n| 2010-11 || style=\"background: rgb(255,255,255)\" | [[Winter of 2010\u201311 in Great Britain and Ireland|Winter of 2010-11]] ||The winter of 2010\u20132011 was a weather event that brought heavy snowfalls, record low temperatures, travel chaos and school disruption to the islands of Britain and Ireland. It included the UK's coldest December since Met Office records began in 1910, with a mean temperature of {{convert|-1|C}}, breaking the previous record of {{convert|0.1|C}} in December 1981.\n|-\n| 2012 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[2012 Great Britain and Ireland floods]] || A series of low pressure systems steered by the [[jet stream]] bring the wettest April in 100 years, and flooding across Britain and Ireland. Continuing through May and leading to the wettest beginning to June in 150 years, with flooding and extreme events occurring periodically throughout Britain and parts of [[Western Europe]]. On 9 June, severe flooding began around [[Aberystwyth]], [[West Wales]] with people evacuated from two holiday parks. 150 people saved by lifeboats with {{convert|4|-|5|ft|abbr=on}} of water. On 28 June, a large [[low-pressure area]] moved across [[Northern Ireland]]. Its [[Weather front|fronts]] brought heavy rain and large hail to many areas in England. One man died from the storm.\n|-\n| 2013 || style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | [[St. Jude storm]] || Torrential rain and winds of up to {{convert|100|mph|abbr=on}} hit the south of England and Wales. 600,000 homes were left without power, and 5 people were killed. In Europe another 6 people were killed by the same storm.\n|-\n|2013 || style=\"background: rgb(255,225,225)\" | [[2013 Great Britain and Ireland heat wave]]||An extra 760 deaths were reported in the UK. In Ireland the heat wave indirectly caused 30 deaths by drowning.\n|-\n| 2013 || style=\"background: rgb(200,200,200)\" | [[Cyclone Xaver|2013 East Coast Tidal Surge]] || On 5 December 2013 a large depression that passed eastwards over Scotland brought strong northerly winds along the eastern coast of Britain. This coincided with the spring tide and caused a large [[Storm surge|tidal surge]] to affect large swathes of the east coast. Many settlements along the coast were severely flooded, with sea defences breached in many locations.\n|-\n| 2013-2014 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[2013\u201314 United Kingdom winter floods|Winter Storms of 2013-14]] || During the winter of 2013\u201314 the British Isles were in the path of several winter storms, which culminated in serious coastal damage and widespread persistent flooding. The storms brought the greatest January rainfall in Southern England since at least the year records began in 1910. The season saw persistent [[Winter flooding of 2013\u201314 on the Somerset Levels|flooding on the Somerset Levels]] with recurrent [[fluvial]] flooding in Southern England of the non-tidal [[River Thames|Thames]], [[River Severn|Severn]] and in [[Kent]], [[Sussex]] and [[Hampshire]] and the [[River Stour, Dorset|Stour]] in [[Dorset]]. Briefer coastal flooding and wave battering damage took place in exposed parts of Dorset, Devon and Cornwall.\n|-\n| 2015 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[2015\u201316 Great Britain and Ireland floods]] || Flooding in Cumbria, Yorkshire, southern Scotland and parts of Ireland.\n|-\n| 2017 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[Hurricane Ophelia (2017)|Hurricane Ophelia]] || During the autumn of 2017, Ireland and the United Kingdom were hit by Hurricane Ophelia, which had completed its transition into an extratropical cyclone shortly before its landfall in Ireland and subjected the island to hurricane-force winds. Three people were killed by fallen trees in Ireland and 22,000 people were left without electricity. This also cut off internet for some households across the UK.\n|-\n|2018\n|[[2018 Great Britain and Ireland cold wave|2018 Great Britain and Ireland Cold Wave]]\n|Britain and Ireland were struck by a cold wave which began on the 22nd February and would affect most of Europe. Officially named Anticyclone Hartmut, the cold wave brought unusually low temperatures and heavy snowfall to the UK and would later combine with [[Storm Emma (2018)|Storm Emma]] which would make landfall over South West England and Southern Ireland on the 2nd March. The lowest temperature recorded was -14.7 degrees Celsius in [[Cairn Gorm]]. The cold spell was nicknamed \u2018''the Beast from the East''\u2019. 17 people in total died from this cold wave, with 95 casualties across Europe. This spell of cold weather cost \u00a31.2 billion in damages.\n|-\n| 2018 || style=\"background: rgb(255,225,225)\" | [[2018 British Isles heat wave|Drought and Heatwave]] || Summer 2018 was the fifth hottest in the CET records back to 1659, with the period May\u2013July being the hottest such period on record.<ref>https://www.metoffice.gov.uk/hadobs/hadcet/mly_cet_mean_sort.txt</ref> During this period there was very little rainfall, with particularly low totals in North West England and South East England. Some places had more than 54 consecutive days without rainfall.<ref>https://www.msn.com/en-gb/news/newslondon/uk-heatwave-parts-of-the-country-have-no-rain-for-54-days-in-scorching-start-to-summer/ar-BBL0B7U</ref> This led to the [[2018 United Kingdom wildfires]]. The dry weather continued into the autumn, with most places seeing less than 90% of average rainfall between September and November.<ref>https://www.metoffice.gov.uk/public/weather/climate-anomalies/#?tab=climateAnomalies</ref> By November 2018, Northern England, the Northern Midlands, Eastern England and some parts of East Anglia were still ranked as 'severely dry'.<ref>https://eip.ceh.ac.uk/apps/droughts/</ref>\n|-\n| 2018 || style=\"background: rgb(255,225,225)\" | [[2018 United Kingdom wildfires]] || From June 2018, many destructive wildfires struck the United Kingdom, with the most prolonged and severe of these being in [[England]], with some fires burning for over a month.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/topics/cq5p6wx822pt/england-moor-fires</ref> \n|-\n| 2019\u201320 || style=\"background: rgb(225,225,255)\" | [[2019\u201320 United Kingdom floods]] || Flooding in much of England in November. 2019 was the wettest year on record across parts of the Midlands, Central and Northern England.<ref>https://www.metoffice.gov.uk/research/climate/maps-and-data/uk-actual-and-anomaly-maps</ref> [[Storm Ciara]] and [[Storm Dennis]] caused more flooding in February.\n|-\n| 2020 || style=\"background: rgb(210,255,210)\" | [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] || Outbreak of [[SARS-CoV-2]], originating in [[China]]. 16 cases reported as of 27 February.<ref name=EveningStandard>{{Cite news|last=Team|first=Evening Standard|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/world/coronavirus-news-live-covid19-europe-uk-latest-a4372836.html|title=Coronavirus news LIVE: Number of UK patients hits 16 as Northern Ireland confirms first case|date=27 February 2020|work=The Telegraph|access-date=27 February 2020|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of disasters in Great Britain and Ireland by death toll]]\n*[[Climate of the United Kingdom]]\n*[[Geology of Great Britain]]\n*[[Geology of Ireland]]\n*[[Tsunamis affecting the British Isles]]\n*[[Drought in the United Kingdom]]\n*[[List of floods#United Kingdom|Floods in the United Kingdom]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of Natural Disasters In The British Isles}}\n[[Category:Natural disasters in the United Kingdom| List]]\n[[Category:Lists of disasters in the United Kingdom|Natural disasters]]\n[[Category:British Isles-related lists|Natural disasters]]\n[[Category:Lists of disasters in Ireland|Natural]]\n[[Category:Ireland history-related lists|Disasters]]\n[[Category:Natural disasters in Ireland|Nat]]\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c6:d0a9:1a01:d190:5565:2e73:ae86", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eList of natural disasters to have affected the British Isles, ordered chronologically)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_natural_disasters_in_the_British_Isles"}
{"title_page": "Scotiabank Arena", "text_new": "{{about|the indoor sporting arena in Toronto|the arena in Calgary|Scotiabank Saddledome|the arena in Halifax, Nova Scotia|Scotiabank Centre|the arena in Ottawa formerly known as Scotiabank Place|Canadian Tire Centre}}\n{{Redirect|Air Canada Centre|the headquarters of Air Canada in Montreal|Air Canada#Headquarters}}\n{{short description|Indoor arena in Toronto, Ontario, Canada}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox venue\n| stadium_name = Scotiabank Arena\n| nickname = The Hanger<br  />The ACC\n| logo_image = [[File:Scotiabank Arena logo.svg|250px]]\n| image = [[File:Scotiabank Arena - 2018 (cropped).jpg|250px]]\n| caption = Exterior view of the arena in 2018\n| address = 40 [[Bay Street]]\n| location = [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|43|38|36|N|79|22|45|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|display=it}}\n| pushpin_map = Canada Toronto#Canada Ontario#Canada\n| pushpin_relief = yes\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in Toronto##Location in Ontario##Location in Canada\n| publictransit = {{rint|toronto|rail}} [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]]<br />{{rint|toronto|subway|1}} [[Union station (TTC)|Union subway station]]<br />{{rint|gotransit|bus}} [[Union Station Bus Terminal|GO Bus Terminal]]\n| broke_ground = March 12, 1997\n| opened = February 19, 1999\n| Acreage = {{convert|61780.5|m2|sqft|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4306707/air-canada-centre-gets-new-name/|title=Air Canada Centre sign removed on eve of facility becoming Scotiabank Arena|work=Global News|accessdate=September 27, 2018|publisher=Corus Entertainment Inc.|date=June 30, 2018}}</ref>\n| owner = [[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]]\n| operator = \n| former_names = Air Canada Centre<!-- This article uses Canadian English. \"Centre\" is the correct spelling in this case. --> {{small|(1999\u20132018)}}\n| construction_cost = {{CAD|265&nbsp;million}}<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.theaircanadacentre.com/corporate/CompanyFacts.asp|title=Company Facts|accessdate=August 29, 2017|publisher=Air Canada Centre}}</ref><ref name=cost/><br />(${{formatprice|{{Inflation|CA|265000000|1999}}}} in {{Inflation-year|CA}} dollars{{inflation-fn|CA}})\n| architect = Brisbin Brook Beynon Architects (Architect of Record)<br />[[Populous (company)|HOK Sport]]<br />(Consulting Architects)<ref>{{cite web |title=Clubhouse Confidential: When a Bunch of Alpha Males Get Together Daily in a Confined Space, Lots of Things\u2014Good and Bad\u2014Can Happen|first=Michael|last=Faber|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1024724/3/index.htm|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=January 14, 2002|accessdate=January 16, 2013}}</ref>\n| project_manager = Clarendon Projects Ltd.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clarendonprojects.com/aircanadacentre.html|title=Clarendon Projects \u2013 Air Canada Centre|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402151414/http://www.clarendonprojects.com/aircanadacentre.html|archivedate=April 2, 2012}}</ref>\n| structural engineer = [[Halcrow Group|Yolles Partnership Inc.]]<ref>[http://www.halcrow.com/Our-projects/Project-details/Air-Canada-Centre-Canada/ Halcrow Yolles \u2013 Air Canada Centre] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111026034118/http://halcrow.com/Our-projects/Project-details/Air-Canada-Centre-Canada/ |date=October 26, 2011 }}</ref>\n| services engineer = The Mitchell Partnership, Inc.<ref>[http://www.tmptoronto.com/document_library/Air%20Canada%20Centre.pdf The Mitchell Partnership \u2013 Air Canada Centre] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517115741/http://www.tmptoronto.com/document_library/Air%20Canada%20Centre.pdf |date=May 17, 2014 }}</ref>\n| general_contractor = [[PCL Construction|PCL Constructors Western, Inc.]]\n| tenants = [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] ([[National Hockey League|NHL]]) (1999\u2013present)<br />[[Toronto Raptors]] ([[National Basketball Association|NBA]]) (1999\u2013present)<br />[[Toronto Rock]] ([[National Lacrosse League|NLL]]) (2001\u2013present)<br />[[Toronto Phantoms]] ([[Arena Football League|AFL]]) (2001\u20132002)<br />[[Toronto Marlies]] ([[American Hockey League|AHL]]) (2010\u2013present, occasional home games)\n| seating_capacity = [[Basketball]]: 19,800 (20,511 with standing room)<br />[[Ice hockey|Hockey]]: 18,800 (20,270 with standing room)<br />[[Lacrosse]]: 18,800<br />[[Concert]]s: 19,800<br />[[Theatre]]: 5,200<ref>{{cite web|title=About|url=https://www.aircanadacentre.com/venue-information/about|publisher=Air Canada Centre|accessdate=May 10, 2018}}</ref>\n| parking = 2 underground levels for 212 vehicles<ref>https://canada.constructconnect.com/dcn/news/projects/2017/03/pcl-construction-reflects-on-building-the-air-canada-centre-1022273w</ref>\n| website = [https://www.scotiabankarena.com/ scotiabankarena.com]\n}}\n\n'''Scotiabank Arena''', formerly '''Air Canada Centre<!-- This article uses Canadian English. \"Centre\" is the correct spelling in this case. -->''', is a multi-purpose [[arena]] located on [[Bay Street]] in the [[South Core, Toronto|South Core]] district of [[Downtown Toronto|Downtown]] [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada. It is the home of the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL), the [[Toronto Raptors]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) and the [[Toronto Rock]] of the [[National Lacrosse League]] (NLL). In addition, the minor league [[Toronto Marlies]] of the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) and the [[Raptors 905]] of the [[NBA G League]] play occasional games at the arena. The arena was previously home to the [[Toronto Phantoms]] of the [[Arena Football League]] (AFL) during their brief existence.\n\nThe arena  is {{convert|61780.5|m2|sqft}} in size. It is owned and operated by [[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment|Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment Ltd.]] (MLSE), the same group that owns the Leafs and the Raptors, as well as their respective development teams. In 2018, Scotiabank Arena was the 13th busiest arena in the world and the busiest in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pollstar.com/Chart/2019/01/2018YearEndWorldwideTicketSalesTop200ArenaVenues_705.pdf|title=2018 YEAR END Worldwide Ticket Sales TOP 200 ARENA VENUES|publisher=[[Pollstar]]|date=2018|accessdate=June 22, 2019}}</ref> It is also the most photographed location in Canada on [[Instagram]] according to [[BuzzFeed]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/leafs/2018/07/01/scotiabank-arena-now-officially-the-home-of-maple-leafs-and-raptors.html|title=Scotiabank Arena now officially the home of Maple Leafs and Raptors - The Star|publisher=Toronto Star}}</ref> Scotiabank Arena is connected to [[Union Station (Toronto)|Toronto Union]] railway station, [[Union station (TTC)|subway station]] and [[Union Station Bus Terminal|bus terminal]] via the [[PATH (Toronto)|PATH]].\n\nScotiabank Arena has, from its initial design to completion, revolutionized many concepts included in new arenas and stadiums built since then.{{according to whom|date=October 2019}} These features include luxury suites accessible on the ground floor, splitting the main scoreboard into several sections, rotating all sponsor signage in the bowl at once (to allow dominant messaging or \"neutralization\" for events that disallow commercial advertising), and multiple restaurants in and out of the main arena bowl view.\n\nScotiabank Arena also hosts other events, such as concerts, political conventions and [[Esports|video game competitions]].\n\n==History==\n===Site History===\n[[File:Toronto in 1858.jpg|left|thumb|A map showing downtown Toronto in 1858]]The stadium is located on land that was once part of Toronto's inner harbour.  Infill of the inner harbour began in the 1850's and accelerated with the arrival of the railroad resulting in the current day shape of downtown <ref>https://www.cgenarchive.org/toronto-lakeshores.html</ref>.  By 1858 the site was located between two warfs (Rees & Tinnings Warf). As land was expanded southward, it remained under Government control as possible locations of various Union Station expansions.  The majority of the land was still part of the lake up until the early 1900's. By 1925 The northern parcel of the property was turned into of Bayside Park, which had been part of an early proposal that was to have seen the lands south of the rail corridor transformed into an extensive lakeside park that followed today's Esplande. The remaining land was most likely under the control of Central Harbor Terminals<ref>https://maps.library.utoronto.ca/dvhmp/maps.html</ref>.\n\nIn the 1930s the property became the proposed home to [[Canada Post]]'s Toronto Postal Delivery Building.  In the 1920's a postal handling facility already existed in the east wing of the city's then New Union Station (Downtown Toronto's 3rd major train station)<ref>{{cite book |last=Filey |first=Mike |author-link= |date=1992 |title=A Toronto Album 2: More Glimpses of the City That Was|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=K0tIsZ_TAIoC&pg=PA43 |location=Toronto |publisher=Dundurn Press |page=43 |isbn=}}</ref>. But it quickly reached capacity by the 1930s due to major population growth of Toronto and its surrounding region.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotiabankarena.com/venue-information/about/history|title=History {{!}} Scotiabank Arena|last=Arena|first=Scotiabank|website=www.scotiabankarena.com|language=en|access-date=November 15, 2018}}</ref>. In 1937 the Postmaster General appealed to the Minister of Public Works to approve a new replacement facility at the corner of Bay & Fleet Street (now Lake Shore Boulevard). Approval was granted by the federal Department of Public Works in part to stimulate the depression impacted construction industry<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://torontoplaques.com/Pages/Toronto_Postal_Delivery_Building.html|title=History|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2020</ref>. Design and construction of the warehouse built with steel & concrete would begin in 1938. Designed by [[Charles B. Dolphin]] it's a building that incorporates a combination of [[Art Deco]] and [[Art Moderne]] architectural style. The original building would be built for around $2,000,000 (CAD)<ref>{{cite book |last=Filey |first=Mike |author-link= |date=1992 |title=Toronto Sketches: The Way We Were |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=NNUAuL5S7gUC&pg=PA82 |location=Toronto |publisher=Dundurn Press |page=82 |isbn=}}</ref> [$ 35 million 2020],  The building was strategically located south of Union Station and was connected directly to the train platforms via an underground tunnel. Trains would be able to directly unload mail and move it directly to the mail sorting centre.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tayloronhistory.com/2013/02/12/torontos-architectural-gemsthe-postal-delivery-building-now-the-acc/|title=History|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> \n\n[[File:Toronto Postal Delivery Building Postcard.jpg|thumb|left|Toronto Postal Delivery Building c.1950s]]\nUpon completion in 1941 the building would be temporarily handed over to Department of National Defence for wartime storage purposes, and be finally turned over to Canada Post in 1946. Required modifications were made to the building to return it back to its postal delivery purposes as a result of alterations done by the Department of National Defence.  After the refurbishment work was completed in 1948, the building now possessed the capability and equipment for proper mail sorting and other mailing processing functions. Though it was designed as a mail sorting warehouse it was also the home of Postal Station \"A\" which served mostly institutional & commercial clients.  The Ground floor was where the mail was dropped off by both railway carts and postal vans. Unsorted mail was moved by conveyor belts to the top floor and via gravity fed mail chutes sorted by size & destination.  Eventually the sorted mail would end up back on the ground floor where it would be sent out for delivery<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://torontoplaques.com/Pages/Toronto_Postal_Delivery_Building.html|title=History|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2020</ref>. The building would be used as a postal sorting centre up until the 1990s.\n\n====Postal Building Sculptures==== \nThe structures most notable feature (which has been retained) are the exterior 13-part series of limestone [[bas relief]] carvings by [[Louis Temporale]] Sr. [[Order of Canada|CM]] which depicts the history of transportation and communication in Canada. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tayloronhistory.com/2013/02/12/torontos-architectural-gemsthe-postal-delivery-building-now-the-acc/|title=History|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>.  Carved in 1938-39 begins with scenes showing human speech, a runner carrying a message, aboriginals communicating by smoke signal, a group of voyageurs, a schooner & a Royal Mail steamship crossing the ocean from England, the CN train used during the 1939 Royal Tour, the mythical flying boat named 'Canopus' and northern travel by dog sled<ref>{{cite book |last=Filey |first=Mike |author-link= |date=1992 |title=Toronto Sketches: The Way We Were |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=NNUAuL5S7gUC&pg=PA82 |location= |publisher=Dundurn Press |page=82 |isbn=}}</ref>. The sculptors son Louis Temporale jr. helped with restoration efforts in 1998 and in 2016 was still critical of the lack of protection of the artwork by stadium ownership for over 20 years. The nearby elevated Gardiner Expressway results in salt spray which is speeding up the deterioration of the limestone<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/mlse-acc-art-temporale-heritage-1.3395714|title=History|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>. \n\n====1990s Transition to Stadium====\nThe the late 1980s, the building & antiquated sorting equipment was in need of major renovations & expensive upgrades. In a cost cutting move (part of larger overall service changes & cuts made to the Crown Corporation under the [[Brian Mulroney]] Conservatives), Canada Post decided to close the facility and move operations to an alternate more modern c.1970s letter processing faculty on nearby Eastern Avenue. A structure with easy access to highways was designed specificity for transport truck delivery of mail. By 1989, all of the old building's work was transferred here.<ref name=\":0\" />. The 1980s real estate boom saw the building site become surrounded by skyscrapers, hotels, convention centres, SkyDome stadium & condo towers.  In the early 1990s, real estate developers [[Bramalea (company)|Bramalea Ltd]] and [[Trizec Properties|Trizec]] arranged to purchase the building from Canada Post, and redevelop the site into a {{convert|230,000|m2|sqft|adj=on}} office, retail and residential space. Financial and development details of the purchase imposed various conditions prior to development, including rezoning by the city, remediation of soil contamination by Canada Post.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bramalea's Moves Shake Taxpayers|first=Stevie|last=Cameron|date=November 15, 1992|publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>\n\nDue to financial difficulties & an ongoing recession, the building's ownership was returned to Canada Post in 1993 and remained abandoned. The Toronto Raptors purchased the unused building from Canada Post the following year.<ref name=\"rapnba\">{{cite web| url=http://www.nba.com/raptors/history/raptors_history.html/| title=Laying the Groundwork for the NBA in Toronto| website=nba.com| accessdate=October 14, 2017}}</ref>\n[[File:Postal terminal now Air Canada Centre.jpg|thumb|left|The arena retains the eastern & southern walls of the original postal structure built, through a process of [[facadism]].]]\nConstruction of the arena was started by the Toronto Raptors, under their initial ownership group headed by Canadian businessman [[John Bitove]]. In 1995, it had been decided that the NBA would expand into Canada. The Toronto Raptors were created and would need an indoor arena to play in. The Canada Post building was chosen to be the new home of the Raptors due to its downtown location and lot size. Other venues such as [[Exhibition Place]], North York Centre, Bay and Wellesley, and Bay and Dundas were also considered. The Canada Post building was purchased for {{CAD|60}} million.<ref name=\":0\" /> The Raptors initially played in SkyDome (now [[Rogers Centre]]) while the arena was constructed.<ref name=\"blogTo\">{{cite web|first=Chris|last=Bateman|title=That time the Raptors and the Maple Leafs moved to the ACC|url=http://www.blogto.com/city/2014/02/that_time_the_raptors_and_leafs_moved_to_the_acc/|website=blogTo|date=February 22, 2014|accessdate=December 4, 2017}}</ref> Groundbreaking took place in March 1997. The building retained the [[Art Deco]] Queenston limestone facade of the Toronto Postal Delivery Building along the east (along [[Bay Street]]) and south ([[Lake Shore Boulevard]]) walls of that structure, but the rest of the building (facing [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]]) was removed to make room for the arena, through the process of [[facadism]]. The original building is protected under the ''[[Ontario Heritage Act]]''.\n\n====Arena 'Wars'====\nWhen MLGL ([[Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment|Maple Leaf Gardens, Limited]] at the time the controlling company of the Toronto Maple Leafs) lost out on their desire to be the franchise owners of the Raptors, competition between the two organizations heated up centred around venues. MLGL declined to allow Maple Leaf Gardens to be used for the NBA upstart as a result pushing Bitove to secure rights to have the Raptors' opening seasons played at SkyDome until construction of the new stadium to be complete.\n\nThe 1930s-era Maple Leaf Gardens was showing its age; the Maple Leafs in desperate desire for a new facility began developing plans for building an all-new stadium with one of the key criteria for the new location that it must be within close walking proximity to both the subway system and GO Transit. During the early stages of construction, MLGL floated to the media plans for their own plans to build a competing single-use stadium on adjacent property just to the north of the stadium atop the train sheds at Union Station (similar to how [[Madison Square Garden]] was constructed) as the new home for the Toronto Maple Leafs.<ref name=ArenaWars>{{cite news|title=Leafs ready to Move (Page 2)|first=Craig|last=Daniels|date=April 16, 1997|publisher=[[The Toronto Sun]]}}</ref> The reaction from Raptors was nothing but anger. \"This proposed (Maple Leaf) location really disturbs us\" stated team president Richard Peddie, who went on to say that they would fight the Leafs \"every step of the way\" and he didn't understand why the Leafs have refused to join with the Raptors at their site; claiming that the Leafs want to \"build virtually on top of us\".<ref name=\"ArenaWars\" /> The major problem of the Union Station proposal is the land that the stadium would be built on was actually City of Toronto land that was leased out to CN Rail and CP Rail, which were in a major, long-standing dispute over rent payments (dating back to 1969). As a result, MLGL offered the city $156 Million (1997 CAD) in cash & assets to settle any and all outstanding claims and to buy the air rights above the Union Station train platforms.\n\nDuring this period John Bitove who disputed over the future of the arena who as a result of a [[shotgun clause]] was forced to sell his stake to Allan Slaight (who wanted a joint arena deal with MLGL) and now with majority ownership immediately went into talks with MLGL which eventually purchased both the Raptors and their partially completed arena, which subsequently resulted in major modifications to the original design, which was basketball-specific, to make the arena become more suitable for hockey. Originally planned to cost $217&nbsp;million, MLGL increased the budget to $265&nbsp;million after taking control.<ref name=cost>{{cite news|title=Upgrades added to cost|first=David|last=Shoalts|date=February 17, 1999|publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> The Raptors were twice fined a million dollars (which were donated to their charitable foundation) by the NBA for missing deadlines to begin construction of their new arena.<ref>{{cite news|title=Raptors' arena bites dust|last=Christe|first=James|date=May 16, 1997|publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>\n\n====Construction==== \nAfter the purchase of the Raptors and the Air Canada Centre the new owners entered into a design-build contract with PCL with the commitment to finish the stadium in 24-months by March 1st 1999<ref>https://canada.constructconnect.com/dcn/news/projects/2017/03/pcl-construction-reflects-on-building-the-air-canada-centre-1022273w</ref>.  The intergartion of the Maple Leafs into the new structure would result in a 25% increase in construction costs (over $25 million CAD in 1999)<ref>https://canada.constructconnect.com/dcn/news/projects/2017/03/pcl-construction-reflects-on-building-the-air-canada-centre-1022273w</ref>. \n\nThe completed structure included a 15-storey tower (reduced from a proposed 30-stories), four restaurants, and an underground parking lot. \n\n====Opening====\nIn 1998, a strange twist of scheduling conflicts had the Toronto Raptors playing their final regular-season game at [[Copps Coliseum]] in Hamilton, as the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] had first right of refusal for all SkyDome dates.  The Raptors had attempted to play the April 19 match at Maple Leaf Gardens, but were unsuccessful.<ref>{{cite news|title=Raptors Move Final Game to Hamilton|date=January 7, 1998|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|url=https://www.apnews.com/7027ff09054e45b3b7471205f12cb521}}</ref>\n[[File:Air Canada Centre in 1999.jpg|thumb|right|Air Canada Centre in July 1999, five months after the arena opened]]\n\nOn December 30th 1998, the building's construction was completed, 9 days ahead of schedule. Opening events took place early the next year and [[Steve Stavro]] (who was the majority shareholder of MLGL) was named CEO. The initial hockey game took place February 20, 1999 (Toronto Maple Leafs vs. [[Montreal Canadiens]]), the first basketball Game on February 21, 1999 (Toronto Raptors vs. [[Vancouver Grizzlies]]), and the opening concert on February 22, 1999 ([[The Tragically Hip]]).<ref name=\":0\" /> Features of the new building consist of a {{convert|65000|sqft|adj=on}} arena and a {{convert|165000|sqft|adj=on}} office tower. There is also an east\u2013west covered, climate controlled galleria and walkway onsite that contains restaurants, the ticket office, and other commercial units. The Galleria also connects Scotiabank Arena to popular locations in the downtown core such as Union Station, Bay Street and York Street. Scotiabank Arena is connected to the underground PATH network. The Galleria also doubles as a historical museum by displaying numerous artifacts from the old Canada Post building.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pcl.com/Projects-that-Inspire/Pages/Air-Canada-Centre.aspx|title=Air Canada Centre|work=PCL Constructors|access-date=November 15, 2018|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nIn its first ten years of operation, the new arena had an estimated economic benefit of $2.4&nbsp;billion. This boosted Toronto's economy and led to further construction in the downtown core. Many projects in the area were completed ahead of schedule as a result of a desire to increase the infrastructure of downtown Toronto, and also from private funding (approximately $13&nbsp;million) that was invested in seeing the economic growth of Toronto. These projects included the Bay West Teamway, Union Plaza, the Galleria (shopping centre), and Bremner Boulevard.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[Air Canada]] purchased [[naming rights]] to the arena for US$30&nbsp;million for 20 years.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/background/marketing/|work=CBC News|title=Branding for dollars|date=February 15, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Current History== \n[[File:PATH Escalators Construction Scotiabank Arena.jpg|thumb|right|Escalators for a new [[PATH (Toronto)|PATH]] system connection to the under-construction [[CIBC Square]] office complex being installed in the arena's lobby in 2019]]\nIn 2003, MLSE completed a $5-million upgrade of the arena, including a new LED signage system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapleleafs.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=459588|title=Air Canada Centre Renovations to Improve Ultimate Fan Experience|date=September 9, 2003|accessdate=January 6, 2014|publisher=[[Toronto Maple Leafs]]}}</ref>  During the summer of 2015, a $10-million upgrade of the arena was carried out, which included the installation of a new scoreboard four times larger than the previous one. The old scoreboard was later installed at [[Coca-Cola Coliseum|Ricoh Coliseum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/leafs/2015/07/24/acc-to-debut-new-scoreboard-this-year.html|title=Air Canada Centre to debut new scoreboard this year|first=Raju|last=Mudhar|date=July 24, 2015|accessdate=July 24, 2015|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref>\n\nIn the winter of 2003\u20132004, the [[Alcohol and Gaming Commission of Ontario]] imposed a seven-day penalty on the arena for \"permitting drunken patrons to be in the licensed patrons{{sic}}\" in the fall of 2002 at a Toronto Maple Leafs game and also a [[The Rolling Stones|Rolling Stones]] concert. As a result of these misdemeanours, there was no alcohol served at the arena from December 21 to 28 in 2003. The venue had multiple major events during this time frame, which included a Toronto Raptors\u2013[[Orlando Magic]] game on December 21, a Toronto Maple Leafs\u2013[[Florida Panthers]] game on December 23, and [[Disney on Ice]]: [[Toy Story 2]], which ran from December 25, 2003 to January 1, 2004.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/air-canada-centre-loses-liquor-licence-for-a-week-1.401537|title=Air Canada Centre loses liquor licence for a week {{!}} CBC Sports|work=CBC|access-date=November 15, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n[[File:DSC08942 - Legends Row (37049346192).jpg|thumb|In September 2014, a group of life-sized statues were installed at the southwest corner of the arena.]]\nOn September 6, 2014, a group of statues known as ''Legends Row'' was unveiled outside the arena at the southwest corner of the building.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/leafs/2014/09/06/maple_leaf_legends_row_unveils_first_three_honourees.html|title=Maple Leafs Legends Row starts with Ted Kennedy, Darryl Sittler, Johnny Bower|publisher=Torstar Corporation|accessdate=September 27, 2018|work=Toronto Star|date=September 7, 2014|last=Rubin|first=Josh}}</ref> The statues were situated in multiple waves from 2014 to 2016 and include [[Ted Kennedy (ice hockey)|Ted Kennedy]], [[Johnny Bower]], [[Darryl Sittler]], [[B\u00f6rje Salming|Borje Salming]], [[Syl Apps]], [[George Armstrong (ice hockey)|George Armstrong]], [[Mats Sundin]], [[Dave Keon]], [[Turk Broda]], and [[Tim Horton]]. In 2017, the final four statues were unveiled including [[Red Kelly]], [[Frank Mahovlich]], [[Charlie Conacher]], and [[Wendel Clark]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/maple-leafs-legends-row-adds-conacher-kelly-mahovlich-and-clark/c-286915412|title=Maple Leafs Legends Row 'is full' with four added|website=NHL.com|language=en-US|access-date=November 15, 2018}}</ref> ''Legends Row'' now features 14 life-sized statues of former Maple Leaf players alongside a {{convert|9|m|ft|adj=mid|-long|round=5}} granite players' bench.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://torontosun.com/2017/10/05/4-more-leafs-added-to-legends-row/wcm/53247716-67d7-445e-9f20-a91a51890592|title=Four more Maple Leafs added to Legends Row|work=Toronto Sun|publisher=Postmedia Network Inc.|date=October 5, 2017|last=Hornby|first=Lance|accessdate=September 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Renaming====\nThe Air Canada Centre was renamed Scotiabank Arena on July 1, 2018. The landmark 20-year sponsorship agreement between Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment and [[Scotiabank]] is worth about C$800&nbsp;million. This is believed to be the highest-priced annual building and team sponsorship in North American sports history.<ref name=\"MLSEScotiaBankArena\">{{cite news|title=HOME OF THE MAPLE LEAFS AND RAPTORS TO BECOME SCOTIABANK ARENA NEXT SUMMER|url=http://mlse.com/news/scotiabankarena/|publisher=[[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]]|date=August 29, 2017|accessdate=May 10, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"WestheadTSN\">{{cite news|last=Westhead|first=Rick|title=MLSE agrees to record arena rights deal with Scotiabank|url=https://www.tsn.ca/talent/mlse-agrees-to-record-arena-rights-deal-with-scotiabank-1.842133|website=[[The Sports Network|TSN]]|date=August 29, 2017|accessdate=May 10, 2018}}</ref> The arena is the third in Canada to bear naming rights to Scotiabank.\n\n==Maple Leaf Square==\n[[File:First period play gets a little rowdy.jpg|thumb|A popular gathering point during [[Toronto Maple Leafs|Maple Leafs]] and [[Toronto Raptors|Raptors]] playoff runs, the arena has a large video screen that overlooks the atrium of Maple Leaf Square.]]\n{{main|Maple Leaf Square}}\nIn late 2005, Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment announced that they would be renovating the western side of the Air Canada Centre during the 2008 off-season to connect it with the [[Maple Leaf Square]] development. Maple Leaf Square is jointly owned by MLSE, [[Cadillac Fairview]] and Lantera Developments. The $500&nbsp;million development includes two restaurants, Hotel Le Germain at Maple Leaf Square boutique hotel, extensive retail shopping, including a {{convert|840|m2|sqft|adj=on}} Leafs, [[Toronto Marlies|Marlies]], Raptors, and [[Toronto FC]] store, two 54-storey condominiums, a [[Longo's]] supermarket, and a public square. It opened in 2010. The two-year, $48&nbsp;million renovation of the ACC added a new atrium that includes a High-Definition broadcast studio for [[Leafs Nation Network]] (formerly Leafs TV), [[NBA TV Canada]] and [[GolTV (Canadian TV channel)|GolTV Canada]].\n\nThe outside wall of the atrium features a {{convert|9.1|by|15.2|m|ft|adj=on}} video screen overlooking the plaza, which often broadcasts games taking place inside the arena. During [[Stanley Cup playoffs|NHL]] and [[NBA playoffs|NBA playoff]] runs, the square attracts thousands of Leafs and Raptors fans, respectively, sometimes broadcasting away playoff matches featuring the Leafs and/or the Raptors as well.<ref>{{cite web|title=Air Canada Centre Re-Opens Bigger And Better After Summer Hiatus|url=http://www.nba.com/raptors/news/accexpansion_presser_091109.html|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|website=NBA.com/Raptors|date=September 11, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2014}}</ref> A section of the square is designated Ford Fan Zone at Maple Leaf Square, with naming rights given to the [[Ford Motor Company of Canada]]. During Raptors playoff runs, the square has acquired the nickname \"[[Jurassic Park (film)|Jurassic Park]]\" after the 1993 film adaptation that inspired the team's name. During the [[2019 NBA Playoffs]] and especially during the [[2019 NBA Finals]], other city squares across Canada also acquired the Jurassic Park nickname, such as in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/raptors-jurassic-park-spin-offs-ontario-1.5159009|publisher=CBC|title=Jurassic Park spin-offs popping up as Raptors fever sweeps Canada|author=Lucas Powers}}</ref>\n\n==Events==\n===Concerts===\n{{main|List of entertainment events at Scotiabank Arena}}\n\n===Political conventions===\nIn 2003, the governing [[Liberal Party of Canada]] held their [[2003 Liberal Party of Canada leadership election|leadership convention]] at the Air Canada Centre. [[Paul Martin]] was elected as the new leader of the party and thus also became [[Prime Minister of Canada|prime minister]], succeeding [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]].\n\n===Sports===\n<!--Please don't add WWE events per consensus-->\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | image1 = Raptors vs Bucks 2.jpg\n | width1 = 165\n | image2 = Buffalo Bandits at Toronto Rock.jpg\n | width2 = 155\n | image3 = Toronto AirCanadaCenter 01.jpg\n | width3 = 165\n |footer= Scotiabank Arena is a [[Multi-purpose stadium|multi-purpose arena]] that is able to host a number of sporting events, including basketball, box lacrosse, and ice hockey.\n}}\nThe first Maple Leafs home game took place on February 20, 1999, versus the Montreal Canadiens, won by the Leafs 3\u20132 on an [[overtime (ice hockey)|overtime]] goal by [[Steve Thomas (ice hockey)|Steve Thomas]]. Maple Leaf home games are generally sold out,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Williams|first1=Cheryl|title=Toronto Maple Leafs|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/toronto-maple-leafs/#h3_jump_10|website=The Canadian Encyclopedia|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> and there is a waitlist since the start of 2015 for Season Ticket Holders for upcoming seasons.<ref>{{cite web|title=Purchase Season Seats|url=http://mapleleafs.nhl.com/club/page.htm?id=73129|website=Toronto Maple Leafs|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> The first Raptors game took place the following night versus the then-[[Memphis Grizzlies|Vancouver Grizzlies]]. The Raptors won 102\u201387 in front of a sell-out crowd. The facility hosted the [[2000 National Hockey League All-Star Game|2000 NHL All-Star Game]], the championship game of the [[2004 World Cup of Hockey]], all games of the [[2016 World Cup of Hockey]] and the [[2016 NBA All-Star Game]], the first NBA All-Star Game held outside of the United States.\n\nThe Toronto Rock also moved to the Air Canada Centre from Maple Leaf Gardens for the [[2001 NLL season]]. The Rock's first game was a 17\u20137 win over the [[Ottawa Rebel]] on December 21, 2000.\n\nOn October 3, 2003, Air Canada Centre had a power outage during the third quarter of a Raptors pre-season game against the Athens-based club [[Panathinaikos B.C.|Panathinaikos]]. The game was called final, because the power was not restored in time and the Raptors already had a [[Mercy rule|30-point lead]].\n\nAir Canada Centre hosted the [[2015 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships]] for the first time, as well as hosted the final match of that tournament, in which Canada was crowned champion, defeating Russia. The ACC co-hosted that tournament with [[Bell Centre]] in Montreal, and both venues co-hosted the [[2017 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|2017 edition of the same event]], though the ACC did not host the medal rounds.\n[[File:Laura Wright performs during the Invictus Flag Raising (37021670620).jpg|thumb|Flag raising during the [[2017 Invictus Games]] closing ceremonies]]\nIn 2017, the Air Canada Centre hosted the opening and closing ceremonies for [[2017 Invictus Games|that year's Invictus Games]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.invictusgames2017.com/ceremonies/|title=Ceremonies|publisher=Invictus Games Toronto 2017|year=2016|accessdate=August 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn September 23, 2017, the ACC presented the opening ceremony as a live two-hour event spectacular. This ceremony was designed to welcome and honour the 550 competitors and their families who come from 17 different competing nations. The show featured hundreds of cast members, including honorary men and women from the [[Canadian Armed Forces]]. The cast showed a display of ceremony in multiple different productions and the raising of the flag. Other guests of the event included celebrities, world dignitaries, headline music stars and other special guests. They gathered to celebrate the service and stories of the members of the 2017 Invictus Games. Headline performers included [[Laura Wright (singer)|Laura Wright]], [[Alessia Cara]], [[The Tenors]], [[Sarah McLachlan]], and [[La Bottine Souriante]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe ACC hosted the Invictus Games Toronto 2017 Closing Ceremony on September 20, 2017. The event featured an arrangement of international headline music artists, coming together to celebrate and recognize the Invictus Games competitors. The closing ceremony featured headline musical guests [[Bachman & Turner]], [[Bryan Adams]], [[C\u0153ur de pirate|Coeur de Pirate]], [[Bruce Springsteen]], and [[Kelly Clarkson]]. This celebration also included words from world dignitaries as the Games are passed to the host nation of the [[2018 Invictus Games|Invictus Games 2018]], [[Sydney]], [[Australia]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe venue hosted its first championship series when the Raptors played the [[Golden State Warriors]] in Games 1, 2, and 5 of the [[2019 NBA Finals]]. The Raptors won the NBA championship, albeit in the Warriors' home arena of [[Oracle Arena]] in [[Oakland]] in Game 6.\n\nThe arena has also played host to five [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] (UFC) events.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmajunkie.com/news/2013/05/ufc-165-heads-to-air-canada-centre-in-toronto-on-sept-21|title=UFC 165 heads to Air Canada Centre in Toronto on Sept. 21|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Staff|date=May 14, 2013|accessdate=May 14, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"UFC206\">{{cite news|url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2016/8/19/12562718/ufc-releases-schedule-for-rest-of-2016-including-ufc-206-in-toronto|title=UFC releases schedule for rest of 2016 including UFC 206 in Toronto|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Marc Raimondi|date=August 19, 2016|accessdate=August 19, 2016}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Event\n! Date\n|-\n| [[UFC 140]]\n| Saturday, December 10, 2011\n|-\n| [[UFC 152]]\n| Saturday, September 22, 2012\n|-\n| [[UFC 165]]\n| Saturday, September 21, 2013\n|-\n| [[UFC 206]]\n|Saturday, December 10, 2016\n|-\n| [[UFC 231]]\n|Saturday, December 8, 2018\n|}\n<!--Please don't add WWE events per consensus-->\n\n===Video game competitions===\nOn August 27 and 28, 2016, Air Canada Centre hosted the [[2016 Summer North American League of Legends Championship Series|sixth season of the Summer North American Championship Series]] of ''[[League of Legends]]'' (LoL), marking the first [[League of Legends Championship Series|professional ''League of Legends'' competition]] in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lolesports.com/en_US/articles/na-summer-finals-coming-toronto|title=LoL Esports|website=www.lolesports.com}}</ref> ''League of Legends'' is a popular [[multiplayer online battle arena]] (MOBA) [[PC game|computer game]] by American video game developer [[Riot Games]]; ''League of Legends'' competitions are among the most viewed among professional video game competitions worldwide. During the final round, [[Team SoloMid]] (TSM) defeated [[Cloud9]] (C9) three matches to one in a best-of-five format. The Summer North American Championship Series serve as the qualifiers for the annual [[League of Legends World Championship]] for North American teams.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- Per [[WP:ELMINOFFICIAL]], choose one official website only -->\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.scotiabankarena.com/}}\n* [http://torontoplaques.com/Pages/Toronto_Postal_Delivery_Building.html Toronto's Historical Plaques; Toronto Postal Delivery Building]\n{{Portal bar|Sports|Ice hockey|Canada|Ontario}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list1=\n&nbsp;\n{{S-start-collapsible|header={{S-sta|et}}}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Home of the<br />[[Toronto Raptors]]\n | years = 1999\u2013present\n | before = [[Rogers Centre|SkyDome]]\n | after = current\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Home of the<br />[[Toronto Maple Leafs]]\n | years = 1999\u2013present\n | before = [[Maple Leaf Gardens]]\n | after = current\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Home of the<br />[[Toronto Rock]]\n | years = 2000\u2013present\n | before = [[Maple Leaf Gardens]]\n | after = current\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Home of the<br />[[Toronto Phantoms]]\n | years = 2001\u20132002\n | before = [[XL Center|Hartford Civic Center]]\n | after = last arena\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Host of the<br />[[National Hockey League All-Star Game|NHL All-Star Game]]\n | years = 2000\n | before = [[Amalie Arena|St. Pete Times Forum]]\n | after = [[Pepsi Center]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Host of the<br />[[NBA All-Star Game]]\n | years = 2016\n | before = [[Madison Square Garden]]\n | after = [[Smoothie King Center]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Host of<br />[[Unforgiven (2006)|Unforgiven]]\n | years = 2006\n | before = [[Chesapeake Energy Arena|Ford Center]]\n | after = [[FedExForum]]\n}}\n{{End}}\n{{Toronto landmarks}}\n{{Sport venues in Toronto}}\n{{NHL Arenas}}\n{{NBA Arenas}}\n{{NLL Arenas}}\n{{Toronto Maple Leafs}}\n{{Toronto Raptors}}\n{{Toronto Phantoms}}\n{{Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment}}\n{{Canada Cup World Cup of Hockey Finals venues}}\n}}<!-- end of infoboxes -->\n\n[[Category:Indoor ice hockey venues in Canada]]\n[[Category:Indoor lacrosse venues in Canada]]\n[[Category:Basketball venues in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Music venues in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Music venues completed in 1999]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1999]]\n[[Category:Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]]\n[[Category:Toronto Maple Leafs]]\n[[Category:Toronto Raptors venues]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Toronto]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League venues]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association venues]]\n[[Category:PATH (Toronto)]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey venues in Toronto]]\n[[Category:City of Toronto Heritage Properties]]\n[[Category:1999 establishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Scotiabank]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the indoor sporting arena in Toronto|the arena in Calgary|Scotiabank Saddledome|the arena in Halifax, Nova Scotia|Scotiabank Centre|the arena in Ottawa formerly known as Scotiabank Place|Canadian Tire Centre}}\n{{Redirect|Air Canada Centre|the headquarters of Air Canada in Montreal|Air Canada#Headquarters}}\n{{short description|Indoor arena in Toronto, Ontario, Canada}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox venue\n| stadium_name = Scotiabank Arena\n| nickname = The Hanger<br  />The ACC\n| logo_image = [[File:Scotiabank Arena logo.svg|250px]]\n| image = [[File:Scotiabank Arena - 2018 (cropped).jpg|250px]]\n| caption = Exterior view of the arena in 2018\n| address = 40 [[Bay Street]]\n| location = [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|43|38|36|N|79|22|45|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|display=it}}\n| pushpin_map = Canada Toronto#Canada Ontario#Canada\n| pushpin_relief = yes\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in Toronto##Location in Ontario##Location in Canada\n| publictransit = {{rint|toronto|rail}} [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]]<br />{{rint|toronto|subway|1}} [[Union station (TTC)|Union subway station]]<br />{{rint|gotransit|bus}} [[Union Station Bus Terminal|GO Bus Terminal]]\n| broke_ground = March 12, 1997\n| opened = February 19, 1999\n| Acreage = {{convert|61780.5|m2|sqft|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4306707/air-canada-centre-gets-new-name/|title=Air Canada Centre sign removed on eve of facility becoming Scotiabank Arena|work=Global News|accessdate=September 27, 2018|publisher=Corus Entertainment Inc.|date=June 30, 2018}}</ref>\n| owner = [[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]]\n| operator = \n| former_names = Air Canada Centre<!-- This article uses Canadian English. \"Centre\" is the correct spelling in this case. --> {{small|(1999\u20132018)}}\n| construction_cost = {{CAD|265&nbsp;million}}<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.theaircanadacentre.com/corporate/CompanyFacts.asp|title=Company Facts|accessdate=August 29, 2017|publisher=Air Canada Centre}}</ref><ref name=cost/><br />(${{formatprice|{{Inflation|CA|265000000|1999}}}} in {{Inflation-year|CA}} dollars{{inflation-fn|CA}})\n| architect = Brisbin Brook Beynon Architects (Architect of Record)<br />[[Populous (company)|HOK Sport]]<br />(Consulting Architects)<ref>{{cite web |title=Clubhouse Confidential: When a Bunch of Alpha Males Get Together Daily in a Confined Space, Lots of Things\u2014Good and Bad\u2014Can Happen|first=Michael|last=Faber|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1024724/3/index.htm|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=January 14, 2002|accessdate=January 16, 2013}}</ref>\n| project_manager = Clarendon Projects Ltd.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clarendonprojects.com/aircanadacentre.html|title=Clarendon Projects \u2013 Air Canada Centre|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402151414/http://www.clarendonprojects.com/aircanadacentre.html|archivedate=April 2, 2012}}</ref>\n| structural engineer = [[Halcrow Group|Yolles Partnership Inc.]]<ref>[http://www.halcrow.com/Our-projects/Project-details/Air-Canada-Centre-Canada/ Halcrow Yolles \u2013 Air Canada Centre] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111026034118/http://halcrow.com/Our-projects/Project-details/Air-Canada-Centre-Canada/ |date=October 26, 2011 }}</ref>\n| services engineer = The Mitchell Partnership, Inc.<ref>[http://www.tmptoronto.com/document_library/Air%20Canada%20Centre.pdf The Mitchell Partnership \u2013 Air Canada Centre] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517115741/http://www.tmptoronto.com/document_library/Air%20Canada%20Centre.pdf |date=May 17, 2014 }}</ref>\n| general_contractor = [[PCL Construction|PCL Constructors Western, Inc.]]\n| tenants = [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] ([[National Hockey League|NHL]]) (1999\u2013present)<br />[[Toronto Raptors]] ([[National Basketball Association|NBA]]) (1999\u2013present)<br />[[Toronto Rock]] ([[National Lacrosse League|NLL]]) (2001\u2013present)<br />[[Toronto Phantoms]] ([[Arena Football League|AFL]]) (2001\u20132002)<br />[[Toronto Marlies]] ([[American Hockey League|AHL]]) (2010\u2013present, occasional home games)\n| seating_capacity = [[Basketball]]: 19,800 (20,511 with standing room)<br />[[Ice hockey|Hockey]]: 18,800 (20,270 with standing room)<br />[[Lacrosse]]: 18,800<br />[[Concert]]s: 19,800<br />[[Theatre]]: 5,200<ref>{{cite web|title=About|url=https://www.aircanadacentre.com/venue-information/about|publisher=Air Canada Centre|accessdate=May 10, 2018}}</ref>\n| parking = 2 underground levels for 212 vehicles<ref>https://canada.constructconnect.com/dcn/news/projects/2017/03/pcl-construction-reflects-on-building-the-air-canada-centre-1022273w</ref>\n| website = [https://www.scotiabankarena.com/ scotiabankarena.com]\n}}\n\n'''Scotiabank Arena''', formerly '''Air Canada Centre<!-- This article uses Canadian English. \"Centre\" is the correct spelling in this case. -->''', is a multi-purpose [[arena]] located on [[Bay Street]] in the [[South Core, Toronto|South Core]] district of [[Downtown Toronto|Downtown]] [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada. It is the home of the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL), the [[Toronto Raptors]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) and the [[Toronto Rock]] of the [[National Lacrosse League]] (NLL). In addition, the minor league [[Toronto Marlies]] of the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) and the [[Raptors 905]] of the [[NBA G League]] play occasional games at the arena. The arena was previously home to the [[Toronto Phantoms]] of the [[Arena Football League]] (AFL) during their brief existence.\n\nThe arena  is {{convert|61780.5|m2|sqft}} in size. It is owned and operated by [[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment|Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment Ltd.]] (MLSE), the same group that owns the Leafs and the Raptors, as well as their respective development teams. In 2018, Scotiabank Arena was the 13th busiest arena in the world and the busiest in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pollstar.com/Chart/2019/01/2018YearEndWorldwideTicketSalesTop200ArenaVenues_705.pdf|title=2018 YEAR END Worldwide Ticket Sales TOP 200 ARENA VENUES|publisher=[[Pollstar]]|date=2018|accessdate=June 22, 2019}}</ref> It is also the most photographed location in Canada on [[Instagram]] according to [[BuzzFeed]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/leafs/2018/07/01/scotiabank-arena-now-officially-the-home-of-maple-leafs-and-raptors.html|title=Scotiabank Arena now officially the home of Maple Leafs and Raptors - The Star|publisher=Toronto Star}}</ref> Scotiabank Arena is connected to [[Union Station (Toronto)|Toronto Union]] railway station, [[Union station (TTC)|subway station]] and [[Union Station Bus Terminal|bus terminal]] via the [[PATH (Toronto)|PATH]].\n\nScotiabank Arena has, from its initial design to completion, revolutionized many concepts included in new arenas and stadiums built since then.{{according to whom|date=October 2019}} These features include luxury suites accessible on the ground floor, splitting the main scoreboard into several sections, rotating all sponsor signage in the bowl at once (to allow dominant messaging or \"neutralization\" for events that disallow commercial advertising), and multiple restaurants in and out of the main arena bowl view.\n\nScotiabank Arena also hosts other events, such as concerts, political conventions and [[Esports|video game competitions]].\n\n==History==\n===Site History===\n[[File:Toronto in 1858.jpg|left|thumb|A map showing downtown Toronto in 1858]]The stadium is located on land that was once part of Toronto's inner harbour.  Infill of the inner harbour began in the 1850's and accelerated with the arrival of the railroad resulting in the current day shape of downtown <ref>https://www.cgenarchive.org/toronto-lakeshores.html</ref>.  By 1858 the site was located between two warfs (Rees & Tinnings Warf). As land was expanded southward, it remained under Government control as possible locations of various Union Station expansions.  The majority of the land was still part of the lake up until the early 1900's. By 1925 The northern parcel of the property was turned into of Bayside Park, which had been part of an early proposal that was to have seen the lands south of the rail corridor transformed into an extensive lakeside park that followed today's Esplande. The remaining land was most likely under the control of Central Harbor Terminals<ref>https://maps.library.utoronto.ca/dvhmp/maps.html</ref>.\n\nIn the 1930s the property became the proposed home to [[Canada Post]]'s Toronto Postal Delivery Building.  In the 1920's a postal handling facility already existed in the east wing of the city's then New Union Station (Downtown Toronto's 3rd major train station)<ref>{{cite book |last=Filey |first=Mike |author-link= |date=1992 |title=A Toronto Album 2: More Glimpses of the City That Was|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=K0tIsZ_TAIoC&pg=PA43 |location=Toronto |publisher=Dundurn Press |page=43 |isbn=}}</ref>. But it quickly reached capacity by the 1930s due to major population growth of Toronto and its surrounding region.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotiabankarena.com/venue-information/about/history|title=History {{!}} Scotiabank Arena|last=Arena|first=Scotiabank|website=www.scotiabankarena.com|language=en|access-date=November 15, 2018}}</ref>. In 1937 the Postmaster General appealed to the Minister of Public Works to approve a new replacement facility at the corner of Bay & Fleet Street (now Lake Shore Boulevard). Approval was granted by the federal Department of Public Works in part to stimulate the depression impacted construction industry<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://torontoplaques.com/Pages/Toronto_Postal_Delivery_Building.html|title=History|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2020</ref>. Design and construction of the warehouse built with steel & concrete would begin in 1938. Designed by [[Charles B. Dolphin]] it's a building that incorporates a combination of [[Art Deco]] and [[Art Moderne]] architectural style. The original building would be built for around $2,000,000 (CAD)<ref>{{cite book |last=Filey |first=Mike |author-link= |date=1992 |title=Toronto Sketches: The Way We Were |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=NNUAuL5S7gUC&pg=PA82 |location=Toronto |publisher=Dundurn Press |page=82 |isbn=}}</ref> [$ 35 million 2020],  The building was strategically located south of Union Station and was connected directly to the train platforms via an underground tunnel. Trains would be able to directly unload mail and move it directly to the mail sorting centre.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tayloronhistory.com/2013/02/12/torontos-architectural-gemsthe-postal-delivery-building-now-the-acc/|title=History|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> \n\n[[File:Toronto Postal Delivery Building Postcard.jpg|thumb|left|Toronto Postal Delivery Building c.1950s]]\nUpon completion in 1941 the building would be temporarily handed over to Department of National Defence for wartime storage purposes, and be finally turned over to Canada Post in 1946. Required modifications were made to the building to return it back to its postal delivery purposes as a result of alterations done by the Department of National Defence.  After the refurbishment work was completed in 1948, the building now possessed the capability and equipment for proper mail sorting and other mailing processing functions. Though it was designed as a mail sorting warehouse it was also the home of Postal Station \"A\" which served mostly institutional & commercial clients.  The Ground floor was where the mail was dropped off by both railway carts and postal vans. Unsorted mail was moved by conveyor belts to the top floor and via gravity fed mail chutes sorted by size & destination.  Eventually the sorted mail would end up back on the ground floor where it would be sent out for delivery<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://torontoplaques.com/Pages/Toronto_Postal_Delivery_Building.html|title=History|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2020</ref>. The building would be used as a postal sorting centre up until the 1990s.\n\n====Postal Building Sculptures==== \nThe structures most notable feature (which has been retained) are the exterior 13-part series of limestone [[bas relief]] carvings by [[Louis Temporale]] Sr. [[Order of Canada|CM]] which depicts the history of transportation and communication in Canada. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tayloronhistory.com/2013/02/12/torontos-architectural-gemsthe-postal-delivery-building-now-the-acc/|title=History|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>.  Carved in 1938-39 begins with scenes showing human speech, a runner carrying a message, aboriginals communicating by smoke signal, a group of voyageurs, a schooner & a Royal Mail steamship crossing the ocean from England, the CN train used during the 1939 Royal Tour, the mythical flying boat named 'Canopus' and northern travel by dog sled<ref>{{cite book |last=Filey |first=Mike |author-link= |date=1992 |title=Toronto Sketches: The Way We Were |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=NNUAuL5S7gUC&pg=PA82 |location= |publisher=Dundurn Press |page=82 |isbn=}}</ref>. The sculptors son Louis Temporale jr. helped with restoration efforts in 1998 and in 2016 was still critical of the lack of protection of the artwork by stadium ownership for over 20 years. The nearby elevated Gardiner Expressway results in salt spray which is speeding up the deterioration of the limestone<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/mlse-acc-art-temporale-heritage-1.3395714|title=History|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>. \n\n====1990s Transition to Stadium====\nThe the late 1980s, the building & antiquated sorting equipment was in need of major renovations & expensive upgrades. In a cost cutting move (part of larger overall service changes & cuts made to the Crown Corporation under the [[Brian Mulroney]] Conservatives), Canada Post decided to close the facility and move operations to an alternate more modern c.1970s letter processing faculty on nearby Eastern Avenue. A structure with easy access to highways was designed specificity for transport truck delivery of mail. By 1989, all of the old building's work was transferred here.<ref name=\":0\" />. The 1980s real estate boom saw the building site become surrounded by skyscrapers, hotels, convention centres, SkyDome stadium & condo towers.  In the early 1990s, real estate developers [[Bramalea (company)|Bramalea Ltd]] and [[Trizec Properties|Trizec]] arranged to purchase the building from Canada Post, and redevelop the site into a {{convert|230,000|m2|sqft|adj=on}} office, retail and residential space. Financial and development details of the purchase imposed various conditions prior to development, including rezoning by the city, remediation of soil contamination by Canada Post.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bramalea's Moves Shake Taxpayers|first=Stevie|last=Cameron|date=November 15, 1992|publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>\n\nDue to financial difficulties, the building's ownership was returned to Canada Post in 1993 and remained abandoned. The Toronto Raptors purchased the unused building from Canada Post the following year.<ref name=\"rapnba\">{{cite web| url=http://www.nba.com/raptors/history/raptors_history.html/| title=Laying the Groundwork for the NBA in Toronto| website=nba.com| accessdate=October 14, 2017}}</ref>\n[[File:Postal terminal now Air Canada Centre.jpg|thumb|left|The arena retains the eastern & southern walls of the original postal structure built, through a process of [[facadism]].]]\nConstruction of the arena was started by the Toronto Raptors, under their initial ownership group headed by Canadian businessman [[John Bitove]]. In 1995, it had been decided that the NBA would expand into Canada. The Toronto Raptors were created and would need an indoor arena to play in. The Canada Post building was chosen to be the new home of the Raptors due to its downtown location and lot size. Other venues such as [[Exhibition Place]], North York Centre, Bay and Wellesley, and Bay and Dundas were also considered. The Canada Post building was purchased for {{CAD|60}} million.<ref name=\":0\" /> The Raptors initially played in SkyDome (now [[Rogers Centre]]) while the arena was constructed.<ref name=\"blogTo\">{{cite web|first=Chris|last=Bateman|title=That time the Raptors and the Maple Leafs moved to the ACC|url=http://www.blogto.com/city/2014/02/that_time_the_raptors_and_leafs_moved_to_the_acc/|website=blogTo|date=February 22, 2014|accessdate=December 4, 2017}}</ref> Groundbreaking took place in March 1997. The building retained the [[Art Deco]] Queenston limestone facade of the Toronto Postal Delivery Building along the east (along [[Bay Street]]) and south ([[Lake Shore Boulevard]]) walls of that structure, but the rest of the building (facing [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]]) was removed to make room for the arena, through the process of [[facadism]]. The original building is protected under the ''[[Ontario Heritage Act]]''.\n\n====Arena 'Wars'====\nWhen MLGL ([[Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment|Maple Leaf Gardens, Limited]] at the time the controlling company of the Toronto Maple Leafs) lost out on their desire to be the franchise owners of the Raptors, competition between the two organizations heated up centred around venues. MLGL declined to allow Maple Leaf Gardens to be used for the NBA upstart as a result pushing Bitove to secure rights to have the Raptors' opening seasons played at SkyDome until construction of the new stadium to be complete.\n\nThe 1930s-era Maple Leaf Gardens was showing its age; the Maple Leafs in desperate desire for a new facility began developing plans for building an all-new stadium with one of the key criteria for the new location that it must be within close walking proximity to both the subway system and GO Transit. During the early stages of construction, MLGL floated to the media plans for their own plans to build a competing single-use stadium on adjacent property just to the north of the stadium atop the train sheds at Union Station (similar to how [[Madison Square Garden]] was constructed) as the new home for the Toronto Maple Leafs.<ref name=ArenaWars>{{cite news|title=Leafs ready to Move (Page 2)|first=Craig|last=Daniels|date=April 16, 1997|publisher=[[The Toronto Sun]]}}</ref> The reaction from Raptors was nothing but anger. \"This proposed (Maple Leaf) location really disturbs us\" stated team president Richard Peddie, who went on to say that they would fight the Leafs \"every step of the way\" and he didn't understand why the Leafs have refused to join with the Raptors at their site; claiming that the Leafs want to \"build virtually on top of us\".<ref name=\"ArenaWars\" /> The major problem of the Union Station proposal is the land that the stadium would be built on was actually City of Toronto land that was leased out to CN Rail and CP Rail, which were in a major, long-standing dispute over rent payments (dating back to 1969). As a result, MLGL offered the city $156 Million (1997 CAD) in cash & assets to settle any and all outstanding claims and to buy the air rights above the Union Station train platforms.\n\nDuring this period John Bitove who disputed over the future of the arena who as a result of a [[shotgun clause]] was forced to sell his stake to Allan Slaight (who wanted a joint arena deal with MLGL) and now with majority ownership immediately went into talks with MLGL which eventually purchased both the Raptors and their partially completed arena, which subsequently resulted in major modifications to the original design, which was basketball-specific, to make the arena become more suitable for hockey. Originally planned to cost $217&nbsp;million, MLGL increased the budget to $265&nbsp;million after taking control.<ref name=cost>{{cite news|title=Upgrades added to cost|first=David|last=Shoalts|date=February 17, 1999|publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> The Raptors were twice fined a million dollars (which were donated to their charitable foundation) by the NBA for missing deadlines to begin construction of their new arena.<ref>{{cite news|title=Raptors' arena bites dust|last=Christe|first=James|date=May 16, 1997|publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>\n\n====Construction==== \nAfter the purchase of the Raptors and the Air Canada Centre the new owners entered into a design-build contract with PCL with the commitment to finish the stadium in 24-months by March 1st 1999<ref>https://canada.constructconnect.com/dcn/news/projects/2017/03/pcl-construction-reflects-on-building-the-air-canada-centre-1022273w</ref>.  The intergartion of the Maple Leafs into the new structure would result in a 25% increase in construction costs (over $25 million CAD in 1999)<ref>https://canada.constructconnect.com/dcn/news/projects/2017/03/pcl-construction-reflects-on-building-the-air-canada-centre-1022273w</ref>. \n\nThe completed structure included a 15-storey tower (reduced from a proposed 30-stories), four restaurants, and an underground parking lot. \n\n====Opening====\nIn 1998, a strange twist of scheduling conflicts had the Toronto Raptors playing their final regular-season game at [[Copps Coliseum]] in Hamilton, as the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] had first right of refusal for all SkyDome dates.  The Raptors had attempted to play the April 19 match at Maple Leaf Gardens, but were unsuccessful.<ref>{{cite news|title=Raptors Move Final Game to Hamilton|date=January 7, 1998|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|url=https://www.apnews.com/7027ff09054e45b3b7471205f12cb521}}</ref>\n[[File:Air Canada Centre in 1999.jpg|thumb|right|Air Canada Centre in July 1999, five months after the arena opened]]\n\nOn December 30th 1998, the building's construction was completed, 9 days ahead of schedule. Opening events took place early the next year and [[Steve Stavro]] (who was the majority shareholder of MLGL) was named CEO. The initial hockey game took place February 20, 1999 (Toronto Maple Leafs vs. [[Montreal Canadiens]]), the first basketball Game on February 21, 1999 (Toronto Raptors vs. [[Vancouver Grizzlies]]), and the opening concert on February 22, 1999 ([[The Tragically Hip]]).<ref name=\":0\" /> Features of the new building consist of a {{convert|65000|sqft|adj=on}} arena and a {{convert|165000|sqft|adj=on}} office tower. There is also an east\u2013west covered, climate controlled galleria and walkway onsite that contains restaurants, the ticket office, and other commercial units. The Galleria also connects Scotiabank Arena to popular locations in the downtown core such as Union Station, Bay Street and York Street. Scotiabank Arena is connected to the underground PATH network. The Galleria also doubles as a historical museum by displaying numerous artifacts from the old Canada Post building.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pcl.com/Projects-that-Inspire/Pages/Air-Canada-Centre.aspx|title=Air Canada Centre|work=PCL Constructors|access-date=November 15, 2018|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nIn its first ten years of operation, the new arena had an estimated economic benefit of $2.4&nbsp;billion. This boosted Toronto's economy and led to further construction in the downtown core. Many projects in the area were completed ahead of schedule as a result of a desire to increase the infrastructure of downtown Toronto, and also from private funding (approximately $13&nbsp;million) that was invested in seeing the economic growth of Toronto. These projects included the Bay West Teamway, Union Plaza, the Galleria (shopping centre), and Bremner Boulevard.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[Air Canada]] purchased [[naming rights]] to the arena for US$30&nbsp;million for 20 years.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/background/marketing/|work=CBC News|title=Branding for dollars|date=February 15, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Current History== \n[[File:PATH Escalators Construction Scotiabank Arena.jpg|thumb|right|Escalators for a new [[PATH (Toronto)|PATH]] system connection to the under-construction [[CIBC Square]] office complex being installed in the arena's lobby in 2019]]\nIn 2003, MLSE completed a $5-million upgrade of the arena, including a new LED signage system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapleleafs.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=459588|title=Air Canada Centre Renovations to Improve Ultimate Fan Experience|date=September 9, 2003|accessdate=January 6, 2014|publisher=[[Toronto Maple Leafs]]}}</ref>  During the summer of 2015, a $10-million upgrade of the arena was carried out, which included the installation of a new scoreboard four times larger than the previous one. The old scoreboard was later installed at [[Coca-Cola Coliseum|Ricoh Coliseum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/leafs/2015/07/24/acc-to-debut-new-scoreboard-this-year.html|title=Air Canada Centre to debut new scoreboard this year|first=Raju|last=Mudhar|date=July 24, 2015|accessdate=July 24, 2015|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref>\n\nIn the winter of 2003\u20132004, the [[Alcohol and Gaming Commission of Ontario]] imposed a seven-day penalty on the arena for \"permitting drunken patrons to be in the licensed patrons{{sic}}\" in the fall of 2002 at a Toronto Maple Leafs game and also a [[The Rolling Stones|Rolling Stones]] concert. As a result of these misdemeanours, there was no alcohol served at the arena from December 21 to 28 in 2003. The venue had multiple major events during this time frame, which included a Toronto Raptors\u2013[[Orlando Magic]] game on December 21, a Toronto Maple Leafs\u2013[[Florida Panthers]] game on December 23, and [[Disney on Ice]]: [[Toy Story 2]], which ran from December 25, 2003 to January 1, 2004.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/air-canada-centre-loses-liquor-licence-for-a-week-1.401537|title=Air Canada Centre loses liquor licence for a week {{!}} CBC Sports|work=CBC|access-date=November 15, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n[[File:DSC08942 - Legends Row (37049346192).jpg|thumb|In September 2014, a group of life-sized statues were installed at the southwest corner of the arena.]]\nOn September 6, 2014, a group of statues known as ''Legends Row'' was unveiled outside the arena at the southwest corner of the building.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/leafs/2014/09/06/maple_leaf_legends_row_unveils_first_three_honourees.html|title=Maple Leafs Legends Row starts with Ted Kennedy, Darryl Sittler, Johnny Bower|publisher=Torstar Corporation|accessdate=September 27, 2018|work=Toronto Star|date=September 7, 2014|last=Rubin|first=Josh}}</ref> The statues were situated in multiple waves from 2014 to 2016 and include [[Ted Kennedy (ice hockey)|Ted Kennedy]], [[Johnny Bower]], [[Darryl Sittler]], [[B\u00f6rje Salming|Borje Salming]], [[Syl Apps]], [[George Armstrong (ice hockey)|George Armstrong]], [[Mats Sundin]], [[Dave Keon]], [[Turk Broda]], and [[Tim Horton]]. In 2017, the final four statues were unveiled including [[Red Kelly]], [[Frank Mahovlich]], [[Charlie Conacher]], and [[Wendel Clark]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/maple-leafs-legends-row-adds-conacher-kelly-mahovlich-and-clark/c-286915412|title=Maple Leafs Legends Row 'is full' with four added|website=NHL.com|language=en-US|access-date=November 15, 2018}}</ref> ''Legends Row'' now features 14 life-sized statues of former Maple Leaf players alongside a {{convert|9|m|ft|adj=mid|-long|round=5}} granite players' bench.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://torontosun.com/2017/10/05/4-more-leafs-added-to-legends-row/wcm/53247716-67d7-445e-9f20-a91a51890592|title=Four more Maple Leafs added to Legends Row|work=Toronto Sun|publisher=Postmedia Network Inc.|date=October 5, 2017|last=Hornby|first=Lance|accessdate=September 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Renaming====\nThe Air Canada Centre was renamed Scotiabank Arena on July 1, 2018. The landmark 20-year sponsorship agreement between Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment and [[Scotiabank]] is worth about C$800&nbsp;million. This is believed to be the highest-priced annual building and team sponsorship in North American sports history.<ref name=\"MLSEScotiaBankArena\">{{cite news|title=HOME OF THE MAPLE LEAFS AND RAPTORS TO BECOME SCOTIABANK ARENA NEXT SUMMER|url=http://mlse.com/news/scotiabankarena/|publisher=[[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]]|date=August 29, 2017|accessdate=May 10, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"WestheadTSN\">{{cite news|last=Westhead|first=Rick|title=MLSE agrees to record arena rights deal with Scotiabank|url=https://www.tsn.ca/talent/mlse-agrees-to-record-arena-rights-deal-with-scotiabank-1.842133|website=[[The Sports Network|TSN]]|date=August 29, 2017|accessdate=May 10, 2018}}</ref> The arena is the third in Canada to bear naming rights to Scotiabank.\n\n==Maple Leaf Square==\n[[File:First period play gets a little rowdy.jpg|thumb|A popular gathering point during [[Toronto Maple Leafs|Maple Leafs]] and [[Toronto Raptors|Raptors]] playoff runs, the arena has a large video screen that overlooks the atrium of Maple Leaf Square.]]\n{{main|Maple Leaf Square}}\nIn late 2005, Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment announced that they would be renovating the western side of the Air Canada Centre during the 2008 off-season to connect it with the [[Maple Leaf Square]] development. Maple Leaf Square is jointly owned by MLSE, [[Cadillac Fairview]] and Lantera Developments. The $500&nbsp;million development includes two restaurants, Hotel Le Germain at Maple Leaf Square boutique hotel, extensive retail shopping, including a {{convert|840|m2|sqft|adj=on}} Leafs, [[Toronto Marlies|Marlies]], Raptors, and [[Toronto FC]] store, two 54-storey condominiums, a [[Longo's]] supermarket, and a public square. It opened in 2010. The two-year, $48&nbsp;million renovation of the ACC added a new atrium that includes a High-Definition broadcast studio for [[Leafs Nation Network]] (formerly Leafs TV), [[NBA TV Canada]] and [[GolTV (Canadian TV channel)|GolTV Canada]].\n\nThe outside wall of the atrium features a {{convert|9.1|by|15.2|m|ft|adj=on}} video screen overlooking the plaza, which often broadcasts games taking place inside the arena. During [[Stanley Cup playoffs|NHL]] and [[NBA playoffs|NBA playoff]] runs, the square attracts thousands of Leafs and Raptors fans, respectively, sometimes broadcasting away playoff matches featuring the Leafs and/or the Raptors as well.<ref>{{cite web|title=Air Canada Centre Re-Opens Bigger And Better After Summer Hiatus|url=http://www.nba.com/raptors/news/accexpansion_presser_091109.html|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|website=NBA.com/Raptors|date=September 11, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2014}}</ref> A section of the square is designated Ford Fan Zone at Maple Leaf Square, with naming rights given to the [[Ford Motor Company of Canada]]. During Raptors playoff runs, the square has acquired the nickname \"[[Jurassic Park (film)|Jurassic Park]]\" after the 1993 film adaptation that inspired the team's name. During the [[2019 NBA Playoffs]] and especially during the [[2019 NBA Finals]], other city squares across Canada also acquired the Jurassic Park nickname, such as in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/raptors-jurassic-park-spin-offs-ontario-1.5159009|publisher=CBC|title=Jurassic Park spin-offs popping up as Raptors fever sweeps Canada|author=Lucas Powers}}</ref>\n\n==Events==\n===Concerts===\n{{main|List of entertainment events at Scotiabank Arena}}\n\n===Political conventions===\nIn 2003, the governing [[Liberal Party of Canada]] held their [[2003 Liberal Party of Canada leadership election|leadership convention]] at the Air Canada Centre. [[Paul Martin]] was elected as the new leader of the party and thus also became [[Prime Minister of Canada|prime minister]], succeeding [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]].\n\n===Sports===\n<!--Please don't add WWE events per consensus-->\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | image1 = Raptors vs Bucks 2.jpg\n | width1 = 165\n | image2 = Buffalo Bandits at Toronto Rock.jpg\n | width2 = 155\n | image3 = Toronto AirCanadaCenter 01.jpg\n | width3 = 165\n |footer= Scotiabank Arena is a [[Multi-purpose stadium|multi-purpose arena]] that is able to host a number of sporting events, including basketball, box lacrosse, and ice hockey.\n}}\nThe first Maple Leafs home game took place on February 20, 1999, versus the Montreal Canadiens, won by the Leafs 3\u20132 on an [[overtime (ice hockey)|overtime]] goal by [[Steve Thomas (ice hockey)|Steve Thomas]]. Maple Leaf home games are generally sold out,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Williams|first1=Cheryl|title=Toronto Maple Leafs|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/toronto-maple-leafs/#h3_jump_10|website=The Canadian Encyclopedia|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> and there is a waitlist since the start of 2015 for Season Ticket Holders for upcoming seasons.<ref>{{cite web|title=Purchase Season Seats|url=http://mapleleafs.nhl.com/club/page.htm?id=73129|website=Toronto Maple Leafs|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> The first Raptors game took place the following night versus the then-[[Memphis Grizzlies|Vancouver Grizzlies]]. The Raptors won 102\u201387 in front of a sell-out crowd. The facility hosted the [[2000 National Hockey League All-Star Game|2000 NHL All-Star Game]], the championship game of the [[2004 World Cup of Hockey]], all games of the [[2016 World Cup of Hockey]] and the [[2016 NBA All-Star Game]], the first NBA All-Star Game held outside of the United States.\n\nThe Toronto Rock also moved to the Air Canada Centre from Maple Leaf Gardens for the [[2001 NLL season]]. The Rock's first game was a 17\u20137 win over the [[Ottawa Rebel]] on December 21, 2000.\n\nOn October 3, 2003, Air Canada Centre had a power outage during the third quarter of a Raptors pre-season game against the Athens-based club [[Panathinaikos B.C.|Panathinaikos]]. The game was called final, because the power was not restored in time and the Raptors already had a [[Mercy rule|30-point lead]].\n\nAir Canada Centre hosted the [[2015 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships]] for the first time, as well as hosted the final match of that tournament, in which Canada was crowned champion, defeating Russia. The ACC co-hosted that tournament with [[Bell Centre]] in Montreal, and both venues co-hosted the [[2017 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|2017 edition of the same event]], though the ACC did not host the medal rounds.\n[[File:Laura Wright performs during the Invictus Flag Raising (37021670620).jpg|thumb|Flag raising during the [[2017 Invictus Games]] closing ceremonies]]\nIn 2017, the Air Canada Centre hosted the opening and closing ceremonies for [[2017 Invictus Games|that year's Invictus Games]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.invictusgames2017.com/ceremonies/|title=Ceremonies|publisher=Invictus Games Toronto 2017|year=2016|accessdate=August 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn September 23, 2017, the ACC presented the opening ceremony as a live two-hour event spectacular. This ceremony was designed to welcome and honour the 550 competitors and their families who come from 17 different competing nations. The show featured hundreds of cast members, including honorary men and women from the [[Canadian Armed Forces]]. The cast showed a display of ceremony in multiple different productions and the raising of the flag. Other guests of the event included celebrities, world dignitaries, headline music stars and other special guests. They gathered to celebrate the service and stories of the members of the 2017 Invictus Games. Headline performers included [[Laura Wright (singer)|Laura Wright]], [[Alessia Cara]], [[The Tenors]], [[Sarah McLachlan]], and [[La Bottine Souriante]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe ACC hosted the Invictus Games Toronto 2017 Closing Ceremony on September 20, 2017. The event featured an arrangement of international headline music artists, coming together to celebrate and recognize the Invictus Games competitors. The closing ceremony featured headline musical guests [[Bachman & Turner]], [[Bryan Adams]], [[C\u0153ur de pirate|Coeur de Pirate]], [[Bruce Springsteen]], and [[Kelly Clarkson]]. This celebration also included words from world dignitaries as the Games are passed to the host nation of the [[2018 Invictus Games|Invictus Games 2018]], [[Sydney]], [[Australia]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe venue hosted its first championship series when the Raptors played the [[Golden State Warriors]] in Games 1, 2, and 5 of the [[2019 NBA Finals]]. The Raptors won the NBA championship, albeit in the Warriors' home arena of [[Oracle Arena]] in [[Oakland]] in Game 6.\n\nThe arena has also played host to five [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] (UFC) events.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmajunkie.com/news/2013/05/ufc-165-heads-to-air-canada-centre-in-toronto-on-sept-21|title=UFC 165 heads to Air Canada Centre in Toronto on Sept. 21|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Staff|date=May 14, 2013|accessdate=May 14, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"UFC206\">{{cite news|url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2016/8/19/12562718/ufc-releases-schedule-for-rest-of-2016-including-ufc-206-in-toronto|title=UFC releases schedule for rest of 2016 including UFC 206 in Toronto|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Marc Raimondi|date=August 19, 2016|accessdate=August 19, 2016}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Event\n! Date\n|-\n| [[UFC 140]]\n| Saturday, December 10, 2011\n|-\n| [[UFC 152]]\n| Saturday, September 22, 2012\n|-\n| [[UFC 165]]\n| Saturday, September 21, 2013\n|-\n| [[UFC 206]]\n|Saturday, December 10, 2016\n|-\n| [[UFC 231]]\n|Saturday, December 8, 2018\n|}\n<!--Please don't add WWE events per consensus-->\n\n===Video game competitions===\nOn August 27 and 28, 2016, Air Canada Centre hosted the [[2016 Summer North American League of Legends Championship Series|sixth season of the Summer North American Championship Series]] of ''[[League of Legends]]'' (LoL), marking the first [[League of Legends Championship Series|professional ''League of Legends'' competition]] in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lolesports.com/en_US/articles/na-summer-finals-coming-toronto|title=LoL Esports|website=www.lolesports.com}}</ref> ''League of Legends'' is a popular [[multiplayer online battle arena]] (MOBA) [[PC game|computer game]] by American video game developer [[Riot Games]]; ''League of Legends'' competitions are among the most viewed among professional video game competitions worldwide. During the final round, [[Team SoloMid]] (TSM) defeated [[Cloud9]] (C9) three matches to one in a best-of-five format. The Summer North American Championship Series serve as the qualifiers for the annual [[League of Legends World Championship]] for North American teams.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- Per [[WP:ELMINOFFICIAL]], choose one official website only -->\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.scotiabankarena.com/}}\n* [http://torontoplaques.com/Pages/Toronto_Postal_Delivery_Building.html Toronto's Historical Plaques; Toronto Postal Delivery Building]\n{{Portal bar|Sports|Ice hockey|Canada|Ontario}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list1=\n&nbsp;\n{{S-start-collapsible|header={{S-sta|et}}}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Home of the<br />[[Toronto Raptors]]\n | years = 1999\u2013present\n | before = [[Rogers Centre|SkyDome]]\n | after = current\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Home of the<br />[[Toronto Maple Leafs]]\n | years = 1999\u2013present\n | before = [[Maple Leaf Gardens]]\n | after = current\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Home of the<br />[[Toronto Rock]]\n | years = 2000\u2013present\n | before = [[Maple Leaf Gardens]]\n | after = current\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Home of the<br />[[Toronto Phantoms]]\n | years = 2001\u20132002\n | before = [[XL Center|Hartford Civic Center]]\n | after = last arena\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Host of the<br />[[National Hockey League All-Star Game|NHL All-Star Game]]\n | years = 2000\n | before = [[Amalie Arena|St. Pete Times Forum]]\n | after = [[Pepsi Center]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Host of the<br />[[NBA All-Star Game]]\n | years = 2016\n | before = [[Madison Square Garden]]\n | after = [[Smoothie King Center]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n